Cask Days 2012. Latest Kensington offering of higher IBU product. Bubbly head on orange body. Some orange citrus taste, not bad a beer, maybe better on tap. Medium mouthfeel, a bit of astringency. Decent drinkability for hopheads. 70 ibu. Some caramel, but the hops are the show.

Ruddy amber with a thin light tan head. Modest lacing. Nice aroma of oak, vinegar and cherries. These continue to the taste where they're joined by some sherry notes and a touch of earthy hops. Very dry, clean finish. Medium bodied with strong carbonation. Better than most American examples, but it still falls quite a bit short of the Belgian classics, IMO.
This beer was aged in virgin oak barrels 10-14 months and leads with a nice acidity. Great mouthfeel brings out tart fruit flavors.
Hoppy red ale. Bright and citrusy. Floral hops. Sticky and resiny. Grapefruit and pine. Perfect carbonation level. A nice bitterness. Well done.

On tap at the brewpub. Served in a standard shaker glass. Appearance: Color is a deep amber red. Moderate amount of bubbles and a solid finger of off white head that slowly settles into a thin creamy layer. Leaves a lot of good lacing. Smell: A ripe, juicy, and spicy hop forward aroma with good hints of citrus fruit, pine, and caramel malt. Citrus hops with good hints of grapefruit, orange peel, lemon, and tangerine. Big hints of spicy and dank pine resin. Floral and earthy hop hints with some grass. Solid malt backing with hints of caramel, biscuit, yeast, and slight roast. A very solid aroma. Taste: Like the smell indicates, a juicy, spicy, and oily hop forward taste with good notes of pine, citrus, and caramel. Solid citrus hop presence with notes of grapefruit, orange peel, lemon, and tangerine. Earthy and floral hops with a big taste of spicy pine resin and grassy hops. Background malt presence with notes of caramel, toffee, biscuit, toast, and yeast. A very good ripe taste. Mouthfeel: Full bodied with a moderate amount of carbonation. Juicy, spicy, and very oily with a drying finish. Overall: A very good hopped up Red ale. Big mix of earthy and citrus hop notes.
Terrific juicy, hoppy IPA from RT. Nice!!

I've been a fan of Rising Tide for quite a while at this point, probably nearing on 5 years or so... jeez, where does time go? So, yeah, whenever I see a new release by them, I typically give it a shot without even thinking about it... they're very trustworthy and have an excellent taproom in Portland, ME to boot! This is an experimental hop series, something that's kinda all-the-rage these days. Playing with different hop profiles and lupulin flavors/aromas is fun for brewers and usually the end result is something I can at least appreciate and think about on a beer-judgment level. This one utilizes Mosaic, Simcoe and Azacca hops. The pour on this is somewhat hazy, and medium-yellow/gold in color. Very, very fine particulate floats suspended throughout the body, and the head here ends up really nice and compact after an initial huge showing. Lace is spectacular as well. Quite nice looking if you don't mind the hop haze. I, for one, do not, so this is a big win for me! Nose is interesting, for sure. Mango and papaya up front with some candied melon, pine sap and spruce. The pine mingling with the tropical elements is interesting as they kind of mesh together amorphously instead of being clearly delineated up front. I feel like, more often than not, the heady evergreen notes of Simcoe punch through the tropical and citrusy/melon character of Azacca/Mosaic. If you like Simcoe-forward notes in your IPA, this will work for you. Flavor is along the same line with some slightly juicier fruit notes toward the mid-palate. Fruit gum, papaya, pineapple and even apricot come across on the tongue alongside a crisp and easygoing malt backbone. Slightly prickly bitterness toward the finish with more pine and spruce from Simcoe. Slight grapefruit rind and light melon in the aftertaste. Maybe even a bit floral at times to my tastebuds. Feel is slick, oily and quite lean with a rather easily-drinkable stature. My cans don't have a listed ABV, but it's probably 5.9% like the other batches have been considering I doubt the grain bill really changes at all. At 5.9%, this is pretty much right in line with other 6%-ish IPAs in terms of body. Just enough to feel like more than a hoppy pale ale but less than an imperial. Alcohol is not really noticeable as bitterness and characterful hops wash it out. Nice stuff here, glad to check it out!

Bottled 2015 Opened the day of this review Very sweet like a good scottish brown ale. Except this is way more complex. Very little carbonation. Finish is dark chocolate and malt Wish I would have picked up 2 bottles

This beer will catch you by surprise. My first impression was that it a bit to casked and did not have traditional beer qualities but in hindsight, that is exactly wha makes this beer so unique. It has a very notable cask musk odor and an understated carbonation, almost seems flat but the carbonation is very fine and the small bubbles helps keep this smooth. If you like Rye Whiskey and you like beer, you'll find this a pleasant combination of both. Has an almost cocktail quality without the watered down addition of ice. Beware though, this beer is not for someone looking for a straight up beer. This is a nice night cap type beer. Drink one and you're feeling quite good. Drink two and you better have a designated driver.
Dark wheat style beer with no carbonation.

On tap @ The Taphouse, Townsville. Lovely bright apricot gold appearance. Fruity/grassy nose, very appealing. Pine and tropical fruits on the palate. If I didn't know better I'd say someone has tried to clone Ballast Point Sculpin; very similar although 8 bit is a tad more full bodied which tends to soften the hop character. Great IPA out of Australia

Fridged at Beer Cartel and tastes like it was brewed yesterday. Full of grassy and floral hops on the nose, and another adder to the New Wave of Aussie IPAs a la Riverside and Modus Operandi. Loads of lychee, mango, stone fruit, and less of the citrus/pine makes it a breeze to drink. Smooth mouthfeel, almost creamy. Top stuff. Freshness is the key!

Bottle pour at mrbubbler's tasting. Pours a hazy orange with a foamy bone head that settles to a partial film on top of the beer. Small streaks of lace form around the glass on the drink down. Smell is of malt, caramel, fruit, and slight smoke aromas. Taste is much the same with fruit and caramel flavors on the finish. There is a mild amount of earthy bitterness on the palate with each sip. This beer has a lower level of carbonation with a slightly crisp and medium bodied mouthfeel. Overall, this is a pretty good beer with a nice caramel and fruit aspect going on.

12 oz. bottle poured into a snifter. Appearance - Clear amber body. Wispy surface. Smell - Slightly fruity. A lot of caramel. A little estery. Clovey and some banana. Taste - More fruit. Drier caramel. Earthy hops in the back. Musty finish. Mouthfeel - Dry with just a hint of bitterness. No booze and medium low carbonation. Overall - Decent just not very interesting.

12 oz bottle poured into a Bruery tulip. Cryyy little sister! (Thou shall not falll) -ok, had to get that out there. A - Swirled half way through the pour, the bottle's sediment clouds the golden wheat colored beer considerably and capping it with plush white foam! S - Little Sister's got it where it counts at the most basic level; wheat, citrus, spice, and classic yeast aroma but, shift gears and dive into it's complexity! Heavy coriander seed and notes of cardamom, as well as sweet orange peel suggest spice and citrus are added, not just influenced by the yeast but esters of lemongrass and white pepper peek out from behind the relaxed floral hop notes. T - Forcefully spicy at first, Little Sister approaches being overdone but hits the breaks just in time. Coriander and cardamom flourish from the front to the back, through the whole ride, with bright orange peel citrus and flirtatious floral hop notes deviating from the spice path, nicely balancing it out. M - Effervescent and lighter bodied, Little Sister is spicy up front, dry on the finish but smooth from wheat the whole way through for a well-balanced and refreshing take on a wit! O - As one of two launch beers for Door County, Little Sister might be a pretty easy drinking witbier but, it's bold aroma and flavors make it anything but introductory. Heavy-handed but purposeful and distinctive, Door County Brewing Co. distances themselves from modest witbiers that feature reserved adjunct additions. And they do a damn good job at it.

Murky golden orange, soapy white foam on the surface, spotty dish bubble soap lacing around the edges of the glass. Poured the yeast and it just hangs in suspension in a wispy flame shape. Aroma is heavy on coriander, a little bit of floral soap. Taste has a hint of sweetness at first, becoming dry in the middle. Creamy wheaty feel, smooth and light to medium bodied. A slight medicinal taste, not sure what that's attributed to, maybe grains of paradise. Easily drinkable, bought a six pack and down to my last one. Overall pretty good first contract-brew effort from this new brewery, hopefully they get into more creative stuff in the future.

I got this beer from my dear beerbuddy Robert (Torino). Thanks Robert. Poured this one in my De Molen tasting glass. Nice golden yellow fluid. Got some heavy pouring to do to get some head. Very light carbonation, little lacing. Floral smell far away with some anice hints. Good mouthfeel. A decent drinkable beer but not too spectacular. The alcohol is pretty well hidden.

(Served in a teku) A- This beer pours a hazy dark orange body with a thick ring of bubbly beige and a very faint pfsst hint is all that was heard when I twisted the cap off. S- The woody caramel aroma has a slight sweet wort note to it with a sweet ester sugar note in the finish. The aroma is very light but also quite mysterious. T- The slightly dry caramel turns to a sweet candy hint. There is some wet wood oxidation taste and some slight tartness in the finish. A light citrus juice note comes through in the aftertaste. There is an alcohol taste that grows and cuts the sweetness quite a bit as it opens up. M- This beer has a medium-light mouthfeel with a full alcohol warmth and a fizz in the finish that gives a fullness texture without being fizzy. O- This has some characteristics of a miabock and hints of a light barleywine with a soft sweetness and a full alcohol. The flavor and aroma were both pretty soft and I just couldn’t get behind this beer. There were moments it was tasty and then it was more odd characters like the oxidation or the tartness or citrus that outweighed the tasty. Thanks to Thickfreakness for sending to me it was fun to try.

On tap at O'Brien's, San Diego. Pours a solid black color with a small tan head and some lacing. Light aroma with citrus and roasted malt. Tastes of grapefruit and very deep roasted malts (with some sweetness up-front). Almost full-bodied, smooth, and with mild carbonation. Tasty and nice to drink; not bad, but probably my least favorite black IPA that I've tried.

Hazy as advertised. Thin dissipating head. Pine and mango on the nose. Overripe mango and waves of bitter resin collide here and settle into a strong pithy afterglow. Palate buster for sure. Awesome Tree House offering.
Sweet heavens. Velvety mouthfeel. Fruity forward, herbaceous late. Everything I like about west coast meets east coast. Nailed it.

Drank the day I brought it home from the brewery out of a TEKU. The line at the brewery was stupid long. Look: As the name suggests, this beer has a full full haze, deep bright golden color and half a finger of fluffy white head. Aroma: Classic TH! Big creamsicle aroma along tons of candied citrus, passionfruit and pineapple. Taste: Aroma translates to the palate. A little more green on palate than the nose would suggest. Definitely a strong pithy bitterness as well balances the strong up front candied flavors. Finishes with a good amount of hop burn though, the only flaw in this beer. Mouthfeel: Super crushable for 8.2%. the strong bitter hop burn slices through that thick treehouse creaminess. Overall(style points): Another amazing IPA from Treehouse. Killer nose that's on par w/Julius but the strong bitter finish slots it behind Julius making this my second favorite beer from them. 99.25 points!
Flawless
Very nice DIPA.

16 oz. can Pours cloudy opaque amber gold with a dense creamy white foam head. Smells like orange citrus, grapefruit, mango, peach, pineapple, guava, papaya, passionfruit, berry, caramelized wheaty bready malts, mild spice, with dank floral resinous earthy herbal grassy pine. Tastes like orange citrus, grapefruit, mango, peach, pineapple, guava, papaya, passionfruit, berry, caramelized wheaty bready malts, mild spice, with dank floral resinous earthy herbal grassy pine. Feels medium-full bodied, creamy and smooth with moderate carbonation. Overall a really great juicy DIPA.
Tastes Like throw up with a bit of lime

Pours a thin head on a hazy dark straw body. The aroma is grain and mild dark fruit. The taste is mild apricot sweet with lemon bitterness, and some toast. Nice. The texture is soft and fizzy. Quite enjoyable.
I think the rating is probably influenced by the price. I thought this was a good beer but for the price it is too much and there are other great BA stouts out there for less.

Bottled at the tail end of 2017. Never given this high of a rating before. This beer was insane. The taste, look and smell notes are basically the same as what others have described. I will add that the batch I tried did not have a lot of maple syrup in the nose, and the maple sweetness was extremely faint, popping up mainly at the finish. The thing that got me with this beer was it’s body. Never had a barrel aged stout that was even close to being this smooth, especially at 12%ABV. The beer is definitely full bodied, but somehow it felt extremely light and fluffy, sort of like drinking a bourbon-maple-stout storm cloud. It was unbelievable. For such a flavorful beer there was no one taste that overpowered. I personally feel that this beer was worth every bit of hype it’s received. Would definitely wait in a very long line for it.

Bottle from Pioneer Supermarket on the UWS, NYC. Pours black with a finger of tan frothy head, smells like bourbon soaked chocolate cake, creamy sugary coffee, maple syrup, molasses, and hints of vanilla and licorice, taste is boozy burnt dark caramel crunch candy (similar to Ample Hill Creamery), sweet maple syrup, a hint of coffee and finishes with roasted coffee bitterness, this beer is nice and velvety. Not quite the RAINS OF AFRICA that I recall from when I first had this at EBF many years ago, but an excellent mocha maple syrup treat.

On draft in a tulip glass Black in color, thick tan head, good head retention. Aroma is nice - chocolate, mild coffee, a touch of bourbon and maple. Flavor is better, complex. A bit sweet. Nice thick full bodied mouthfeel.

25.4oz bottle. 2017 Vintage. Pours a viscous black color with an inch of dark brown head. Moderate amount of lacing. Lots of Bourbon and maple syrup in the nose. Coffee, chocolate syrup, roasted malts, espresso, earth, notes of leather and maybe a hint of vanilla as well. The taste isn’t as sweet as I expected. Bourbon taste is upfront but the maple syrup and sweetness from the chocolate are not over powering. Woody with cocoa and black coffee. Roasted malts, leather and earth towards the end. Woody, Bourbon finish with one last hint of maple syrup. Medium to heavy mouthfeel with low carbonation. Not quite as boozey tasting as I had expected but it does have a noticeable alcohol presence. It took me a while to get one of these but I’m glad I finally got to try it. Worth seeking out for sure.
Really, really good. But also really, really over-hyped and over-priced. Will not be picking this up again until I make a 6 figures a year.

750mL (2017) into a tulip. Pours a deep oily black with a thick, dense, sudsy mocha head. Inviting. Aroma is chocolatey and rich. Dark roasted malt, vanilla, smoky bourbon, sweet toasted coconut. Taste is likewise rich and delicious. Bittersweet chocolate, fig, coconut. Subtle undertones of maple and bourbon. No hint of alcohol. Mouthfeel is smooth and slick, full bodied. Just right. Overall an outstanding imperial stout that lives up to the hype.
Wow!!!! Buy it when you find it.
All the best parts of KBS really shine through, a tad bit sweet for my palate but excellent for the style. I would love to catch another one to try after some time in the cellar.

Stood in line for an hour at the Craft Beer Hop Stop on 12-5-2017 and picked up a 750ml bottle for $24.99. Bottled likely in November 2017 (no bottling date visible). Beer poured black as night with a very nice tan head that is leaving lacing behind. Nose is a awesome combination of coffee, cocoa, bourbon, and maple; it is very subtle yet wonderful! Taste is a masterful blend of coffee, chocolate, subtle maple, and a nice touch of bourbon. Initial sips were warming to let you know the bourbon was there, yet a beautiful compliment to the entire flavor profile. Mouthfeel is medium to full bodied, so velvety smooth across the palate with each sip. Overall this brew lives up to the hype. I honestly thought i would not like it a lot because i am not big on maple but i have to say i am totally impressed!
I frequently hear people complain about the lack of maple but in fairness it’s a maple bourbon barrel beer it doesn’t actually have maple added

Shared with friends around a fire. I know - heresy! But I had purchased it over the holidays and wanted to share with friends, and had forgotten about it for a few months. Perhaps I should have left it shelved for longer. Look - is very dark and thick looking pouring out into tasting cups. Smell is very sweet, yes on the border of cloying. Maple syrup, chocolate, coffee. I thought at that point "oh no, is this like those sickly sweet holiday stouts?" Taste is very very very sweet, I would counter and say on the wrong side of too sweet. Maple, chocolate, some hint of coffee (weak) and then hard to discern much else, but I suspect some vanilla was present to try and calm it down, but at the expense of more sweetness. Cloyingly sweet. Mouthfeel was fine and unoffensive, but it did feel like drinking watered down syrup. Overall, this disappointed me at the cost of $28 bottle and for a beer ranked #13 on this site. I admit I "am" some BMCer posting only my third review, and I have been swayed to the East Coast juice bomb IPAs for the last couple years, but I drink Guinness, Founders Porter, and other darks on occasion, and was expecting something more subtly balanced and much much less sweet. I may re-evaluate after exploring more stouts, but this was more like a dessert than a beer. I will say that it smelled delicious and made us all hungry for pancakes as we doused the fire with the remainder at end of night. Can't say we weren't warned, it did say "breakfast" right there on the label. Mea Culpa!

Pours a thick jet black with some chocolate colored foam. Smell is very sweet, but not cloying. The maple syrup really shines, backed by coffee and chocolate. Taste is massive and sweet, but again on the right side of too sweet. Maple syrup, bourbon, oak and vanilla assault your taste buds. More chocolate appear as it warms. Superb. Mouthfeel is perfect, thick and sticky with just the right amount of carbonation. Overall, this managed to live up to my hype. One of the best stouts I've ever had.

10oz draft pour from Whichcraft North in Austin,TX compared side by side with a draft KBS. The KBS was so good that I didn’t think I could identify any flaws with it until I took my first sip of CBS. Both beers are incredible but I would give the edge to the CBS. The additional sweetness from the maple helps to mask any remaining alcohol flavors that survived the chocolate and coffee infusion. There is no trace of its double digit ABV. The CBS is smooth, sweet, silky, deliciousness and a must try for any BA fan.
Vintage 2017

2017 release. Pours nearly full black, 2 finger dark tan head. Barrel smell with chocolate and faint coffee. Roasty. Not much maple. First sip carries coffee bitterness, powder cocoa and a bit of booze. Continues with faint sweetness from the syrup sugar. Bitterness fades and opens up some more semi sweet chocolate. Vanilla as it warms some with background sweetness throughout. Medium to big bodied, more carbonation than I was expecting. Full mouth coating and long finish. This definitely is more complex than KBS, but not as much as I expected. It is sweeter from the maple but it's much subdued by coffee and bakers chocolate bitterness. Body seems right for the ABV and the flavors hold back any real booziness.

Also thanks to thanks to ApostleBrewing as well as dcloeren for this one as I just had a Jester King beer that came from them as well, coincidence. Pours a decent fizzy almost 1 finger head, not bad for 10% abv, fades at a med pace with little lacing, hazy, slight suspended particulate, amber nectar orange color. Nose starts like candy, butterscotch toffee, slight peanut brittle, candy syrup, sweet malty, reddish malts, hint of clean booze, light fruity touch as well, not much else though. Taste starts with more candy, sweet slightly syrupy candy, light toffee and brittle, light apple fruit and candy apple flavor. Booze cuts in and let's you know with warming tingly booze but clean, some nutty caramel with the syrupy sweetness, rich buttery toffee comes out more on the back end. Finish is semi syrupy sticky with an anesthetizing booze feel, lingering nutty and buttery toffee, caramel, just a touch of earthy bitterness even slight creamy caramel and creamed honey. Mouth is med to fuller bodied, plenty of warming tingly booze, decent carb. Overall not bad, but nothing special. It's more like a big candy beer than anything, with the sticky sweetness, syrupy flavors, lots of toffee and brittle like flavors, pretty sweet as expected. Not much for the nice malty flavors though, esp aged soft malt characters I expect in a good old ale, but otherwise not too bad.

Bottle date on 7/12/12, if I read it correctly. Thanks to XicanoBeerRun for this one. Imported from Texas! This pours an amber-caramel color with a thin ring of foam. The hops have faded on this, leaving behind a boquet of caramel and malt notes. It’s stickly piney, with a sweet finish. The flavor is fairly mellow, with a rounded piney resin, and some light toasted coconut and almond notes. The body holds up, and it warms well enough to savor for a spell. Certainly the Divine Reserve series is a high point of the St. Arnold stable and this does not disappoint.

Served in a tulip from the hand-pump at Fountainhead. A - Quick-dissolving white foam settles to a thin collar and a few spots of lace. Lightly hazed pale yellow body. S - Initially I thought this smelled a lot like Gossamer - I was actually suspicious I had received the regular beer and not the special cask variant. However, letting it sit for a moment and warm up revealed tropical and earthy brettanomyces notes. Still, the main flavors were those of Gossamer's sweet malt backbone and potent dry-hopping. As it warms up there's an odd vegetal note, but it didn't seem much like prickly pear flesh - perhaps they used the whole fruit in the cask? T - Less overt hop character, with more sweet malts mid-palate as well as some lightly toasted grain. Finishes with a mildly funky and slightly medicinal brett note. Still, it's largely Gossamer in character. M - Smooth body, dry and mildly tannic fruit husk texture, lower cask-style carbonation, and some dryness in the finish. D - Easy to drink, but a fairly tepid attempt at a wild. The aggressive dry-hop character seems at odds with the wild elements of the beer, and the use of prickly pear cactus doesn't add much depth. The aroma actually reminded me a little of the infected can of AXL Pale Ale, but this tasted much better. Not a bad attempt by Half Acre - was the brett added directly to the cask? Perhaps it needs a bit more time to work (and for the hops to dissipate).

Served in a tulip at Fountainhead 4/2/2012. A: Gorgeous cask pour. Cloudy, bright golden color with a creamy/frothy bright white head on top that hangs around for quite a while. A few whisps of lace were left behind. S: Really kinda mild. A faint amount of hops mixed with a a faint amount of fruit. Became a little more assertive as it came up to temp. T: See above but the taste hits the ground running a little faster than the smell. Obviously Brett-y. M: Dry and spicy with a long lasting prickly finish. O: Pretty cool experiment. I got there at 4pm and actually got the first glass out of the firkin. A little too cold for my liking at first, but it didn't take very long to warm up. I'd love to see how this opens up and changes after a few hours of getting air at it.

April 28th 2011- Dark black with tan head. Very roasty on smell really didn't get any hops. Taste was much more hop forward, surprised me after smell. Overall the hoppiness and roasted characters collide a little too much but its still a good beer.

Served on-tap at the Blind Lady Ale House in San Diego, the beer was served in a Weisse vase, and this bad boy poured just like a stout. Jet black with a creamy chocolate colored head. Nose of heavy and wet hops with roasted malt. Super hoppy forward flavors, with peppery highlights and a bitter coffee backbone that lasts through the aftertaste. Robust and a little dry on the body, with a bitter finish. Very tasty!

Poured the blackest of black with one finger tan head. Smelt of slightly of fresh fruity hops. The taste was more roasty than what I expected. At first you get chocolate and roasted coffee then on the back you get the standard bitterness of an IPA. I would think it would be the other way around but it surly is not. A pretty good beer and I love the Cascadian style but this is probably on the lower end of the ones Ive tried. I would order it again however because it does have pretty good drink-ability.

This is a really nice Black IPA. This hops are undeniable in the aroma, it's got some little hints on burnt malts on the nose but not much. The color is very black. The head is very durable and thick for the entire course of time from start to finish. This is super citrusy up front and then smacks you with a very dry aftertaste that begs for another sip!
Liked this the first couple times I tried it but more recently have tired of this ultra juicy style.

In a mug at the brewery earlier tonite (not a fan of remote reviews but this is a new one so I made an exception). It's not really a strong ale, it's a black IPA but there is no category for that yet. The body is dark, more black than brown, thick and topped with a dark mocha colored head. About a finger's worth on it initially which dissipates to a sploty thin film which remains throughout. The smell is floral hops initially, a refreshing scent which perks up the nostrils, this is followed by a smoked malty sweet type tinge. The flavor profile is very interesting. First I got the smoked malt which gave me a bacon taste which was very intense. This was followed by an indistinguishable malty flavor, kind if a sweet molasses and dark biscuit combined into one. The hops come more towards the end and are very subtle but leave you with a great balanced aftertaste which I enjoyed. The mouthfeel is great, it's super malty so it's thick creamy and smooth as well as having a lightening sense from the hoppy aftertaste. For sure a sipping brew, I am not 100% on the abv but I would guess between the 8 and 9 percent range.

Had a pint while dining in for lunch today with Da Boss for $7.00. Beer poured hazy orange with a nice white head, definitely fits its billing. Nose is a nice citrus forward aroma, again hitting the style. Taste is a very nice combination of mango, grapefruit, and orange over an oat and barley malt base. Flavors really popped when sipping while enjoying the PAB burger. Mouthfeel was light to medium bodied and refreshing. Overall a nice representation of the NEIPA style although a bit pricey compared to their other offerings.

If I could describe this beer in a single sentence it would be... "Angel Piss in a Glass" Cold, Fresh and On Tap (keg), It has the perfect mouthfeel, the taste is slightly creamy and buttery...yeasty if you will and this bad boy packs a wallop!!! - Have a DD on hand if you're having more then 2. From Cask it's just a little sweeter and more lacing then a Victoria's Secret Catalog. This is one of the best things to come from Saint Arnold and is hands down one of the Top 5 Beers in all of Texas, Ever. The only thing SA has done on par with this is Bishop's Barrel No. 1 With all of that said, From a bottle....it's not nearly as good - All the Cream and Butter is gone from it.

12oz. bottle: Thanks, Kevin! This one pours a slightly hazy, lighter orangish-amber color. The aroma is a bit light for a 10%er, but good none the less. It’s a bit musty, with caramel and citrus notes. Also a bit of breadiness, spices and grassy notes. The taste is good. Body is more towards medium. Slightly bitter/sour taste. Some caramel and spice, as well as some faint fruits. No evidence of the alcohol. Very nice!

Little head. Color is a clear golden color. Very sweet and malty. Not a big taste profile. Just kind of boozy and malty. Caramel and some bready flavors. Maybe some citrus blended in. Full bodied and hot. Ends sticky. Overall, not really my type of old ale. It's kind of like a golden old ale. Odd. August 2015, this beer has rounded out a lot and isn't very hot. A malt bomb. Cereal grains. Aged well. Original score was 2.98

Served in a Rager Creek Tulip. Bottle dated 7/19/12 A: Ruddy orange color, that is pretty transparent. There is a thin white head that dissipates pretty quickly and doesn't lace very much. The color on this old ale is pretty different from any other I've had. S: It's you regular "old ale" scent, but a bit lighter. There is some malty sweetness, a little bit of hoppiness, but very little of the dark fruit type flavors you'd expect from your average old ale. T: It tastes a lot darker than it looks; the taste is almost your average old ale, but a bit lighter and a bit easier to drink. It is almost like an "old ale light," and brings a much more easily downable taste to the old ale canon. M: Thin, but not too thin, and smooth. The carbonation is pretty light, as you should expect from an old ale, and the bubbles are pretty mild. D: It goes down easy, amybe TOO easy for a 10% ABV beer. This one could get people in a lot of trouble. I see the DR#12 as a great way to get friends that are into milder beers introduced to the old ale genre of beer, and follow it up with something heavier like a Curmudgeon.

This is a historic Polish style-session beer made with oak smoked wheat. Too curiosity provoking to pass up! It poured a cloudy golden color with tightly laced foam atop. It had a light, barely perceptible smoke aroma to it. The light smokiness carries over to the flavor with a surprising tartness. It’s lemony and crisp with a wheated smoothness. Overall just an interesting, complexly flavored, curious beer. Surprisingly filling too—its effervescence which kept it light also unexpectedly inflated my belly! In some ways it reminds me of a Berliner weiss (a la Bell’s Oarsman) with a similar tart/lactic souring and light/crisp/refreshing flavor, not to mention the low ABV—and minus the smoke nuances, of course. Love it or hate it I imagine you’ll find this brew hard to forget.

May 21st, 2015 - I'm a sucker for a good Coconut Porter and the Space Oasis is a fine example of what I love. Dark and chill, it has a chalky, murky and soily aroma with a touch of sweet potato, but the aroma is more coconut milk than coconut. The flavor is also smooth and groovy, with a velvety coconut flavor.
0% Had on tap at Intergalactic tasting room

FOUNDERS CBS 4/6/18 a: Opaque black with an enormous five inch tan head which receded slowly to thick even surface foam and very dense lacing. s; Primarily roasty malt with some alcohol notes. t: Follows the nose with additional fairly prominent maple syrup flavor. Mainly sweet finish, high ABV quite well covered, with virtually no throat burn. m: Silky medium to full, great body and some carbonation tingle. o; Definitely a superlative brew loaded with pleasing flavor. However most of us can't afford to drink this too often at $15 per 12 ounce glass.

Christmas present from my brother that I finally decided to open... Poured into a small chalice: color is solid black with tan head of fine bubbles, presents at least 1 inch thick and lingers really, really well. Good spotty lacing on the glass sides. Smell is probably the most subdued aspect, even after 20-30 minutes of warming: aroma is sweet, light roast, hint of vanilla, bourbon, chocolate. Not much coffee, especially compared to base breakfast stout. Taste is somewhat ridiculous - hard to fathom that this is a 12% abv brew, but i think the maple/bourbon barrel aging really softens the booziness. Flavor is sweeter than expected, but not cloying, good base stout with vanilla, bourbon, chocolate interplaying well. No coffee like notes. Still a beer that is too easy drinking at 12%. Mouthfeel is where the booziness comes into play, but still not detracting from the beers character - you expect it. Feel starts sweet, with moderate/low carbonation, good presence. Overall a great brew that hides its strength and is too easy to drink.
Just a fantastic representation of an imperial stout. Love the sweetness of maple that is followed by the coffee and bourbon flavors. Amazing aromatics!

This beer certainly didn't live up to the hype for me. Its not a bad beer but it was overly sweet for me. Comparing it to Clown Shoes Snow On the Maple Tree, which is also aged in bourbon barrels that had maple syrup previously in them, I'd give the nod to Clown Shoes. The Clown Shoes beer is also nearly half the price of CBS. Taking cost out of the equation I'd still pick Clown Shoes simply because the sweetness was balanced with the bourbon notes. If you like sweet stouts this is a good option, if you want a bit more bourbon bite it won't hit the mark.

Celebrating my recently achieved Cicerone CBS and my 100th review on BeerAdvocate with CBS. From a 355ml bottle served chilled at 11 degrees Celsius into a TeKu glass. Best before date: 27.10.2018 – I've had the bottle since December 2017. My expectations are sky-high given the hype around this beer. I also may have had it on tap during its December release. Yup, most definitely did. Look: The beer pours an opaque black with 4.5cm of dense, mousse-like, brown head that dissipates into a partial film within 5+ minutes. Exceptional lacing with some of the most persistent head I've seen for a near 12% ABV beer. World-class. Smell: Medium-strong and balanced. Rich, deep, and layered. A staggering malt complexity with moderate vanilla and oak. Prominent notes of chocolate and coffee with a roasty character that surprises you every now and then. A well-hidden ethanol along with some licorice and caramel also come up. The dry nose is oaky-caramelly. For such a robust beer this shows an impressive amount of restraint. No apparent hop or yeast aroma. Taste: Follows the aroma with strong intensity, bitter balance, and assertive perceived bitterness. Big, bold, and absolutely delicious. The gorgeous flavour opens up with chocolate, vanilla, caramel, and some bourbon. Moving towards mid-palate, notes of coffee begin to take over along with a sweetness that I assume comes from the maple syrup. Additional notes include dried fruit (prunes) along with black licorice and the faintest of ethanol right before the aftertaste settles in. The long finish is strong and bitter with lingering notes of bourbon and chocolate. Simply delish. Feel: Full body with mild carbonation. Thick, velvety-smooth, and creamy with great chewy, viscosity. Smooth and balanced alcohol warming of moderate strength. No harshness or astringency even with the strong bitterness. Overall: Founders Canadian Breakfast Stout is a wonderful, world-class beer featuring excellent craftsmanship and low drinkability. Robust, full of layers, and most of all balanced. It's rare to find a barrel-aged beer with such grace. I do prefer the KBS for the lack of sweetness that the maple syrup brings in. A must-try in my books.

750ml bottle poured into a snifter. A: Inky black with a creamy brown head. Half a finger of retention. Spotty lacing. S: Freshly brewed pot of coffee, roasty, maple syrup, dark chocolate. Perhaps the faintest whiff of green hops. Slight oakiness, bourbon is barely perceptible if at all. Well put together. Smells like breakfast in a glass. T: Fresh coffee, maple syrup, dark and semi-sweet chocolates. Plenty of malt roast and caramel. The barrel itself is rather subdued, with a faint corny-sweet bourbon flavor and warmth and a dab of oak. It manifests itself a bit more into the finish, where just a bit of char is evident as well. M: Rich, thick, and sticky. Very chewy. Carbonation is apparent, but has a soft touch. Creamy and decadent. O: Damn good stuff. Strikes a perfect balance. Coffee, chocolate, and maple syrup meld perfectly with the base beer. The syrup flavors are 90% of what the barrel has to offer, though there are some bourbon and oak subtleties too. It is big and sticky in texture and feel, but as far as the alcohol goes only a faint warmth belies its strength. It's easy to see why this became such a coveted beer.

I had this beer a few days ago and I had to sit on it for a while before giving it's score. This beer is absolutely fantastic through and through. Wonderful dark dark brown with an almost chocolate colored head savory head. Powerfully strong aromas of chocolate, dark fruit, roasted Carmel, vanilla, sugar can, brown sugar, roasted nuts, roasted oats, chocolate, coffee, toffee and of course, lots and lots of maple. The flavor is pretty much the same. It tastes as powerful as it smells and it is truly delicious. The mouthfeel is very juicy and rewarding as well. But I have one problem with this beer. It seems to try and stand on its own, but in reality it is literally KBS with maple. I understand how well crafted and special this beer is, but without the maple it is KBS. With that being said, this beer's maple flavor isn't exactly a step forward in the breakfast stout from founders. I guess what I'm trying to say is that it doesn't have a quality that makes it better than KBS. I really love the maple flavor in this beer, but in reality, KBS is better because it doesn't have that maple flavor. Again, great beer that is extremely well crafted and delicious. But it's just KBS with the flavor of Maple. I understand the hype and I would try it if I were you, but the similarity is just too close and KBS did it before so it's the better beer to me.
Decent Stout with a nice hint of Maple. Hyped up hard.
One of my favorites. I feel the bourbon barrels that were holding maple syrup give this beer a nice smooth tasting experience that will leave you wanting to try it again and again

How high can one rate a local pilsener when they are so light? Compares well w. Prima, Pivo, Nooner, Carton ThisTown and the Crisp. Pleased to be 7th review of Lawn Dart. a) Totally Euro in look, aroma and taste. Straw gold with steep head that slacks to a ring of suds and dotty lace. s) Lots of grain, biscuit malt and continental hops. Smells like Luxembourg. t) Follows smell, more white crackers, with good lemony crisp astringency and euro style bitter hops. f) Thin, cleansing, bright, and crisp. Good first beer, aperitif. o) All Pilsners are too similar to tease a part. This one falls a bit for being a bit too yeasty, crackery, grainy, but otherwise refreshing.

Pours clear, gold in color with 3/4 inch head. taste is cereal, grass, and grain. Light bodied, slightly sweet, with moderate carbonation. Holy domestic pils. Makes for an excellent domestic version of the style. Would gladly drink a six of this.

Lawn Dart brewed by DuClaw Brewing Company, with an ABV of 5.40% This German Pilsner pours out a nice golden amber color with a nice white head. There is a nice amount of lacing to this brew, it sticks to the side of the glass well. The smell of this German Pilsner is rich with grains and malts. You also pick up on some nice hoo bitterness in the smell of this brew. This is a real nice inviting German Pilsner. Now for the taste, it is Bold but mild with flavors. You pick up a good amount grains and malts in the taste. There is also a nice mild hop bitterness in the taste this brew has the look and taste if most German Pilsners on the market, not saying that is a bad . The body of Lawn Dart, is a solid medium. There is nothing overpowering about this brew, it goes down nice and smooth. This is one fine drinking brew it would go. Ice with almost anything. The mouth feel of Lawn Dart is Bold, Clean, Smooth, and Refreshing. Overall I'm giving Lawn Dart a 4.50 out of 5. I would definitely look this brew up again. DuClaw Brewing Company, did a real nice job with this brew.
Pours a clear light yellow. Persistent lacing. Smell is pretty minimal. Faint sweet malt and grain. Taste is a quick flash of sweet malt followed by a fair amount of hop bitterness.

A thanks ton the prince of pilsners, woodychandler, for this beer. Poured from a 12 oz. can. Has a clear yellow color with a 1/2 inch head. Smell is of malts, a bit sweet. Taste is mild, malts, hints of grass and lemon. Feels medium/light bodied in the mouth and overall is a mediocre beer.

A: The beer is clear yellow in color and has a moderate amount of visible carbonation. It poured with a two finger high white head that died down, leaving a thin head covering the surface and lots of lacing down the sides of the glass. S: Light to moderate aromas of grassy hops are present in the nose. T: The taste follows the smell and has flavors of grassy hops and a moderate amount of associated bitterness along with underlying hints of bready and grainy malts. M: It feels medium-bodied, crisp and clean on the palate with a moderate amount of carbonation. O: This pilsener is more hoppier than it is malty. The hops provide a nice amount of "bite". Serving type: can

Lawn Dart | DuClaw Brewing Company. Poured from the can into a pint glass, the head here is two fingers thick, with lateral lacing, and a light gold body. Smells like hearty grains and full-bodied malts. I taste slightly toasty malts with a light hop zing. Clear and bright in all. Medium-light mouthfeel with mild carbonation. Lawn Dart | DuClaw Brewing Company gets a 4.25 rating.

Poured from a 12oz can into a high sided pilsner glass. Look is a clear yellow with a constant stream of bubbles to an inch head. Aroma is biscuit malt and continental hops. Taste is lighter than aroma, little astringency and some bitter hops.

Poured from a 500ml bottle into a pint glass. Purchased direct from the brewery. Pour a dark black colour with a creamy thick off white head. Smells like a cup of cold coffee, so strong coffee aromas. Tastes very dark and burnt, with malts and actual coffee coming through, finishing with a bitter hop tang. Overall a lovely beer, quite a surprise but yes very decent indeed.

Had on cask at Bierkraft in Brooklyn, NY tonight. A - This beer pours a very nice mahogany ruby color, and it has very small off-white head. The head left some specs of lacing on the glass. It also has a nice clarity to it. S - It smells of sweet caramel malts, hops, and cedar. There are also some notes of dark fruits present. T - I am getting some smooth caramel sweetness at first. Almost as soon as the sweetness hits, I got an assault of bitter hoppiness attacking my taste buds in a wonderful way. There are nice cedar notes here as well as some brown sugar. M - This has a very smooth and creamy feel to it. It has a medium body with medium-low carbonation. There is an extreme puckering hop bitterness here that I find wonderful. The bitterness lingers in the mouth for quite some time. D - The drinkability is good. I really like this beer. It is smooth, creamy, and it goes down easy. The flavor is great as well. Overall, this is a really good beer, and I'm glad I got the chance to try it, since I think its pretty limited. I recommend trying this is you ever come across it.

Darker gold, unusual for a "Blonde". Clear. Little head which leaves only a few spots for lace. There's a burnt wood element to the initial smell. Darker (than Blonde) malt aromas. Too much of a macro malt taste despite the "pilsner and Munich malt" description. Dry with a bit of an ashen flavor. The body and carbonation are appropriate for the style.
Incredible IPA, so sad that I was only able to get 5 cans. Tree house in a class all by itself

Good one here, didn't enjoy quite as much as Alter Ego and Green. The aroma here was interesting, had almost a banana aroma going on. Flavor is very fruity, hops are less pronounced. Feel is medium-full.

This beer is amazing. It pours very cloudy in a tulip glass. The aroma is peach and grapefruit. The taste is tart and fruity without being overly sweet. The mouthfeel is incredible. Treehouse simply makes the best IPAs in the United States. Everyone is a treasure.
Wow! Just got it in growler for first time.
This is amazing, the aroma is incredible. Honestly, the only knock I have is some excess bitterness probably due to this being two months old, otherwise this beer was outstanding.

oh wow, took a while for me to get my hands on this but it was well worth the wait, very smooth and virtually no alcohol prominence whatsoever, for a 8.2 very smooth and drinkable, a grapefruit IPA with orange showing slightly on finish, wish it could be a regular for me....great feel and carbonation, a smooth sipper that improved with it warming in glass

16oz can from the Brewery: This one pours a milky, darker straw yellow color. There was about a finger of a frothy off white head that leaves some lacing. Very nice nose. Orange, pineapple, peach, maybe some earthiness. The taste is excellent. A fairly good amount of bitterness. Orange, pineapple, a bit of resinous hops. Good malts in the background.

Pours hazy and looks like orange juice in the glass though tad more towards yellow than straight orange. The smell follows the look on this one. Orange up front along with peach notes. Going along with the balance the beer, the taste follows the nose as the nose follows the looks. Sweet up front with orange citrus predominating. The back end is very balanced and not that bitter at all. Notes of orange candy linger. The feel is medium thick. Overall this is an amazing beer; orangey and tasty!

Drank it out of the can. Smells awesome taste is smooth and fruity. would have liked slightly more bite. Maybe that is the magic for 8.2 % went down real easy. I would like to try this on draft. Outstanding I really want to try this again.

Look - Black and thick with a small mocha colored head, slight lacing Smell - Coffee, malt, raison/dried fruit Taste - Coffee with sweet caramel flavor and notes of chocolate and some raison/dried fruit flavor - well balanced Feel - Too much carbonation for my liking, takes away from the beer a little bit but still thick and full bodied Overall an exceptional imperial stout and I highly recommend drinking along side either a bourbon or a light irish style stout such as guiness or any stout that tastes like an iced coffee. This will enhance the flavors of this beer and make it superb as well as enhance the flavors of the bourbon. I paired with Vault's Coffee Stout and a couple average priced bourbons that ended up tasting amazing.

2011 side by side with 2017. 2011 may have faded a bit over the years, but still phenomenal taste, and great maple. 2017 looked great in the glass, and had a strong coffee flavor that pops over the maple. Very little bourbon character, but this beer is all around balanced and phenomenal.

2017 Release Pours a deep stout-brown with no light penetration. Soapy dark brown head settles into a ring and a dusting of fuzz. Good lacing. Right off the bat it's big sweet notes of barrel and coffee and chocolate. Vanilla and oak. Black coffee. Almost a cinnamon-spicy element that's probably more barrel, but gave a spice hint for a second. I'm not really getting any maple, but my sniffer is notoriously weak, so *shrug* Oh man... First thought: this is a damn good beer. Second thought: this is a damn sweet beer. Third thought: but this is a damn good beer! Sugar maple is the first thing that makes its presence known. I know I said I didn't smell it, but it is absolutely there in the taste and it is delicious. I love maple, though. As it warms, the maple moves from the big splash at the first impression to more of the build and a supportive role. OK. So sweet maple, like the crust that builds at the lip of your jug of maple syrup. That's what the first impressions are. In support of this sweet crust is a balance of acrid black coffee and rich hints of dark chocolate and char. The vanilla and oak of the barrel gets folded in as the grout between the sweet maple syrup and richness of the dark chocolate. Finish leans more heavily into the fudgy rich chocolate before lingering with a bitter dark chocolate finish. Body could stand to be a touch heftier, per my personal preference (I admit I'm a sucker for those stouts that are like used motor oil). Fine pinpricks of carbonation help usher the tongue along between the various notes listed above. I'm not surprised that it is 11.7% ABV per se, but it is very well folded in with the rest of the brew and does not taste 'hot' like many big big stouts like this can. This is a beer with an incredible reputation, and I'm glad to finally confirm it for myself. Much much love to @FlintB for sending this along for NBS BIF#007. This was one of the first beers that I listed after that I couldn't get locally, and here almost seven years later I'm finally getting to try it thanks to Brian's generosity. I think it's likely to stay as a permawant.

Pours a midnight black with thick khaki head slowly dissipating into heavy lacing up to the lip of the snifter.Nose is very mild roasty malt,espresso,mapely-bourbony oak sweetness. Taste is a bit more of all of that plus vanilla,cocoa and more maple sweetness.Very creamy and smooth ,could easily get carried away with this.First experience with this and it is outstanding. Pricey ,but probably worth it - hard to compare to anything else I've tasted so far.Highly recommended.Will definitely buy again when available.

750 ml bottle into a snifter. Had 12/9/17. Pours dark, opaque, with a one and a half inch foamy head of darker foam and soapy lacing. Aromas of lots o’ coffee, malt, chocolate, maple, light bourbon, vanilla, cocoa. Smells divine. The taste also starts with strong coffee, then malt, chocolate, vanilla, maple, some bourbon. Smooth, a solid full, well carbonated. Way more coffee than I expected, a little less bourbon, too. The chocolate also stands out, the maple is solid, and even if less than I thought, the bourbon sneaks up on you. Certainly a great beer.

The beer pours out a dark black color, with a thin mocha colored head-------------- the aromas are of fudge, maple, vanilla and lesser coffee-------------- the flavors are of liquid fudge, dark chocolate, bitter chocolate, maple and lesser vanilla and coffee, the beer has a medium mouthfeel with a smooth finish---------------- overall this beer was amazing so smooth for almost 12% I could not taste any alcohol, the beer had a wonderful pop of sweetness up front with some bitter chocolate mid pallet to keep everything in balance

I concur pretty much with the review of Bierman.... Finally opened up a balmer of this one after (3) months purchased - a recommendation from local brewpub. This is comparable to Weyerbacher Sunday Morning Stout; just , not as boozy (taste & in ABV @ 12.7%).

Was up in Waterbury VT on 24FEB18 with Alewife and stopped into Craft Beer Cellar. Spotted about 15 of this beer on the shelves, so I had to swoop in. The 750ml bottle set me back $24.95. Diving into it today, a sunny, cold, lazy winters day (18MAR18). Poured about half into a small snifter to start... It is an oily, dense, black brew, with a fine, creamy but thin beige head. Lacing is pretty decent, overall. The aroma is rich with dark choco, mocha, some maple and a hint of coffee. The feel is easily medium-plus, bordering on being full and chewy. And it is smooth and silky all the way across the tongue. Flavor has a lovely mix of various items... There's dark choco, but it's rather sweet and not bitter at all. Then some mocha and cocoa, plus subtle coffee notes. Sweet maple syrup action lingers lovingly on the palate, along with some bourbon lurking in the background. Being such a chocolaty malt bomb, the hopping is rather light and barely noticeable. This one is going down quite easily, and my innards can feel the warmth . Not sure I'd shell out that kind of coin again, but I'm glad I was able to get to try this one.... I think I picked a good one for my 2000th BA review... Prosit!! 4.53/5 rDev -2.8% look: 4.25 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4.75 | feel: 4.5 | overall: 4.5 2000

750 mL bottle poured into Teku glass. Drank side by side with KBS for comparison. Pours black with a thick 1 inch medium brown head Nose: phenomenal mix of coffee, maple, and bourbon. Noticeably sweeter than KBS, but also more complex with the added maple component. Overall great balance and depth. Taste: follows the nose. Equal parts maple, coffee, and bourbon. The maple really stands out in a direct comparison with KBS and the coffee in CBS is less prominent (not muted by any extent, there are just more competing elements). Again noticeably sweeter than KBS, but never becomes cloying. Mouthfeel is silky smooth and extraordinarily drinkable. Feels a bit more full-bodied than KBS.

Look - pretty much black with a lasting thick creamy tannish brown head Smell -maple syrup, chocolate, coffee and maybe a little caramel Taste - sweet caramel chocolate candy with some maple glaze and coffee Feel - full body creamy light carbonation and so smooth Overall - so damn yummy!

Deep black with maple syrup colored edges, nice brown initial head that fades to a ring, leaving trails of lace Vanilla, bourbon, and yes, maple in the nose. Vanilla, roasted malt, white sugar, maple syrup, bourbon. Delicious. Nice smooth mouthfeel. This was superb. I'm going to track down another one. And have it with pancakes.

Founders Brewing Co. "CBS Imperial Stout" $10.50/10.5 oz. on tap @ Union Tap House, Philadelphia, PA on 9 February 2018 Notes: Very dark brown-black body beneath a creamy head of brown. The head retention is very good and the lacing is even better. The aroma suggests chocolate, cocoa beans, toffee, oak, vanilla, Bourbon, coffee, and maple syrup. The taste follows, with stronger notes of maple syrup, caramel, Bourbon, vanilla, chocolate, a charred roastiness, and coffee beans. It's sweet and just moderately bitter but also balanced by a touch of alcohol and acidity. Medium-full in body and smooth and oily with a moderate, very fine-bubbled carbonation.

Black color with a modest brown head. Aromas start with the bourbon, though it is fairly subdued, at least in comparison with her sister KBS. There are clear maple aromas, but again not so strong. Mellow aromas of maple and red soft fruits. Plum, cocoa aromas are apparent, also coffee but again little less than KBS. Taste is a nice mix by sweet and bitter. The vanilla and maple provide a mellowness that balance out any original bitterness of the KBS, so the beer is more balanced and less rough. The body is full, there's a distinct alcohol warmness. The texture is a bit creamy, more so than KBS, thanx to the impact of the maple and vanilla from the oak barrels and the maple syrup. A great beer but I prefer the KBS's strongness than this wonderful "soft" maple syrup version.

Received in a Ninja box from @Dragginballs76 – Thanks Michael! Undated 750 mL capped bottle, stored at 42 degrees and served at 58 degrees in a hand washed and dried Jester King snifter. Appearance – 4.25 Body – Dark brown/black, opaque. Effervescent. Head – Large (Maximum 4.5 cm, aggressive center pour), khaki, medium density with a rocky top, good retention, slooowy diminishing to a very irregular three to twelve mm ring fed by effervescence and a thick and rocky partial layer. Head retraction leaves complete rings of lacing, fairly unusual for a brew that is both 11.7% ABV and barrel-aged. Lacing – Good. The combination of the head retraction and the lowering of the beer level with consumption leaves a picturesque curtain effect. First pour – Dark brown, clear. Aroma – 4 - Dark chocolate, light roasted malt, a hint of coffee, no maple syrup aroma. Flavor – 4.25 – Initial flavor is coffee followed by a bit of chocolate. Maple ghosts by on the aftertaste. Alcohol is not found in the taste, nor on the nose, nor evident by gastric warming. It was, however, evident in my mental patterns as I finished the bottle. Hops are not evident. No diacetyl and no dimethylsulfide. Palate – 4 – Medium to full, almost creamy, soft carbonation. Impression and summation – 4.25 – There is no argument that this is an above-average impy stout. However, IMHO, those rating it as straight “5”s across the board need to re-examine every impy stout they have ever reviewed. The aroma is not extremely above average – I wasn’t transported to Dream Lands by the wafting perfumes of ambrosia. The palate is not excessively better than most impy stouts. The appearance was only slightly unusual in that good lacing remained considering the ABV and the barrel-aging factor. The flavor, while good, did not transport me to Paradise, not even by the dashboard lights. I’m certainly glad that I tried it but still, it’s much like buying a unicorn and finding out it’s only a mutated goat.

Got the first pour off a new keg at New Albanian during Gravity Head. Strangely, I smell nothing. But that's it. Phenomenal. Smooth. Like the KBS without the sharpness or boozy taste. Yes there's booze, but it's mellow. OMG GOOD
Very dark clear brown, aromas of coffee, maple and chocolate. Rich, but not as sweet as I expected - balanced vs. the ABV. Aftertaste has wonderful layers of flavors that linger on the tongue.

This delicious stout has plenty of the advertised maple, but its subtleties also recall sweet fruit—I sense cherry and maybe a bit of strawberry. The beer pours a deep, thick brown with a gorgeously tan head, and it smells like a sweet coffee. Truly an excellent beer for a special occasion.

Appearance – Half finger head on a nearly opaque clear brown body. Aroma – Coffee, dark roasted malt, maple syrup, dark chocolate. Wow. Very layered. Taste – Coffee, roasted malt, maple syrup, slightly sweet, definitely a sipping beer. Very rich. Mouthfeel – Full and thick, slightly creamy. Overall – Well worth the hype. The best stout I have had in years.
More chocolate than I expected.

On tap at the brewery. Dark, near black in the pint shaker. Modest head that doesn't last as well as hoped. Winey and a little oily for the mouthfeel. A decent spritziness, but less carbonation than average. The deep, dark burnt flavors are pretty strong, but it's on the sweet and malty side rather than the dry. The coconut is pretty intense and tastes like it's been scorched a little, too. Rather sweet, and quite bitter like an IPA. Brewers say this is 40 IBUs. Interesting smell of coconut along with the flavor, is nice in the beer. Overall, this is just a little over-hopped and over-roasted, but I found that I finished the glass without intending to.

This was poured into a becher pint glass. The appearance was a semi-dark burnt orange ranging close to brown color with a one finger white foamy head that formed rings of lace around the upper rim of the glass. A bit little darker than expected for an APA. The smell starts off with an earthy tobacco sweetness allowing a nice dried pine backing up the aroma. The taste was basically the same. Dried tobacco aftertaste leading into the same finish. On the palate, this one sat about a light to medium on the body with a decent sessionability about it. Carbonation feels good as an APA. Overall, I dig it as an APA. But it definitely has a lot of earthy to tobacco aroma going on.

From the 650 ml. bottle. No bottling/expiration date. Sampled on September 7, 2016. Decent looking mahogany amber brown with a soft, lingering tan head and slightly cloudy. The aroma is of caramel malts, herbal notes, and a mossy-tobacco under current. Low earthy hop profile. Medium, smooth body. Slight malted sweetness with that same peat-like moss-like addition and a mild, smooth finish. Nothing spectacular but it may be an older bottle.

Big thanks to raffy313 for blindly dropping a pair of these on my porch to attempt to prove to me how not awful this beer is despite the iffy ratings for a barleywine. :) 12oz bottle poured into Duvel tulip Appearance: Color is a deep orange, thinnish off-white head that goes about a finger deep on an aggressive pour. Very nice lacing. Smell: Boozy, bread, caramel malt, and a bit of earthy/grassy odor. Taste: Alcohol, lots and lots of alcohol. There is a nice body here with caramel, and even a decent little bitter pine-y hop punch, but really this beer is all about the booze at the moment. Mouthfeel: A bit thin for the style, but still medium. Carb level is nice. Drinkability: Average. ABV is on the high side, and the beer is hot, but it goes down fairly easy, all things considered. Overall: I'm glad I have another bottle of this, because it really needs some time to knock the edge off. I do actually think this beer will be better in a year or two, as what lies underneath is not bad. It's just not ready yet.

Served in a Freetail 2012 shaker pint glass. Thanks to twiggamortis420 for this bottle! The underside of the cap instructs me to "Get a Head". As if that wasn't the goal of every man at all times anyway... So, yeah, this stuff pours a clear bronze-amber topped by a half-finger at best of sad little off-khaki suds. The nose comprises buttery biscuit, light melon, light grapefruit peel, and a few drops of dried maple syrup. The taste holds notes of maple syrup, caramel, honeydew, orange peel, light toasted bread, and a strong surge of straight-up booze. This last bit ruins things, as it washes over and o'ercolors all else, leaving only a bludgeon of alcohol to have its way with my tongue. The body is a lithe medium, with a light moderate carbonation and a generally smooth feel. Overall, I felt this old ale overdid it a bit with its alcohol presence, with little else going on in the background. Not my cup o' tea, right here.

Poured a ruddy orange amber with two fingers of eggshell head. Relatively mild aroma of caramel, pine, and dark fruit mixed with booze. Moderate carbonation and a full, rich mouthfeel. Grapefruit and orange up front followed by sweet caramel and toffee. Sugar cookie and dark fruit mingle on the finish, which features some bitter pine. Interesting mix of strong hops and figgy sweetness. Not overly boozy. Looking forward to seeing how my other bottle develops.

Casked DR12 tapping at Hay Merchant A: Not perfectly clear, a bit murky. Copper in color with a creamy off white head. Slightly different character than when i had it from the keg. S: Fresh, lemon grass, hoppy, fruity. A touch of pickled ginger. T: Taste follows the smell. Hops are present. Citrus, crisp, and refreshing. Undoubtedly smoother in flavor out of the cask. Reminds me of Endeavor a bit. Mild bitterness in the aftertaste. M: Smooth as silk from the cask. Markedly different than the keg offering. O: A good beer. The ratings are weak but i still came out for the cask tapping because its a decent brew. Reminds me of an IPA overall.
From a can dated 10/18/16.

Sampled December 2014 from bottle in pint glass. Appearance: Very dark color, dark tan head that quickly disappeared. I would have liked the head to last longer. Smell: Sweet with strong toasted coffee aromas, also some hints of the hops. Taste: Full-bodied with great balance of malt and hops. Dominated by roasted coffee, but with some flavor from the hops. The strong alcohol adds to the flavors as well. Taste starts sweet with malts, then comes the roasted coffee flavors, and then a little bitterness from the hops. Overall a great combination and a great taste. Mouthfeel: Full-bodied, but smooth. Overall: Nice imperial stout. Best if you enjoy a combination strong malts & coffee, with a little bitterness from the hops. I will buy this again.

Not bad. Not a first choice stout for me, but no complaints in a pinch. Dark black. Moderately rich mouthfeel. Some malty bitterness, simultaneous with hints of dark molasses sweetness that partially masks what feels like potent alcohol. Long finish, with some licorice.

The beer pours out a medium hazy golden color, with 1 finger of white head and nice lacing----------- the aromas are of malts, floral notes and pine---------- the flavors are of Carmel malts, pine, citrus, floral/soapy notes, the beer has a thin to medium mouthfeel with a nice bitterness on the finish-------------- overall this beer was good - this was a nice mix of the British pale and the American versions, nice Carmel malt backbone followed by floral and pine, what a well balanced beer

Dark golden straw almost amber color. The head is super thick, and pillowy white. Malty and fruit in the aroma, smells sweet. Tastes of bicuity malts and mild toffee sweetness with faint pine. Very light bitterness and dry finish.

I remember listening to Def Leppard in the mid and late-'80's, wearing acid washed jeans and growing my hair. This beer, from a tall can, is a golden-amber color. The head is modest, thick, and white. Malt and fruit are notable in the aroma....along with a musty, hop scent. The taste is balanced, with just a tilt to sweet with a solid bitterness. Firm body. All in all, a nice beer. Not sure if it tastes better while wearing acid-washed jeans.
Not a bad beer at all. I'd pay $1.60 for a 16oz. again.You don't even notice it's 6%.

16 ounce can into tulip glass, canned on 6/1/2018. Pours slightly hazy deep golden amber/light orange color with a 1-2 finger fairly dense and rocky off white head with fantastic retention, that reduces to a nice cap that lasts. Thick soapy lacing clings around the glass. Fantastic appearance. Aromas of tangerine, lemon, grapefruit, peach, pineapple, apricot, mango, melon, citrus peel/zest, light pepper/pine, honey, bread dough, toasted biscuit, light caramel/nuttiness, herbal, and floral/grassy earthiness. Nice and pleasant aromas with good balance and complexity of citrus/fruity hops and bready malt notes; with solid strength. Taste of big tangerine, lemon, grapefruit, peach, pineapple, apricot, mango, melon, citrus peel/zest, light pepper/pine, honey, bread dough, toasted biscuit, light caramel/nuttiness, herbal, and floral/grassy earthiness. Light pine, zesty, herbal, grassy, spicy bitterness on the finish. Lingering notes of tangerine, lemon, grapefruit, peach, pineapple, apricot, mango, melon, citrus peel/zest, light pepper/pine, honey, bread dough, toasted biscuit, light caramel/nuttiness, and herbal/floral/grassy earthiness on the finish for a while. Great complexity, robustness, and balance of citrus/fruity hops and bready malt flavors; with a solid malt/bitterness balance; and no cloying/astringent flavors after the finish. Lightly increasing dryness from lingering bitterness. Medium carbonation and medium-plus body; with a very smooth, creamy/bready, and lightly sticky mouthfeel that is great. Zero warming alcohol for 6%. Overall this is a delicious American pale ale! All around nice complexity, robustness, and balance of citrus/fruity hops and bready malt flavors; very smooth and refreshing to drink with the mildly bitter/drying finish, great soft feel. Definitely a lot of Cascade/Amarillo hop notes going on. Awesome balance of juicy hops and bready English malts, with mild lingering sweetness. A very enjoyable offering, and spot on style example.

Canned On: 06-11-18. Appearance: Pours a relatively clear, deep golden-hued body with an inch or two of near white froth. Competent lacing. Smell: Oven-toasted biscuits, crisp grains and lightly sweet-smelling toffee with understated notes of citrus and pine. Taste: Toasted bicuity malts with a thin brushing of toffee sweetness. Gently citrusy with modest hints of grapefruit and lemon. Faint, faint pine. Clean albeit light bitterness. Drying finish with quick, fleeting flashes of the aforementioned toasted biscuit tops and bitterish citrus. Mouthfeel: Medium-bodied. Medium carbonation. Overall: Hmm, well, I must say I didn't mind this one at all.

Like other TH pale ales, this one isn't much to look at. Where it shines is the hop finish that is lacking in some of the brewery's other popular offerings. The citrus aroma isn't nearly as overpowering as it is in Julius, Green, or Alter Ego. The taste has a better malt/hops balance. The mouthfeel and body are right on par with the best TH has to offer. A fine example of the NE-style pale ale.

Haaze is the best "normal" IPA TH makes. It has a peach-like quality to it. Sometimes it can be rank though. I got a growler fill once and it was nasty. This beer must be consumed quickly after canning. Overall, one of their better beers.

16 ounce can into tulip glass, canned on 6/14/2017. Pours moderately hazy/cloudy medium golden yellow color with a 2 finger fairly dense and rocky off white head with fantastic retention, that reduces to a nice cap that lasts. Dense foamy lacing clings on the glass, with a moderate amount of streaming carbonation retaining the cap. Fantastic appearance. Aromas of grapefruit, lemon, orange, peach, pear, pineapple, red apple, melon, coriander, dill, citrus peel/zest, light pepper/pine, wheat, cracker, white bread, herbal, floral, grass and yeast earthiness. Nice and pleasant aromas with good balance and complexity of citrus/fruity/earthy hops, fruity yeast, and pale/wheat malt notes; with solid strength. Taste of grapefruit, lemon, orange, peach, pear, pineapple, red apple, melon, coriander, dill, citrus peel/zest, light pepper/pine, wheat, cracker, white bread, herbal, floral, grassy and yeast earthiness. Light-moderate pine, citrus peel/zest, herbal, grassy, spicy bitterness on the finish. Lingering notes of grapefruit, lemon, orange, peach, pear, pineapple, red apple, melon, coriander, dill, citrus peel/zest, light pepper, pine, wheat, cracker, white bread, herbal, floral, grass, and yeast earthiness on the finish for a good bit. Great complexity, robustness, and balance of citrus/fruity/earthy hops, fruity yeast, and pale/wheat malt flavors; with a great malt/bitterness balance, and zero lingering hop astringency after the finish. Light-moderate increasing dryness from bitterness and carbonation. Medium-high carbonation and medium body; with a very smooth, creamy/bready/grainy, fairly sticky, and slightly resinous balanced mouthfeel that is great. Zero warming alcohol for 6.4%. Overall this is a delicious hoppy American pale wheat ale. All around nice complexity, robustness, and balance of citrus/fruity/earthy hops, fruity yeast, and pale/wheat malt flavors; very smooth and pretty refreshing to drink with the mellowly bitter/drying finish. Great balance of juicy/earthy Columbus, Cascade, Sorachi ace hops; with fruity American wheat yeast, and pale/wheat malts. A very enjoyable offering, and spot on style example.
Pours a pale cloudy yellow with the nice head typical of wheat beers. The hops provide the major taste notes, not overdone so this beer feels nicely balanced.

tall can., I cant find any freshness/canning date info Hazed lighter amber, soft and fluffy head, leaves fine bubble strands of lacing. Citric hop nose with lime coming to mind Fresh, fruity, citric and worthy hopped up wheaty brew. Lemon, lime and lemongrass...yum...would be great with thai/vietnamese/Indian/BBQ/Spicy food....quality stuff...go get some

16 oz can. Pours hazy medium gold color, thick meringue head has great retention and leaves rings of lace. Wheat and citrus aroma. Wheat bread base with citrus peel hops and lemony grassy bitterness that lasts a while. Soft feel. Very solid hoppy wheat ale, liked the back end bitterness.

An odd greenish gold with tons of haziness and particulate. The aroma is sweet with a lemon candy scent and some pine. The taste is malty, lemony and sweet with a quite aggressive pine finish. This is an odd beer but not bad. I love the flavors but the looks, not so much.

Pours a nice murky hazy orange, almost grapefruit juice color. Nice off white colored dense two finger head, falls slowly laces fairly well. Aroma is nice nice sweet orange on whet base dominate. Some lighter grapefruit but only get hints of lemon grass kind of strange for a beer claiming that on the label. That being said the nose in very nice and citrus hoppy wheat ale. Taste is like the nose, nice wheat malt base loaded with west coast citrus hops. Orange, grapefruit notes and lemon grass more in the flavor then the nose. Some earthy like notes of hops appear in the linger end of the finish. Mouthfeel is solid medium if not a touch more. Carbonation in fairly peppy and kick up the hoppy resin a touch. Overall an enjoyable hoppy wheat ale very well done in my opinion. Would purchase this one again to be sure.

Very hazy, deep golden color. Smell is of sour lemon, citrus. Not a typical wheat beer. No banana, clove signature. Very lemony citrus, bitter hop taste. Definitely taste the Sorachi Ace here. Very solid beer and a nice change of pace.

My Bro-in-law got this from a buddy and he so kindly was willing to share. It poured a opaque hazy applesauce with white head that is leaving a spotty lace. The scent is mostly lemongrass. The taste is affected by the sorachi ace hops. Very distinct flavor. The Mouthfeel is medium in body with smooth carbonation. Overall it's definitely worth a try.

2016 can, pours a cloudy dark golden color with a thick white frothy head. There is quite a bit of a soapy lacing. The odor for me is grapefruit, orange, lemon, herbal, slightly spicy, slight pineapple, pine, slight resin. The taste for me is spicy, herbal, grapefruit, lemon, grassy, hay, earthy, spicy, dry. There is some bitterness throughout.

A: Pours a very cloudy/murky deep golden honey in color with light to moderate amounts of active visible carbonation rising along the edges of the glass and some faint amber highlights. The beer has a finger tall dense foamy (almost creamy) bright white head that slowly reduces to a large patch of medium thick film covering the entire surface of the beer with a medium thick ring at the edges of the glass. Significant amounts of lacing are observed. S: Slightly stronger than moderate aromas of citrus/grapefruit, citrus/grapefruit pith, citrus/lemon, and pine/resin hops over light aromas of wheat and toasted malts. T: Upfront there is a just shy of moderate flavor of wheat and toasted malts with a hint of caramel sweetness. That is followed by slightly stronger than moderate flavors of citrus/grapefruit, citrus/grapefruit pith, citrus/lemon, herbal, and pine/resin hops which contribute a light to moderate amount of lingering bitterness. M: Just slightly heavier than light bodied with moderate amounts of carbonation. Almost creamy initially with a light amount of dryness in the finish. O: Very enjoyable and very easy to drink with a slightly thinner mouthfeel than I expected but that improves it for the hot weather. Really nice hop flavors and aromas.

Beer review #1000 for me. Actually drank this beer a while ago but knew that with a beer this special I'd wait till the one thousand mark. This beer pours a beautiful deep dark brown with a legitimate dark tan head. The aroma is a fantastic blend of coffee, chocolate and maple. The flavor follows the nose, with vanilla, caramel and oak joining the party. The feel is smooth and creamy. Overall I believe this is the best beer I've had.

this was really good however I feel like I really shot myself in the foot by not letting this one sit for at least 6 months or so. You can tell all the flavors would round out really well then it would be spectacular. Still very good just a touch rough around the edges

Poured from a 750 bottle into a St Bernardus goblet. Vintage 2017. 4.75/4.25/4/4.5/4 A: Pours black, not too viscous, with an impressive two fingers of latte-colored foam. S: Smells like oatmeal raisin cookies with stale cold brew and loads of sugar and a touch of dark fruit and vanilla. No booze. T: Tastes smooth, but with a touch of fire. Most obvious are the toasted malts, which along with the sugar hints at toasted coconuts. Long endtaste is mostly dates and maple candy, but there is a touch of chocolate right at the end that forestalls any lingering cloyingness. From a beer with this much going on, I frankly expected a lot more. The taste is subdued and rather balanced, a rounder, sweeter KBS. I miss the bitterness from the FBS/KBS actually, but this is extremely well done. M: Very fine, toeing the line between thick and spritzy. Never too heavy or too anemic. Well done. O: Impressive, if not entirely worth scouring the planet. Virtually no trace of the 11.7%, a mellow, contemplative, after supper drink like a fortified wine.
Bottle courtesy of Toby. Dark brown with some light sneaking through. Aroma is the normal RIS aromas with hints of maple. Taste comes on a bit stronger, more of the booze, sweetness, coffee, maple.

This beer has the same great look as its more famous brother, KBS. The maple is distinctly present - somewhat in the nose and very potently in the flavor. The sweet maple flavor could present a nice contrast to the bitter roast but instead it somewhat detracts from the stout-like qualities of this offering. The bourbon also seems to be a bit drowned out. I waited a long time to sample this Great White Whale. Unfortunately, I was somewhat disappointed.

Pours an oily, pitch black coloration with a large, creamy head. Smells absolutely intoxicating of caramel, roasted malt and coffee, with lovely, mellow notes ouf bourbon, oak, vanilla chocolate, toffee and maple. Taste follows the nose, with a complex and incredibly well-balanced harmony of caramel, roasted malt, coffee, dark chocolate, toffee, bourbon, oak, vanilla and maple, with some earthy notes and a certain spicyness coming through as well. There is a slight bitterness in the aftertaste that really balances out the caramel, maple sweetness, not that it would be too pronounced in the first place. A little booze coming through as well, but it's such a lovely, mellow shade of bourbon that it doesn't feel unpleasant at all. Rich body with a thick, oily mouthfeel and low carbonation. This is without a doubt my new favorite stout, no contest. The exceptional balance is what makes this special. Nothing really stands out too much, which is a GOOD thing. Balancing a stout this complex so well is a true accomplishment.

I have finally had the pleasure of getting ahold of this legendary and well respected brew, this winter of 2018! First time tasted at a friend’s place, 2nd time, purchased by myself, cracked open at my son’s 2nd birthday party, reviewed here. Pours a dark mahogany and nearly black color.
