What is there of the maple is more of a sweetish earthiness than the unctuous liquid usually found on pancakes. The base beer contributes some more readiness and a vaguely creamy notion, probably attributable to the oats, but it really only seems to serve as a field for the additives to play on. The barrel is nearly impossible to find either in oak or bourbon; maybe there is some sweet vanilla toward the back end, but it is a reach. This seems to be a rather simplistic dessert showcase.On the plus side, the alcohol is nowhere to be found on the nose. 3.75/5 T: Aha, there is the maple! It runs a beautifully rich undercurrent of sweet, rustic earth through every sip, playing beautifully off of the moderately heavy coffee roast and sweet chocolate, which still remain the primary flavors. The base beer contributes a little umami and a ton of earthy hop flavors and bitterness; these hops get along wonderfully with thr maple. Finally, the bourbon barrel comes around in a big way with some savory spiciness, oaky tannins, bitter vanilla, and a little alcohol sweetness. The overall impression is something like buckwheat pancakes with too many chocolate chips and dark chocolate chunks drizzled moderately with bourbon barrel-aged pure maple syrup and with too-dark coffee washing each bite down. All that was absent from the nose shows up here resulting in a vast improvement and a delicious treat (though it is still lacking in nuance and balance keeping it firmly in the dessert beer category). 4.5/5 M: The feel is a slight tug of war between the thick and creamy base stout and the thinning nature of high alcohol beers, bourbon aging, and maple syrup. What results is a tale of two beers with the prevailing impression of a slightly too thin beer. The bitterness and dryness is surprisingly (and pleasantly) on the high side, letting this be far more drinkable than it should be. There is medium alcohol heat on the end of each sip, which is expected but still unfortunate. This area could use some improvement. 3.5/5 O: First things first: this is a marked improvement over KBS, which is even more imbalanced and is generally (ironically) way over-barreled in addition to the too-strong nearly burnt coffee assault. The maple syrup bourbon barrels are slightly more subtle, and the balance of the flavors is much better for it. That said, this is not a beer that benefits much from scrutiny and analysis like this; no, this beer was meant to be savored, a hedonistic prize for those who want pure enjoyment. For them, it will succeed, but for me, well, I prefer more balance, more nuance, and more base beer. This is enjoyable, no doubt, but it is not worthy of the hype, the cost, or the search. At the time of its original release, CBS was innovative, but it has since been definitively surpassed time and time again, just like its brash older brother. Pair with seminal death metal group Morbid Angel's newest (and still somehow dated) release "Kingdoms Disdained". 4/5
2017 release enjoyed January 2018. Smooth & well balanced!
It's a good beer. Not deserving of it's status though. Came off a bit unbalanced and boozy. Maple flavor comes in at the last second. Hype beer

750ml bottle - 2017 release Pours black with a creamy tan brown foam head. Smells like maple, wood, oak, bourbon, cherry, dark fruit, rich luscious chocolate, roasted coffee, toasted bready malts, caramel, dark toffee, molasses, brown sugar, some vanilla, with floral earthy herbal grassy pine. Tastes like big sweet rich maple syrup, wood, oak, some bourbon, cherry, dark fruit, luscious dark chocolate, roasted coffee, toasted bready malt, caramel, dark toffee, molasses, charred brown sugar, vanilla, marshmallow, with floral earthy herbal grassy pine. Feels medium bodied, thick and creamy with moderate smooth carbonation. Overall a really great imperial stout with chocolate and coffee aged in maple syrup-bourbon barrels.

2017 vintage poured at fridge temp from a small bottled obtained in France. Pours jet black with nice carbonation - nice light brown head. Nose is full of coffee, maple, and bourbon. Also layers of chocolate fudge, wood, and black licorice. Quite amazing nose. Taste is roasted malts - quite a bit of burnt notes. Not a ton of bourbon barrel. Lots of coffee and chocolate. Dark fruit and tobacco linger around, along with black licorice. As this warmed, the sweetness intensified. The maple comes through a bit more as well. This is similar to KBS, although there are definitely differences. Mouthfeel is thick and creamy. Overall, it's not quite living up to the hype it once received, but it's a fantastic BA stout and I'm very happy to have a few.

I've had this three times now in the last few weeks, since the 2017 came out. All were servings on tap. I also bought a bomber, but I haven't cracked it yet. I can respect this beer, but I'm not in love with it. Yes, it's a richly flavored barrel aged stout. Once upon a time, that simple statement would be enough to rate a beer in the absolute top tier. But these days, a lot of brewers are making fine stouts with whisky barrel aging. Just being a barrel aged stout should not be enough to get a top rating. Among the large number of barrel aged stouts I've had, CBS does stand out ... for being too damn sweet. I do like maple syrup, but not in these quantities. The maple sweetness steps on all the other flavors that are a part of the stout, which is too bad. Hey, it's still pretty good, but I won't buy another bottle. There are much better barrel aged stouts available around here.

Appearance: Quite clear, apropos amber-hued body with a very, very thin head -- due mainly to a to-the-top pour from the Taco Mac bartender. Smell: A scent of barley grains given a thin layer of toastiness, followed by a sniff of crystal malts, florals, and reserved citrus. Taste: Mildly toasty, bready malts tipping towards a moderate crystal sweetness. Hoppy qualities of florals, herbs, and citrus. Well-rounded, yes, though all very subtle. Medium-low bitterness. Dry, faintly toasty finish with a lingering near-muted floral tone. Mouthfeel: Medium-bodied. Medium carbonation. Overall: Jailhouse delivers a likable, easy-drinking amber. A beer I’ll cheerfully opt for a second or third helping of.

Bought a 750 ML growler on Thursday 9/29. Appearance includes a very murky yellow orange with a thick, bubbly head with thick lacing on the sides. Aromas are very apparent with grapefruit, tangerine, and orangepeel smells. Taste follows the nose with an incredibly fruity (citrus mostly) flavor, including a sharp orange aftertaste. The mouthfeel really helps to bring out the flavors by making this beer have a medium carbonation while being very refreshing. Overall, this was a fantastic beer, especially with its aromas.
Hazy (to be expected). Taste is super-mango, super fruity, with a bitter, wet finish. I can taste the alcohol very slightly. Flavor spreads nicely, good drinking beer.
Poured from growler 2 days after buying. Dark orange murky look. Big juicy notes of mango and melon/passionfruit. I found finish to be pretty bitter. Enjoyed this but little underwhelmed.
Very nice double IPA. Nice aroma out of the glass with the same hazy appearance as most every other Treehouse beer that I have had. Great fruit and tropical flavors on the palette as well.

My 1st Treehouse brew I was able to trade for. Canned 8/13/16 poured into Teku glass. Milkshake haze orange appearance brings an insane aroma of pineapple, mango orange when I popped open the can. Taste is mango, orange hoppy goodness with a very boozy finish I was not expecting (but enjoyed). Overall very crushable the alcohol burn on the finish is what pushed this to almost a 5 for me most juice bombs I have had are a little too sweet. Will definitely be seeking out a lot more TH in the future.

Canned date of 07/20/16 Appearance - Pours extremely hazy and orange in color with an off-white, frothy finger width head. Fair retention, resulting in a thin, consistent layer of suds across the surface. Fair lacing, most of which is made up of spotting found around the glass. Smell - Plenty of juiciness on the nose, with orange, pineapple, lesser peach and a hint of spice. Taste - Follows the nose. Juicy notes of orange and pineapple upfront, following shortly with lesser notes of peach and mango. A touch of hop spice and some stonefruit pit nuttiness mid-taste. The back end rings with fair grapefruit pith and some light, bready sweetness. Mouthfeel - Medium-bodied with moderate carbonation. Smooth drinker, though a touch of chalkiness (presumably from the yeast) in the texture. Overall - One heck of a NE-style DIPA, and certainly one of the trendsetters of the style. If there's one knock, it may be a bit too yeasty, but I'm nitpicking. This is a damn tasty brew.

Draft pour to snifter, very dark brown with a beige head, some retention and lacing. Nose of roasted coffee, oak wood. Taste leads with cinnamon and moves to coffee, then to a bitter finish with somewhat of an off flavor. Creamy mouthfeel and above average body.

2017 Edition 375ml bottle. Look: Beautiful dark brew with a huge tan head. Smell: Bakers chocolate, milk chocolate, Maraschino cherry truffles, Taste: Wow! Nice big chocolatey stout, nougat, maple syrup, sweet red maraschino cherries and finishes with a slight hit of bourbon booziness. Nice thick mouthfeel. Overall: Pretty amazing! Chocolate decadence in a glass. It's a fairly sweet affair, which may be off-putting to some. I am not sure what happened to the coffee, I just don't get the typical roasty to green flavours that coffee imparts on beer. I would seek this out but I would not age it, this needs to be drunk within it's expiry date - which in this case was October 27th, 2018.

It's a well done big stout. Can't say I see the mania for it though. I never had the original but it was the first really rare one I couldn't get back when I first started trading, so it was legend. Maybe the game has caught up to them in the years since the first release. I enjoyed it, but I didn't $30 enjoy it. I can't say I really picked up on the maple either. Too much maple is too much, but It must have been very subtle. If you had given this to me blind and not told me anything about it, I'd have rated it a nicely done stout. But I'd do that for tons of big stouts these days, so I'm not seeing it as a standout amongst the many others. I would buy this again at $12.99, or $15 tops.
As a huge fan KBS I knew that this would be good. And I wasn’t disappointed! Sweet chocolate and coffee. Thick and chewy. Super duper!

Yeah I bought into the hype and paid $27 for 1 pint 9.4 oz bottle here in Oklahoma and it doesn't disappoint. Beer pours a motor oil black with a dark tan head. The smell is alcohol, chocolate and some coffee. The flavor is first and foremost sweet then roasted malts with the chocolate, coffee maybe a hint of maple no strong presence of bourbon which is a good thing. A nice smooth stout just a tad overpriced but hey they got me.

L - Vigorously poured into a snifter. Jet black with about an Inch of cocoa brown head, which stays around a lot longer than I would have thought at 11.7 abv. S - Nose is full of chocolate and coffee with a lot of booziness in the back. Can only barely detect the maple syrup. Way boozier than I expected. Buddy even commented on how strong it smelled when I was pouring mine some 5 feet away. T - Taste is the same chocolate and coffee, but it's only a tad hot in the back. Very sweet. Thankfully the booziness takes a backseat when actually drinking it. Maple syrup is ever so slight on the backend and only makes itself known upon swallowing. Delicious but I really expected a lot more maple syrup based in what I had heard. Flavors really pop as the beer warms up. Drink it slow. F - Oh so creamy. Coats the mouth nicely to the point where the taste lingers around for quite a bit after swallowing. Feels like a stout is supposed to feel. O - Absolutely a world class beer. I was not disappointed, but I don't think it quite lived up to the hype. I will certainly seek it out in the future, and if the opportunity arises will try earlier batches. I really want to try that overwhelmingly maple forward beer I have heard stories about, but this isn't quite that. Drink it slow and enjoy it, it is still fantastic.

2017 vintage from a 35cL bottle. What strucks me the most the instant I try this beer is its wonderful balance. Gorgeous pitch black with a mocha/maple head. Nice lacing all along. The smell is incredible with coffee, maple, toffee, bourbon, oak, vanilla. Very attractive smell The taste follows with a certain maple/toffee sweetness, some cocoa, some coffee, and a certain peppercorn spiciness. Some booziness but nothing overwhelming The mouthfeel is very smooth, Very very nice. Overall a wonderfully balanced beer, a gourmet beer. I think I prefer KBS but this one is wonderful in its own way. It's 11.7% ABV but I'm drinking so fast as it's crazy drinkable! It's gonna it me hard in some time, for now it's great. I'll try to age at least one bottle to see where it's going. Anyway it's great now!

From Hopt.es. In Teku glass. Playing Super Furball. Very smooth but I prefer KBS. This hasnt the excellent coffee touch and instead it has bourbon notes that becomes fairly strong as warms up, more than I like. 2017 version

Served on tap in a snifter glass. Nose is very similar to KBS, but more chocolate forward. Little to no maple syrup on the nose, even as it warms. Taste is very similar to the nose. It’s incredibly delicious, but again, chocolate forward and reminiscent of KBS. I wouldn’t say it meets the hype built up over the years, but it’s a fantastic beer nonetheless.

On tap at Blind Tiger New Year's Eve party. After chasing this beer for so long, it is really nice to see that this batch is pretty available on tap and in bottles. I had really high expectations for this one and it pretty much delivered. I've had better BA stouts, but this one is pretty special.

Poured an inky black at 53 degrees, with thick mousse-like lite tan foam; long cap retention; heavy lacing; the skinniest of legs upon swirl. Strong coffee nose with vanilla bean, maple syrup and roasted malt as it warms to 55 degrees. Flavors of toasted tootsie roll, espresso, vanilla bread pudding with chocolate bits; barely any bourbon; lite maple on the finish. Somewhat creamy feel;medium full body - definitely not thin; light plus carbonation; fetishized Barrel/wood tongue coating. Overall this stout hits on all cylinders for me; no strong flavors, all in balance, and the maple contributed more to the feel as its flavor is subdued, which is fine by me; a pleasure to sip and experience.

CBS - Founders Imperial Stout - 11.7% abv L - 3-finger hazelnut head atop a pitch black body. S - bourbon, maple, coffee, chocolate, molasses, oak, booze. Wow there’s so much going on here! T - I get a lot of bourbon at first. A little maple syrup but it’s subtle. Coffee and chocolate in equal measure. Booze is quite apparent at this young age. Not too sweet. Low bitterness. F - medium-full creamy body. O - I wish the maple was a little more forward, but still this is one amazing brew.

Pours pitch black with a well retained two inch tan head that left excellent lacing. Smells of dark roast coffee, dark chocolate, roasted malts, maple syrup and a hint of bourbon. Taste follows the nose with dark chocolate up front followed by dark roast coffee, toffee, vanilla, dark fruits, bourbon and maple syrup. I was expecting far more of the barrel and maple flavors. Medium to heavy bodied, light carbonation, thick and creamy mouth feel.

12 fl oz bottle poured into tulip. I’d always resigned myself to never trying this beer as I had no idea that it would ever reach UK shores. Needless to say, I leapt at the opportunity to get my hands on some. This is simply exceptional. Maybe it was the anticipation and I know that most heavyweight stouts have a fairly uniform appearance but I’ve never seen a beer look more stunning in the glass. The depth of flavour is incredible and the mouthfeel is divine. It’s really difficult to define “balanced” but CBS ticks every box in this regard. If only the aroma was a tad more assertive, this would be utter perfection in my book. Better than KBS? Maybe just a touch. Love it. Cheers!

Unlike my baby mama, there is nothing bad I can say about this drink. Smells like Nina Agdal in a nightie, while the taste is akin to Nina’s mom in a corset. See, I went with said Victoria’s Secret hotties mother because there is something mature about CBS with every sip. So yeah, drinking this intoxicating beverage is like being with a Victoria’s Secret model and her mom. Prost!

Review #1400 Appearance: My bright flashlight will show through the edges, but not across the glass. So, we're going with opaque. Black, bit of ruby brown edge, holds a thin halo of tan foam that gives up a little lace. Aroma: Bourbon barrel, black bread, caramel malt, earthy hop, with a harsh burnt edge that might be coffee or heavy roasted barley. Light sour stout note as well. Frankly, not super inviting, a bit boozy and burnt. Taste: It's everything it says on the tin. Barrel charred bourbon soaked wood, sweet malty stout, maple candy finish. A little bitter chocolate in the finish. Dark fruit flavors, plum, fig, purple grape, all have gone quite ripe and begun to ferment. Mouthfeel: Heavy body, low medium carbonation, warming slowly drying finish, little chew. Overall: Currently #13 on the all time beer list. I understand the hype. I made a special trip to pay $25 for the bomber, and have no regrets. I probably should have let the bottle sit for a few months, it may have mellowed out the bourbon and let the cast of characters shine a little brighter, but it's easy drinking as it stands fairly fresh.

0% Pours a hazy (obviously) golden yellow color with a frothy bone white head. The smell hits your nose right as you open the can. Notes of mango, pineapple, guava, grapefruit, and orange. Also getting a slightly weedy aroma as well. Taste is majorly up front with pineapple, mango, and guava, with bitter grapefruit and orange zest coming through towards the end. Alcohol is slightly noticeable. Mouthfeel is smooth and creamy. Carbonation is slightly low but helps with the overall mouthfeel. Overall, an amazing NE DIPA. It has that typical tropical taste and smooth feel you'd expect from breweries like Tree House, Trillium, and Monkish.
Excellent selection if you're looking to try Treehouse beers and can't get your hands on Julius or Green. Tastes great!

Big thanks to Kegatron for the growler share. Poured into a snifter appears a milky looking melted creamsicle orange color with a white head that holds well painting the glass with a curtain of lace. Aroma is fruity orange/pineapple juice very hoppy and wonderful smelling. Slight grassiness and overall hop pellet feel with a touch of alcohol. As it breathes even more tropical hop scents emerge. Taste is more of the same orange juice meets pineapple, mango, cantaloupe, honeydew with slight yeastiness and bitter lingering grassy pith/pulp. Medium in body with modest carbonation. This has a creamy yeast filled feel that goes down easy. Despite tasting similar to just about every other hoppy thing ive had from tree house, this one brings a little brighter pop of fruity quality. Hell yea id drink it again if offered. This goes down crazy easy, never would have guessed it at 8%.
an amazing IPA unlike many i have had . a unique flavor with note of papaya. the nose and mouth on this beer is so pleasant and different

From the 16oz can, dated 09/07/16, served in an imperial pint/nonic. Pours a profoundly turbid orange-grapefruit colour with a generous finger of lush, creamy head. Retention is just pretty good but leaves a rich, enduring skim of suds and thick sheets of lacing. From a classical standpoint, this beer is butt-ugly; to the aficionado of NEIIPA's, it is a beverage of surpassing beauty. The nose is sugar cookies, peaches, pineapples, and sweaty sex in a weedy ditch. Tastes of soft, juicy, fruity yeast. Dank herbal notes, fresh white bread, pineapple, grapefruit pith, orange zest and a melange of various fermented (read boozy) tropical fruits. Ends with grass clippings and a little pine tingle. The feel is oily and medium-heavy, very juicy but well carbonated. All (maybe just almost all?) of the Tree House PA's share that signature, instantly-identifiable peachy-bubblegum-yeasty-somethingness and Haze is no exception. The booze is quite prominent on this one, maybe a little too much so but, otherwise, it's just SO damn good that it's hard to ding it too much for that.

L: Cloudy, milky orange yellow. Coul d almost pass for mango juice. Two to three fingers of head. Left a thick lacing all the way down the glass. S: Pineapple juice. T: Follows nose with some mango, papaya, orange peel. Slighty bitter on the end. As it warms a pine bitterness finishes. F: Sticky, moderate to high carbonation. Medium body. O: Well done new england dipa. Alcohol is well hidden. Very juicy.
Another winner from Treehouse. Tasty n juicy like everything I've had from them. Very easy to drink and smooth. Like pretty much everyone who's had TH brews I just wish you could get more.
Fresh can. Very clean flavors. Crisp and refreshing. Nice even level of hop flavor, balanced and not overbearing but still enough to keep you interested. A great beer for hot weather days.

This is a phenomenal APA. No clue what the hop profile is, bit definitely C-hop driven with Columbus being a primary component. Very clean, crisp, and well carbed. Would make an excellent daily drinker. Boat had been my go to summer beer, but this is right up there. When they can it, may become my preferred pool beer. Really damn good.

Pours a straw-yellow color with a stable, one finger broad head. Tastes of bread and floral hops, together with marzipan and a herbal whiff. The nose turns into a slightly sweeter, malty direction, next to a flower garden during spring. Has a fitting, lively carbonation, with a light, sessionable body. Begins with slightly honeyed malts, balanced by floral hops and wheat. The carbonation adds a metallic aspect, adding depth to the prominent malts. A pleasant bitterness is recognizable, cutting through the malts, inviting flowers to the palate. During the finish, the bitterness departs, accentuating biscuity malts, bread and a pleasant, short dryness. Well balanced, easy drinking beer, with enough depth to it, preventing it from being one-dimensional, mostly based on the intriguing addition of utmost flowery hops.

L- murky pink, almost like grapefruit juice S- raspberry is definitely potent, with a pungent aroma of bacteria T- strong raspberry taste, along with the lactobacillus F- acidic, sour and light but not so much acidity that would cause acid reflux like some of the sour beers ive had O- the flavor is very well done and enjoyable to drink. I wish there was more of a sour expression from this beer. Overall i give it a 4/5

A: The beer is clear crimson red in color and has a slight amount of visible carbonation. It poured with a thin tan head that quickly died down, leaving a thin collar around the edge of the glass and eventually completely fading away. S: The smell is rather sweet and has hints of rye bread aromas. T: Similar to the smell, the taste is quite sugary and sweet and also has notes of rye bread and yeast in the flavors along with hints of raisins. M: It feels light- to medium-bodied and a bit syrupy on the palate with a moderate amount of carbonation. O: Compared to the brewery's Домашний, this beer seems a little bit heavier on the palate and is also sweeter with added hints of raisins, making the taste a bit more complex. It's quite easy to drink and doesn't have any "off" flavors.

A 330ml can with a BB of May 2018, so it's a little out of date. Given its strength I'm hoping it has aged well. Acquired a little while back from Trembling Madness in York. The label calls it an Imperial Vietnamese Coffee Milk Porter; the ingredients include Vietnamese coffee and lactose. A: Poured into a Duvel tulip. Can-conditioned. A very dark brown colour that appears ultra-black in the glass. Produces a large head of creamy brown foam that rapidly settles and dissipates. S: Aroma of rich roasted coffee with hints of dark malt, burnt grain, subtle molasses, chocolate, earthiness, vague fruitiness, ale yeast and faint stewed leaves. Complex and decadent - fantastic. T: Tastes of intense roasted coffee with notes of burnt grain, dark malt, bitter chocolate, mild molasses, a touch of caramel, lactose sweetness, earthiness, faint spice, ale yeast and vague stewed leaves. Quite sweet, followed by a powerful malt-driven bitterness upon swallowing. M: Mouthfeel is smooth and lightly tingly, with soft carbonation and good body. Pretty astringent; dries the palate. Could be a tad creamier for the strength. Aftertaste of bitter roasted coffee, dark malt, chocolate, molasses, lactose, earthiness and faint stewed leaves. O: Excellent - a rich, complex imperial coffee porter that packs a punch. Looks good, while the aroma and flavour are stuffed with coffee, roasted malt and earthy yeast. Nice body; could be thicker. Goes down like a dream - a treat for the senses. Well worth sampling if you come across it.

Explodes with a five+ finger off-white head that fades leaving some lace. Hazy amber color with some yeast left in bottle. Strong carbonation and medium bodied. Citrusy and yeast nose, flavor is almost sweet citrus, Belgian yeast and a nearly clean finish. $2.95 for a 330ml bottle from Colonial Spirits Acton, MA.
Smell is nice but flavor is dry and bitter. Was hoping for some sweetness and Belgian yeast but it's not there.

Pours from the bottle an opaque dark brown with a voluminous, tan head that fades slowly, leaving plenty of lace. The aroma is led by roast coffee, dark chocolate and vanilla with touches of molasses, brown sugar and maple syrup. The taste is big and smooth. Medium-roast coffee, dark chocolate, vanilla, a hint of dark fruit. A slightly bitter, dry finish with a maple aftertaste and a hit of boozy warmth. Mouthfeel is creamy and smooth. Superb.

I know a lot of people are bagging this year's release, likely due to nostalgia factors in comparison to previous years as well as having so many more options available now. That said, there is an awesome depth of flavor present in this beer that changes as the glass gets lower and the beer warms. All the flavors seem well balanced without any one getting the higher hand.

Third time around and had it fresh. First time was 1 year old bottle and second was 2nd release on keg but a year old. Massive coffee up front. Better as warmed. Maple hard for me to find. Second bottle was much better all warm. I thought waiting bad at first but have another for next fall.

Pitch black in color with no penetration to light. There's an inch of thick, creamy brown foam on top. The aroma is dominated by a blend of sweet maple syrup and bitter dark coffee. There's also a bit of milk chocolate that comes out as it warms. The flavor is a blend of bitter, dark roasted coffee along with sweet maple syrup and a bit of smoke initially. The milk chocolate and bourbon seem to show as it warms. The mouth is sticky, chewy, and a bit warm with alcohol. There's so much going on here!
Pretty much a KBS... But with more maple. Excellent. Aged in maple barrels and it definitely comes through. 9/10.

Look jet black mocha head. Smell dark chocolate Rich nuts coffee and a hint of bourbon. Taste dark chocolate and coffee. Feel great mouth feel very rich oily and thick. Overall a pretty tasty beer a little too coffee for me but definitely full flavor. I would definitely say it's couple notches below Bourbon County though
Pours dark brown to black, sweet but full of coffee, and the bourbon comes through perfectly.

Dark brown color with really creamy mocha head. Aroma has deep chocolate and fudge notes with some light bourbon and toffee in the background. Taste is sweet at first with bourbon and toffee notes, very faint maple, bitter cacao and dark chocolate on the finish. Medium body with soft carbonation, drinks very smooth. As it warms it gets slightly boozy on the nose but overall it's a still a very smooth and easy drinking barrel aged stout.

1/8/17: $12.50 12 ounce draft pour into snifter at The Garage. Let this one sit for 15 minutes, felt a little to cold poured. Glad I did. Pitch black pour, slight tan head. Chocolate, bourbon and maple aroma, sweet but not overly sweet, very nice blend. Subtle and good bourbon taste, not overly strong but a not overwhelming, balanced with sweet chocolate, syrup and coffee. Excellent tasting beer, one of my favorites yet. Thin texture, nice body but not thick like similar offerings. Very smooth going down. I enjoyed this one over 30 minutes, very nice beer to slowly enjoy and savor. Overall, excellent offering, will save bottles and see how they aged down the road. I've liked Breakfast Stout and KBS, but didn't rate them as high when I first rated, will have to revisit.

Poured from a 750ml bottle into a speiglau BA glass. Look is pitch black with a thin espresso foam colored head. Aroma definitely holds all the components. Hints of roast malt, coffee, bourbon , and a hint of burnt maple syrup come through. Taste is smooth velvety and delicious. Absolutely fantastic Beer.

Serving Type: 16 Oz. Draught at The Lunar Rogue Pub in Fredericton, New Brunswick A- Pours a Deep Amber topped by a thin skin of off-white head. Minimal lacing. S- Bready and caramel maltiness paired nicely with dank hops. T- Grain and caramel malts along with the same dank hoppiness, perhaps a little more pronounced. M- Medium Mouthfeel with low carbonation. Dry body. O- A great sessionable ale from Picaroons. Very malty with a good dosage of hops. Goes great with a nice rack of ribs from the Lunar Rogue!

Bottle share, thanks to Jeremy. Not picking up the saison notes, coming off as more sour. Body seems right, but nose and flavor a bit off center. A boutique saison? Perhaps. I miss the cut and dried style definitions.

650ml bottle poured into a Deschutes teku glass. Enjoyed on 12.10.14, reviewed from Tasting Journal. The beer pours a peachy orange color, hazy with a nice two fingers of white, thick, soapy head that very nice retention that is easily summoned with a quick twirl of the glass but yields little lace. The aroma is quite nice, soft, fleshy fruit, mild funk, fruity yeast, wine barrel, brett with a touch of must and some cereal grain, nicely balanced. The flavors are right in line with the nose, plenty of fruit, fleshy light stone fruits, wine barrel, chewy oak, musty funk, soft grain, lightly bitter with a peppery finish, nice array of flavors that balance themselves quite well. The mouthfeel is good, lively, coating, nice carbonation with a general softness and creaminess at the finish that also feels lightly dry. Verdict: A very nice saison from Deschutes that showcases the barrel treatment quite well, very integrated without taking over and dominating the beer. Instead, it highlights the subtleties and adds to the complexity.

RB Rich hooked this one up... Waxed bottle with a flimsy brown paper label. Shared with COOPMatt and DerekA while chatting about the state of local breweries. Pours a hazy light orange.. good 1" head with nice retention and lacing. Nose is lightly bretty with apricot esters and some background bubblegum phenols. Really respectable Saison.. dry and light esters.. oak notes come with big hits of Oregon Pinot.. hints of barrel acidity on the finish ties things together. I REALLY want some cellar bottles. 3.5/3.75/3.75/4/4

Poured into a stange. The appearance was a dark pink/reddish color with a quickly dissipating little white semi-foamy head. No lace. The aroma had some red raspberries, currants, lemon notes and acidic grassy fruity features. The flavor blended the sour to the tart with a fruity underscore of raspberries, lemon and an ever so light strawberry. Slight acidic aftertaste of red raspberries and lemon with a super light touch of sour-ed wheat. The mouthfeel was between light and medium bodied with a fair in between quality of being sessionable and being a sipper. Good carbonation and ABV. Slight red raspberries and lemon-ish finish. Overall, to me, it's a nicely done fruited sour ale but not enough "sour-ed wheat" to call it a true Berliner weisse. I'd still have again.

Pours a hazy strawberry color, minimal head. Smells like tart raspberry. Tart with a little sweetness, I definitely taste the raspberry and currants, has a light sourness. Crisp and clean, maybe a little overcarbonated. Overall a very crushable beer that I will buy again. 8/6/18 16 oz can dated 10/17/17 4.25 rating

A: The beer is clear cherry red in color and has a slight amount of visible carbonation. it poured with a quarter finger high pink head that died down, leaving a collar around the edge of the glass. S: Light aromas of raspberry purée are present in the nose. T: The taste follows the smell and has flavors of raspberries along with notes of other berries such as blackberries with a light amount of sourness. M: It feels a bit more than being light-bodied and slightly creamy on the palate with a moderate amount of carbonation. O: I liked how this beer had lots of raspberry flavors without any of the associated acidity that you would normally expect. It is very easy to drink. Serving type: can

With a deep coffee-like flavor the Hubrew Jersey Milk Stout is a highly drinkable dark beer even for those who don't like dark beer. It was actually the Milk stout that brought me over to the "dark side." Honestly, it's my favorite beer. Bar none.

Look: Opaque hazy orange with a white head. Smell: Pungent fruit hops burst from the can. Notes of peach, pineapple, papaya, guava, and grapefruit dominate the nose. All hops. Taste: Thick juicy hops buckle the tongue with notes of peach, pineapple, grapefruit pith, papaya, and guava. This slowly fades to a honey biscuit malt with a lingering bitter pine as it finishes. Feel: Thick and juicy yet not abrasive. Light bitter on the finish and just a hint of alcohol on the finish. Very drinkable for the ABV. Overall: One intense IIPA. Big, juicy, and tongue buckling. Yet drinks way below its actual ABV. The flavors develop over the course of the sip adding an unexpected complexity that just adds to the beauty of this beer. It's not just juice it has a notable malt and layers to the hops. World class stuff.

On tap at Au Brasseur, Strasbourg, France A: The beer is jet back in color. It poured with a short beige colored head that quickly faded away, leaving a thin collar around the edge of the glass. S: Moderate aromas of chocolate malts and coffee beans are present in the nose. T: The taste follows the smell and has flavors of coffee and chocolate along with a slight amount of bitterness. M: It feels just about medium-bodied and a little thin on the palate with a moderate amount of carbonation. O: This is a really nice beer if you like chocolate and coffee. It just seems light on the palate. Serving type: on-tap

Wow. This beer starts off with and amazing pour, both in its coloration and it's beautiful head. Hazy, almost pastel orange colour. Appears practically radioactive. Screaming juicy and it doesn't disappoint. Strong blood orange aroma. Taste is well balanced. Oranges with a bit of peach. Not too sweet or acidic. Soft mouth feel with considerable body. A real thrill to drink this!

Can dated 07/20/16. Pours hazy pale yellow. Closely resembles grapefruit juice with a one-inch off-white head that remains as a cap on top and leaves strands of lace on the drink down. The smell is of fresh squeezed citrus juicy with some faint tropical fruit accents. The taste follows with juicy grapefruit and a hint of pine bitterness. Full texture. World class.

Of the half dozen or so Tree House offerings that I have had, I still think that this is my overall favorite. It looks beautiful in the glass, as do most all of their beers - appears as a hazy, golden pineapple with a bit of white head that leaves a very nice lacing as the beer goes down. Nose consists of tropical fruit and citrus along with notes of peach. Taste is similar but mixed with a touch of dank hops. That note of peach comes through in the taste as well and there are hints of pepper towards that finished that make me assume there's some Amarillo hops to this one, which is likely why I'm such a fan of this beer. Feel is as expected - smooth and slightly creamy. Overall, this is an excellent beer that I wish I could get consistently and IMO, the best of their "regular" offerings.

16 oz. can. 3 days old A- Cloudy orange juice looking with a fluffy white one finger head. Sticky lacing left after every sip. S- Apricot, peach, mango, pineapple. Throw in all the tropical fruits you can think of. Slightly resinous. T- Another fruit juice in beer form from Tree House. Mango, papaya, peach....you get the picture. Perfect amount of bitterness. Slight alcohol warming. Great stuff. M- Medium to full and smooth. Perfect amount of carbonation. Silky. O- Like all the Tree House IPA's I have tried, I love it. Recommended if you can get it.

Look: cloudy, golden orange with a thick creamy looking head Smell: citrus, floral, mango, orange, caramel, grapefruit Taste: Hop bitterness up front, fading to a floral finish with orange Feel: very oily, almost slick from the hop oils Truly a juicy, juicy Double IPA

From the 16 oz. can dated Aug 24, 2016. Sampled the same day on Aug 24, 2016. The pour is a hazy looking yellow color under a modest white foamy head. Lingering head. The aroma brings out orange, tangerine, peach, and citrus character mainly but there is still a worthwhile toasted bread and biscuit character worth mentioning. Zero booze for 8.2%. Medium to full body but so smooth. The peach jumps forward in the taste but is usurped by the other fruity character and toasted bread sweetness that hovers under it all. Mostly clean finish. Just delightful and worth waiting in line to grab one.

16 ounce can into tulip glass, canned on 9/28/2017. Pours slightly hazy ruby reddish orange color with a 1-2 finger fairly dense and fluffy light pink head with solid retention, that reduces to a minimal spotty lace cap that lingers. Slight spotty lacing on the glass, with a fair amount of streaming carbonation. Aromas of big juicy and lightly tart/tangy raspberries, red currants, fruit jam, lemon, pear, red apple, fruit skin/seeds, wheat, cracker, white bread, herbal, light lacto funk, and yeast earthiness. Very nice aromas with good balance and complexity of fruity/acidic yeast, raspberry/currants, and light-moderate moderate pale malt notes; with great strength. Taste of juicy and tart/tangy raspberries, red currants, lemon, pear, red apple, fruit skin/seeds, wheat, cracker, white bread, herbal, light lacto funk, and yeast earthiness. Light fruity/lactic tartness and fruit tang on the finish. Lingering notes of tart/tangy raspberries, red currant, fruit jam, lemon, pear, red apple, fruit skin/seeds, wheat, cracker, white bread, herbal, light lacto funk, and yeast earthiness on the finish for a good bit. Nice complexity, robustness, and balance of fruity/acidic yeast, raspberry/currants, and light-moderate pale malt flavors; with a nice malt/tartness and tangy fruit balance; with zero puckering/astringent flavors after the finish. Moderately crisp/clean finishing. Moderate increasing dryness from lingering tartness/fruit tang. Medium carbonation and light body; with a very smooth and fairly grainy/acidic/tangy/tannic balanced mouthfeel that is nice. Zero warming alcohol as expected of 3.8%. Overall this is a nice fruited Berliner weisse. All around nice complexity, robustness, and balance of fruity/acidic yeast, raspberry/currants, and light-moderate pale malt flavors; very smooth, crisp, clean, and refreshing to drink; with the mildly lactic/tangy/tannic finish. Better aromas than flavors. Nice jammy nose going on; but the flavors felt watered down and not as heavy on the berries as I hoped. Still has nice overall balance, and is a well made style example. A nicely enjoyable offering.

Mild fresh raspberry aroma with a hint of tartness, pours a clear red with a dusting of white head. Clean sour flavor, which fades out to raspberries. Light body and easy drinking, with just enough tartness to keep the flavor bright. A very enjoyable Berliner Weisse.

Quick hit. Let's go. Clear ruby color with no head or lacing. Jammy raspberry and blackberry on the nose. Little to no acid. Very sweet. Medicinal berry notes like generic hard candy. Not even remotely tart or acidic. Astringent aftertaste. Everything about it screams extract. Thin bodied, even for the style. This is my last Platform beer unless they seriously step it up. Just too underwhelming as a whole.

If this beer is retired then A) the beer I just drank is really old and B) it holds up well over time. It poured with minimal head and was translucent with a purple-ish color. I liked the sour berry taste.

Tall boy poured into a tulip. Pours an almost headless pomegranate color. The nose is straight sour (in that only-barely-funky kettle-sour kind of way) with elements of red berries. The palate opens with a clean sour taste that progresses into faint fruit notes (raspberry, strawberry, pomegranate). The funky sour taste here has no nuanced earthiness (not that any would be expected from a kettle-sour), but this leaves the palate feeling somewhat bland and one-dimensional. The fruit notes on this monochromatic background almost taste like they belong in a juice bag. Mouthfeel is moderately carbonated (though it could perhaps use a little more). Overall, another interesting experiment in the kettle-sour series, but another beer that falls prey to the same mistakes of its more recent predecessors in the series. Platform is a tremendous brewery doing interesting things at their taprooms, I only wish this series would showcase that talent more adequately.

Tasted on draft on 7/28/2010 Brewed with the same yeast strain that he used to produce his excellent Sunfire Saison back in June, this is a formidable beer, coming in at 10.75% ABV. True to the style, adjunct sugars were used to keep the body lighter than you would expect for such a strong brew. It was slightly cloudy in the glass, but the aroma spoke strongly of the Belgian yeast used, with plenty of earthy, spicy notes. On the palate it was smooth, with hopping robust enough to stand up to all this malt and alcohol.This brew is fantastic, so long as you remember to enjoy it in moderation, which can be tough, given how delicious it is. The beer is only for sale by the 6 oz glass; no pints or growlers.

16 oz bottle poured into a pint glass A: Pours a light red/light orange mix with a 1/2-finger head S: Red currant/raspberry, lemon and a hint of vinegar/herbs T: Matches the nose. Mouthwatering and refreshing M: Light-bodied, noticeable but not bracing acidity, crisp and refreshing O: A tasty, enjoyable beer

Pours golden in color with a purple/magenta tint to it. Smells sour, with subtle notes of berry. It's initial flavor is of either blackberries or raspberries with a fair amount of sour notes. It's definitely sour and tart, but not to an extreme. Finishes heavily salinic. By far the saltiest aftertaste I've ever experienced in a beer, even of this style.

Pours a pale opaque raspberry golden color. Aroma is tart raspberries. Flavor is a light tart ale with tart fresh raspberries. Has a clean refreshing finish. Overall this is delicious. I've had server all of thier beers an this is the most impressive to date.

Bottle: Poured a pitch-black color stout with a nice dark brown foamy head with good retention and some lacing. Aroma of coffee with nice maple and vanilla notes with some bourbon and plenty of residual sugar notes. Taste is a mix of bourbon and vanilla with coffee with some maple notes and some black chocolate notes with a ton of residual sugar notes. Body is full with oily texture and good carbonation with light warming alcohol notes. Very rich and decadent while retaining some good drinkability but maybe a tad too sweet at the end of the day.

A: Poured into a snifter to a deep black beer topped by a dense three finger tan head which fades slowly to a collar around the edge of the glass leaving some lacing S: Smells of coffee, chocolate, oak and roasted malts with a little maple T: Taste is coffee, dark chocolate, and a little roasted malt. Nice oak, light vanilla and a hint of caramel along with a nice undertone of maple throughout. Swallow is more oak, coffee, maple, chocolate, and some light caramel and vanilla. M: This beer is big and silky on the palate with a slightly velvety feel on the palate. Carbonation is on the low side and close to perfect for the style. O: Overall this is a very nice beer with some really great flavors and complexity. Easy to drink and alcohol is well hidden. Maple is a hard flavor to balance in a beer and this one seems to do pretty well. It's there but it doesn't dominate though if that is what people are expecting. Worth a try if you like the style and Founders.
This is a freaking tasty stout. There's a rich, delicious aftertaste to every sip of it. I really loved it!!
A slight notch above KBS, but need to know taste can vary pending batch. I have had both draft and bottle. Not overly sweet on draft that I had, but the bottle was a little sweeter than I care for.

A: Appearance is a dark brown/black color, essentially opaque. Nice brown head that fades slowly. S: The aroma contains strong notes of bourbon, barrel wood, and maple. T: The taste starts out semi-sweet with very well incorporated flavors of bourbon, chocolate, maple, and malt. The high ABV is barely noticeable and the aftertaste is muted, but great. M: Crisp and smooth, medium/full body, medium carbonation (I would have liked a little more), finish is slightly sticky. O: This beer doesn't deserve a review, it deserves a parade. There's nothing else I even want to say, just stockpile it, age it, drink it. Then repeat. I had the 2017 vintage and, while it was incredible when fresh, I'm certain that it will only improve with age.
Pours almost like a syrup. It's thick and rich in flavor. Definitely one of my favorites.

Enjoyed on draught in a snifter. Pours black, similar head to KBS. The maple and bourbon really compliment each other very well. Flavor was greatly enhanced once warmed up. Certainly worth the hype for me and I'm really glad I got to have some. I would really wish for it to be sold in 12oz.
Looks & smells great. On tap at Fog’s Pub. Can taste maple and booze. Not for the faint of heart. I’d rate just slightly below KBS. Taste improves as it warms up. Enjoy slowly!!

Given the score and the hype, I was a little underwhelmed. Thin tan head. Smells like breakfast. Pancakes and coffee. Wish the maple was more assertive. Mostly I just thought I'd rather be drinking Double Stack.
Best beer I have ever had!

Dad grabbed a bottle from a friend in parts unknown. First impression is...meh. Not bad, but not really knocking my socks off. Not head to speak of, slightly spicy taste, watery mouthfeel. It isn't bad. You have a malt presence, not so much hops. some presence of standard dunkle flavors. But.... it is just kindda....yeah. Not bad deal for free, but nothing I am going to hunt down

A: Brown/caramel color, cloudy. Weak head- vigorous pour netted barely one finger of head, which dissipated quickly into a light wring around the edges. Lacing is non-existent. S: very little aroma, I'm just not getting much there. a subtle hint of caramel is about all I'm picking up. T: A bit of caramel. Toasted malts. A hint of banana comes out as it warms, but just a subtle amount. M: surprisingly, given the lack of head, a carbonated fizz filled the mouth after the initial taste and pretty much consumed the flavor. Once the fizz eroded, the caramel/malt flavor lingers throughout. D: not bad. This is not a style I seek out on a regular basis, but this beer is at least interesting enough to encourage me to explore other examples. This beer is smooth and has just enough flavor to hold my attention through the full pint.

Poured into a 16 oz glass. A: Even on a very hard pour, little to no head at all. A mm cap on top, made of tiny little off white bubbles. Not impressive. Limited lacing as well. Color however was good, a deep dried oak leaf brown, with the classic hazy color of an weizen. S: Not too much on the nose, I am thinking I drank it a bit too cold. I do get some funky wet towel smells, wheaty dark malt and some apple aromas as well. T: Bready, yeasty with a bit of sour apple as well. Kind of funky and not really what I was expecting. A bitter after taste, I guess hops were in fact, added to this beer. Dominated by wheat malt however. M: Average on just about everything. Carbonation, body etc. D: Pretty drinkable. Didnt have the ABV on the bottle, but went down smooth. A bit strange for my liking, but not an awful beer.

On-tap over at Sebago's for their Full Moon Cask Night. Probably the first time Moat Mountain has been inside the state of Maine so it was quite the treat to try, even if I'm not the biggest fan of the style. Pours a light amber color, decent amount of head considering it's from the cask, no lacing. Smell isn't as strong with the smoke as I thought it would be (which is nice, it not being overpowering), the sweet malt melds nicely with an undertone of smoke. Taste has low carbonation, the smoked malt has a slightly larger presence than the aroma suggested but isn't overpowering and doesn't take of cigarettes, the light sweetness helps cut any harshness. Since it's not really my thing, I'm glad I only got a half pint, just makes me want to try more Moat Mountain though.

Look : Hazy, as the same says. Little bit dark but pretty similar compared to Julius. Aroma : this aroma is fucking crazy. Pure peach bomb from yeast, then tropical fruits from hops. Mouthfeel : medium-medium. Flavor : this is my second dipa from TH so its hard to tell, but they are all "boozy" and I dont like that. Trillium perfectly hides the alcohol taste, but this has a sharp alcohol taste at the start, other tastes are great thi. Overall : the booziness ruins everything, wish they make a regular version of this. Sad.

Another great beer from Treehouse. Similar to the Julius - very similar to me. Exotic flavors shine through - notes of fruit, mango, orange, rine - seems to be a staple with Treehouse. Tastes extremely similar to the Julius - smooth, refreshing, definite dankness to this one, hops shine through, but the fruit definitely is at the front of the flavors. The fruit blends in and is in balance with the malt backbone.. it all works - beautifully. All in all a great beer - didn't change my life, but was an amazing offering from Treehouse. Can't wait to have more of these and continue trying some different beers from Treehouse.

I tried this at the brewery. It poured an opaque dark with no head and no lace. The scent had chocolate tones. The taste was sweet molasses lean. The mouthfeel was fuller in body with subtle carbonation. Overall it's a decent stout.

275ml bottle poured into a white wine glass · Fridge temp · 2012 Appearance: Pours a pale straw color, 2" golden head with great retention. Smell: Ginger abounds, pilsner malts, no hop aroma. Very fresh smelling with lemon lime attributes as well. Taste: A light, crisp lager with ginger flavor. It's a shame the bottle says "ginger flavor" instead of the actual use of ginger. A quite tasty beer. Mouthfeel: Crisp, gingery, light, easy to drink. Overall: Not bad for what I expected. Could drink a lot of them.

Look: a wet red brick lathered in late autumn sunlight. Smell: distant camp fire at whose side unknown wanderers are barbecuing potatoes with the skins still on and toasting. woody resin also moves within and without the smoke. Taste: a near unfathomable ancient biscuit malt dying into a confused, dry citrus finish. the sweetness transits from molasses to sugar-augmented soy sauce, to mellow aged stone fruit. as time wears an occasional lingering salmon swims about. Feel: a little tickle despite the light cream texture. Overall: not my preferred genre at the moment, though I do appreciate the rapid evolution into variegated degrees of malt sweetness.

I bought this on a recommendation from my local beer shoo who I trust immensely and they were right on. I'm surprised this one has not received better reviews on this site. I probably would have thought this beer was a gimmick, but for the recommendation, but oh man, it's the real deal. It's not real carbonated, but it drinks nice and smooth. It's a red ale, but reminds me a little bit of a Belgium pale ale. Either way, do not let the Star Trek nod throw you. This beer is delicious

4/3.75/3.75/3.5/4 Look, I'll admit that I bought this pretty much entirely for the novelty. It was relatively cheap, and I love Star Trek, so I figured why not? The pour is a nice surprise: Ruddy amber body: appears crisp and clear. One and a half finger almond meat head dissipates eventually down to just a couple of cm, all the while leaving wonderful lacing down the edges. Nose is wonderfully caramel rich, some biscuits and some spicy... something? Can't quite put my finger on it. Definitely driven by the toasted caramel and biscuits. The pleasant surprise continues Starts out more green than expected based on style and aroma, but considering the blood of its namesake.. Sweet toffee and caramel greet the crisp... green-ness (almost kind of vinous, maybe somewhat leafy?), dominating most of the malt profile, which is the driving force in this brew. There's some biscuit stuffiness, but it's definitely sweeter than most red ale's I've had (admittedly not that many). Fairly crisp, and a bit of leafy hops continue through the finish. The stale-type biscuit malts are present, but the sweet greens and toffee really drive this thing. I bought this because it was cheap and, hey, Star Trek (DS9>TNG>TOS>VOY>TAS>ENT. Though Voyager and Animated could easily flip flop. Don't hate. JJs 'Lens Flare: The Remake!' don't count for these purposes). I expected fizzy stale water, but what I got was a pleasant surprise. This is not a GREAT beer by any means, but it is much more drinkable and enjoyable than I was anticipating. Reds are not a style I'm generally that into, and this one is sweeter than any others that I've tried. Maybe that's why I like it. Whatever it is, I'd drink it again, though probably won't again any time soon.

Poured into a Seattle Beer Week pint glass. Pours a medium red-orange amber with a half finger of light tan head that dissipates to patches, with light lacing. Aroma of caramel malt, tea, mild citrus, a bit vegetal with a mild spiciness, almost like a light winter warmer. Flavor is a spicy biscuit and caramel malt with the same tea-like components in the aroma, light apple juice and berries, finishing with light grassy hops. Medium bodied. A pleasant enough red ale, not quite an Irish red, the fruit flavors are kind of unbalanced with the malt, leaving a slightly odd overripe fruit element. Drinkable, but not fascinating, doctor. I'm not sure what Spock would think of it. Vulcans are split between teetotalism with some drinking port and brandy. Perhaps not model beer drinkers.

I've never watched more than 30 seconds of a Star Trek episode or movie so Vulcan Ale is a missed opportunity as far as cheesy puns or dorky sci-fi jokes go. But I will say this: its head certainly does *not* live long nor prosper; it fizzles out at light-speed pace. And the relatively bright, clear amber ale is nowhere near deep or dark enough to pass as a final frontier. This so-called "mind-melding good" ale has a merely so-so aroma, one comprised of only moderate maltiness and just a very general toffee-like flavour. It's lightly toasty and lightly buttery but, unlike my morning breakfast, isn't exactly something one would wake up craving for. The taste, however, does contain a pleasant nuttiness; notes of pecan and filbert beg for milk chocolate (even if this malty profile sticks to caramel sweetness). There are flavours of buttered toast and honeycomb toffee yet the finish is dry and tastes of smoked biscuits. Though Irish by birth and in name, that country can't really lay claim to the style's best. In fact, my favourite examples hail from America and they're amped up with piny, resinous hops - but that was not done here. This is no-frills, just basic caramel malt flavor and dry roasty finish. While I hate to generalize, Irish Red Ales are rarely glamorous and, what's more, Vulcan Ale is far from the style's most impressive example. Unless you're the most die-hard of Star Trek geeks I don't know that this even warrants collectors item status. This mundane ale is very much of this planet - there's nothing remotely out-of-worldly about it.

0% 473 mL can from the LCBO served slightly chilled; no freshness info. An Irish Red Ale would not have been my first guess as the Vulcan libation of choice, but it definitely sounds more appealing than that crappy lager with the blue food colouring that the Romulans have been passing off as beer. This ale pours a ruddy, ruby-amber colour, topped with two fingers of fluffy, off-white head that recedes at a steady pace over the next period of minutes. A dense, lumpy cap and collar are the eventual result, alongside some messy lacing. It definitely looks the part, but the aroma is not really what I expect from this style. Candied orange, lemon, caramel sweetness and some bready malts come through, with a note of pineapple as well (which is far more noticeable off the can than the glass). Fascinating. A little less fruity than the aroma let on, with the malt backbone boldly going where I wasn't really expecting it to. Slightly bready, with caramel, roasted malts and toasted nuts coming through prominently. Notes of red apple and berries are next, with the hop bill providing an adequately enjoyable blend of earthy, leafy, and grassy bitterness that rounds out the profile. An earthy, almost dirty aftertaste with some lingering bitterness and toasted grain sweetness. Medium-bodied, with moderate carbonation and a fairly smooth feel on the palate. While it would be illogical to call this a bad beer, it would seem overly exuberant to claim the opposite. Final Grade: 3.4, a B-. As soon as I spotted this can on the shelves, my internal sensors detected a strong probability that Vulcan Ale was nothing more than a cash grab aimed at fans of the long-running franchise. Given the fact that there are several other 'Vulcan Ales' being contract brewed elsewhere, I can't really doubt my initial gut instinct, but this particular edition is at least a serviceable red ale with a nice hop twist. I wouldn't buy it again at this price point (3.40 per can), but there's nothing wrong with the beer itself so I'd certainly say it's worth at least one try whether you're a Trek nerd or not.

This was my 2018 New Years beer. Beautiful blackish brown with a beautiful brown head and curtain lacing. Wonderful chocolate-coffee smell. Taste is multi-faceted with dark coffee, chocolate, vanilla, dark berries, and a comforting sweetness. Very smooth and velvety feel. A great beer for a celebration!

Without a doubt one of the best. Split 750ml bottle with a friend over dinner and cards. Served in snifters. Chilled to 38 degrees. Sweeter than some stouts, but not too much. Can taste the maple and chocolate. Barrel flavors too of woody oak and bourbon. Slight alcohol taste but not overpowering. Deep flavors and smooth dark color. Second round of tasting had more to offer....maybe because of overloading on senses and tounge. This is clearly worth the hype and should b on the bucket list for true craft beer lovers. I was fortunate to acquire 42 bottles in less than two weeks through rapid travel and an extensive network of friends and lucky timing. These will age well. I will wait a couple months before cracking open another.

Split a 750ml bottle two ways - highly enjoyed by both drinkers. A maple beer that I could actually taste the maple syrup as opposed to sugary sweet molasses. Perfect beer for this blast of frosty weather, for sure. Super high marks for being a big barrel aged stout that actually generates and holds a head. Black body beneath a sturdy cap of mocha-chocolate froth. Bravo! Aroma is warm and comfy - roasted malt, dark chocolate, char, coffee grounds and maple syrup. Simultaneously roasty, bitter and sweet. Light on the coffee. Hint of burnt sugar and molasses. Taste is dark chocolate, bitter bakers chocolate, light roast coffee and sweet maple syrup. Beautiful cascade of flavors and meld perfectly on the palate. Never cloying but it gets sweet on the backend. Thick and chewy and smooth - a real mouthful of a beer. Warmth from the alcohol with a kiss of booze. Great experience.
Black Friday 2017 @ Lincoln Fillstation - Well that is certainly not Dudley Do-Right astride the horse and this is a beer not to be missed. Well brewed, great balance, lots going on!

Thick head that is the color of khaki/caramel. Wish it would've been a little darker as far as the head. But beautiful thickness that sticks around. Nose is sweet bourbon! The bourbon and the maple are bouncing off each other perfectly. Taste follows up the nose perfectly with maple and bourbon. I'm picking up HUGE chocolate notes. And MOCHA. This is perfectly balanced. That bourbon is just in there to help everybody else out, not taking the spotlight from anything. The feel is thick. It stays around in the mouth for a good time after it's gone. Doesn't have a burn at all to it. But it is warming. Once again perfectly balanced on this side. Overall, this is everything I wanted it to be. I was hoping the head would be a little darker but that didn't matter at all once you got into it for the nose and taste. This did not disappoint at all, even with the HUGE expectations that I had for it. Really glad I got to enjoy this brew and would drink it whenever I had a chance to. Great brew!
Excellent

I was fortunate to obtain a good amount of the 2017 vintage of this beer. After drinking multiple pours on tap and several bottles, I have to conclude this beer is bliss in a bottle..You crack open a 750ml bottle and take your time with it.. CBS is a perfect balance of chocolate, coffee, bourbon barrel and maple.. All flavors make their presence known..But one does not dominate over the other. Once this beer warms, you get the absolute harmony that Founder’s Brewing intends.. This balance means CBS lives up to the hype and will exceed expectations. CBS might be the BEST stout I’ve ever consumed. And it may be the best overall beer I’ve ever consumed. It’s that good and that rewarding.. Cheers!...

Poured from a bottle from the 2017 release A: Deep Mahogany, no light shines through. The head is 2 fingers of a thick foamy tan S:Maple syrup, Bourbon roasted coffee T: Chocolate, Maple, walnuts, coffee, Bourbon, a char finish MF: Thick and creamy like an ice cream sundae. O: A wonderful amalgamation of flavors. I've waited quite a while to try this and it doesn't disappoint.

Look 4.25 poured a deep dark color into a tulip glass Smell 4-a hint of sweetness on the nose Taste 4.75-Just awesome on of the best in a long time, a bit of sweetness from the maple syrup but very well balanced Feel 4.5- The mouth-feel is full without being overly heavy Overall 4.5- This is just good, no complaints here. A bit more aroma might help but on the whole it just works. 4.48 rDev -4.1%

750 ml bottle- Pours black with a large mocha colored head with excellent retention. Aroma is chocolate, vanilla, milk duds, caramel, a bit of bourbon, but just slight. The taste is similar, milk duds, vanilla, toffee, caramel, velvety and smooth, delicious. Would love to compare with KBS.
Amazing beer

Finally able to try this landmark brew on tap on a cold December, 2017 night at the Gerst Haus in Evansville, IN after about a half-hour line. 8 ounces in a snifter, from draft. Appearance: Black. Pitch. As the night. Aroma: Plenty of vanilla and maple here, alongside some chocolate and coffee notes. Really just a “wow” on the nose. Taste: Sweet maple up front with touches of warm bourbon and vanilla. Not overly boozy, amazingly, this one sips really wonderfully with an ideal blend of chocolate, coffee, and maple. Just a beautiful beer that I’d buy weekly if I could. Easily qualifies among my favorite beers of the 2000-ish I’ve tried.
Great Beer! I'd put it in between a traditional brown ale and stout because of the heavier mouthfeel and hefty use of chocolate malts.
Better than I expected. I guess I’m just spoiled living on the west coast. Drinkable but nothing compared to the offerings out west.
The North Country of New York has a lot to be desired, much like this beer.
So good. Cinnamon then vanilla nice. At original h&s brewery.
Sample from the Granite State Brewers Festival 7/25/15 Big rich bready sweet light caramel maltiness with barely enough spicy floral hops to counter, light alcohol notes.

1ST Sept 2012: hand pulled pints (three) in the Wetherspoons in Hereford. Dull golden body with a mini-haze in each pint: white head which varied from full to thin depending on who pulled the pint! Fruity hops with lemon/citrus hints hit my nose, the aromas carried on into the taste with the same flavours being prominent also. There is a malty content, but it is hidden by the hops which also add a slight bitterness and dryness to the mouth feel. OK without being great: I had three pints because there was nothing else worth having on my visit to this pub.

Pours a hazed golden color with a white head. Smell was fruity with loads of oranges. Taste was very orange juice like with som pineapple and mango. Mouth feel citrus forward with slight bitter finish. This was straight up juice.
Pours a very hazy yellow orange color with a medium white head on top. Has a very citrus hoppy smell to it. Tastes like orange juice with a very small hint of hops.

On-tap at Daiquiri Deck, Sarasota, FL A: The beer is clear amber yellow in color and has a light amount of visible carbonation. It poured with a thin white head that died down and left some patches of bubbles on the surface and a narrow collar around the edge of the glass. S: Moderate aromas of grapefruit are present in the nose. T: The taste follows the smell and has lots of flavors of grapefruit. M: It feels medium-bodied and slightly crisp on the palate with a moderate amount of carbonation. O: This IPA is all about the grapefruit. It smells and tastes like fresh sliced grapefruit. Serving type: on-tap

Slightly hazy coppery golden color with a frothy creamy head, persistent, lacey; Nice citrusy bouquet; Smooth sparkly mouthfeel; Surprising flavor, quite unusual. After sipping for a while, I decided that I don't much care for the odd flavor. From the can - looks good, smells good, feels good, doesn't taste good. Yes, it is grapefruit juice beer.

Had this beer on tap at Motorworks Brewing Company and it was fantastic! I was very excited to find a 6-pack at a local store but this beer tastes very different out of the can. On tap it had the hop bitterness mixed with the sweet taste of grapefruit. From the can, this beer still had the bitterness from the hops but the sweetness was gone. It was more of a soured grapefruit taste.
Goddamn

2017 release. Very dark brown in color with a nice mocha colored foam head. Slight streaks of lacing line the edges. Chocolate, coffee, toffee caramel sweetness and slight maple on the nose. Now, wow, that taste! So flavorful and robust with flavors of caramel sweetness complimented by the maple flavored coffee infused chocolate. The feel is more of a medium but I find, for me, this helps the taste instead of a thick feel leaving a greater impression. Over hyped? Over priced? Maybe, but expectations were meet so no complaints from me! Overall, world class for a reason and I'm very glad to have indulged upon this beast. Well crafted and please do enjoy!

Pours deep black with nice light mocha head. Aroma is chocolate, coffee with very slight maple. Taste is the def high point for this beer. Nice chocolate coffee beer with sweetness of the maple syrup shining at the end . No booziness at all with this. Mouthfeel is solid but I would it if this was just a little thicker. I liked this beer very much, but I def preferred bourbon county and morning wood to this. When I pay $30 for a bottle I expect just a little more.

Look: Pours black with a tan head Smell: Incredible smell, lots going on here. Bourbon and vanilla, chocolate, coffee Taste: Very well balanced with the bourbon, chocolate and coffee. Didn't get much maple until it warmed, then the sweetness from the maple syrup lingered. Mouthfeel was rich and smooth. Overall: This is a great beer. So well balanced. A lot of things going on but nothing is overpowering. Taste definitely changes as it warms.

So i Don't usually like anything barrel aged. But this is an exception. Nose is chocholate and maple sweetness wth a tinge of barrel in there. Looks like most stouts. Feel is slick and coating. The taste follows the nose with nice coco and toffee with mingling maple and just a twinge of burbon. Mouthfeel makes this slide down and not a lot of booze noted. The subtle burbon notes makes this beer very drinkable to me. The overpowering barrel prescence in most BBA stuff is offputting to me but this hits the sweet spot. 32 bucks a bottle may be steep but im glad to have tried it.
Favorite beer.
So complex and decadent. Equally appealing to the nose and palate. A remarkable brew and easily the best I have had from Founders. Worth the hype.

22 ounce bottle poured into a snifter A: Pours black with a mocha colored head that was full and creamy, very little carbonation, lots of mocha colored lacing, no head retention as it dissipated into a mocha colored soapy film. A: Smells like KBS, bourbon, toasted coconut, vanilla, chocolate, coffee, not getting any of the maple, hint of alcohol along with dark roasted malts, nice aroma. Like KBS, the barrel, chocolate, and coffee are well balanced. T: Taste follows the nose with bourbon, oak, toasted coconut, vanilla, chocolate, coffee, dark roasted malts, hint of maple that underlies the beer throughout but then reemerges in the finish and lingers with a touch of sweetness, lots of depth and complexity, more so as the beer warms. M: Full bodied, very little carbonation, very smooth mouthfeel with a chocolate and coffee like dry finish. O: I'd made several quick trips to my local bottle shops when I found out this had hit my local stores, missed each time, then I finally found it. It's a very tasty beer but it tastes like KBS with a touch of maple syrup, while it adds another layer of flavor, it's not another layer that would make me discard KBS in favor of CBS, both are world class and I'd be happy enough to find KBS or CBS, at least one yearly but I would not chase CBS again.

Reviewed on 12/4/17, from notes L - Pours like dirty motor oil with a fluffy mocha head and good retention. S - I get a good mix of coffee roast and sweet maple syrup aromas. They are subtle though. T - The flavors start of sweet. But not really a maple syrup sweet. Kind of a turbino sugar sweet. In the middle there is a bit of bourbon bite with vanilla and the maple comes forward a bit. Finishes with a medium roast coffee and a lingering sweetness. F - Not the most dense beer by far, but it has a nice creamy mouth feel. A little sticky. O - This is a subtle beer with descent balance. Everything is there, but you've got to really slow down and look for it. Very drinkable. There is a sugary sweetness throughout the sip. Certainly not a maple bomb.

Smells like that classic sweet malt that founders seems to use in all their stouts (the malt i cant not hate), smells boozy, slight maple and faint chocolate. Taste follows suite but as it warms the chocolate is pretty heavy which is awesome, more booziness also comes out as it warms of course. Looking for some coffee but not getting any. Very balanced, hands down my favorite stout from founders unfortunately since ill prolly never have it again.

Canned 8/3. Consumed 8/11. A: Pours out a bright golden orange. Sits completely opaquely in the glass, a murky and turbid yet still vibrant heavily burnt orange. S: Tons of orange. Spritzy OJ mixed with pithy, astringent orange pith. Tropical and stone fruit undertones—peach, passionfruit, mango. Bit of grassy dankness as well. Significant backing of sweet white-bready malt. T: Sweet, delectable citrus juice up front. Orange with tons of lemon and lime throughout. Explodes off the tongue initially, but succumbs relatively quickly to a milder assortment of tropical fruits—papaya, peach, passionfruit. An herbaceous and bitter finish combats any noticeable sweetness from the malts, imparting a well-balanced and almost cocoa powder-esque quality to the finish. M: Rich and luscious, very reminiscent of the feel on Green. Bubblegum yeastiness hints at a milkshake-esque feel. A bit more bitter—though more floral than piney or astringent—on the finish, but a welcome bitterness in its balance of the sweet, doughy malt that sits further in the foreground on Haze than it does in other TH brews. It's not quite as thick and full as Green, but it's pretty close. O: Up there with anything else I’ve tried from Tree House. Haze pops in both the flavor and aroma categories, packing a punch of orange juiciness that is pretty much unrivaled in its intensity. I’ve heard Haze aptly described as a fusion of some of the defining characteristics of Julius and Green, and I totally see this. It embodies an amped up version of Julius’ orange qualities while mirroring the mid-mouth doughy bubblegum flavor and herbaceous bitter finish of Green. It’s really hard to find anything wrong with this beer, and I’d gladly drink it over pretty much anything else I’ve ever had. Damn near perfect.

16 oz. can dated 8/3/16. Poured into 18 oz. Belgian ale glass. L: 2F+ typical Treehouse head with long retention, lacing, cap, and ring. Beer is hazy orange juice color. Don't leave it around your kids :) S: It smells wonderful from 4 feet away. Closer in, you get orange, grapefruit, pineapple, and peach. There's also an earthiness on the back end that seems to be part of all Treehouse beers (something in the water in Monson?) T: Just a juicebomb: orange, grapefruit, pineapple, peach, lime up front with a dank earthy finish. This is really very nice. I do get a tiny bit of alcohol heat on the finish. F: Medium body, light to medium carbonation. Good drying on palate. Very solid construction and balance. O: Would be really hard for me to choose between this and Julius if I had to. I tend to go with the DIPAs over the IPAs when pressed, but both are so good. It's no wonder they blazed through 1200 customers the day I got these cans.

Like many Tree House beers, its somewhere between yellow and orange and 'hazy' as hell. There is always this slightly creamy head as well. Beautiful. Aroma: enormous tropical fruit flavors. pineapple, papaya, mango, all kinds of citrus there as well. Taste: this one certainly has some bite to it. grapefruit, papaya, citrus, even some faint peach. Feel: medium with some chew to it,

L.currently drinking from the gorgeous can S. Cracked the ta NB a m d enjoyed a summer reminder of why this is my favourite season T I am currently nursing my last sips of so far my favorite TH brew. A s much As I enjoyed Julius,sap,green and very green, I just am amazed by the light finish. Ken will be lucky to get what I owe him O.As I have had Lawson's Sos both canned and luckily on tap I can't call this m y favorite but definitely top 5

I think Haze has overtaken Julius as my favorite from the "regular offerings". It just has everything. Look is like any other IPA from TH. The smell and taste is tropical fruits but has an explosion of pineapple and grapefruit half way through swallowing it. The slight dankness and bitterness at the end makes this beer so refreshing. Feel is easily my favorite from TH as it coats slightly better than the other 3 (Julius, Green, and Alter). Overall, my favorite regular offering nowadays but Julius is a close second. A must trade for IMO.
Bright wit with a touch of melon. low ABV and perfect option for a hot Paris afternoon. Nice carbonation.

hazy ipa is obviously their thing here at finback, they make or have made about a million of them, and while sometimes they are not all that different, they are almost always amazing. case in point, this one right here, softly hazy, white frothy headed, mostly dry hopped, simcoe and amarillo, we have all heard that before somewhere, but this one is just better than most of them, near masterful execution, is round feeling without being expressly malty, the combination of the two hops is awesome, they highlight the best parts of each other yet retain their unique identities in aroma and in flavor, and it ends u-p being really fresh and easy drinking for what it is, nice balance from the starchy malt and the bitterness thats allowed to exist. a cryo sort of concentrated hoppiness too, almost candied for a second, but never sweet, melon and pine, fresh as can be, simple beer really all said and done, but of an extremely high quality that others should aspire to. i keep being impressed by these guys every time i track down one of their beers!
Not a big nose, but equal parts coffee chocolate and maple, delicious!!!
On tap at Cask and Vine in Derry, NH. Black color, no head. Aroma had some maple, touch of chocolate, no bourbon and no coffee. Flavor followed suit exactly. Way overpriced, give me a KBS any day.

Tried a 5 oz draft pour at lowes foods into a sh!tty plastic cup: Look: pours nice and black, purty brown head, thin but nice. Just a lil bit of lacing Smell: kind of lacking. Some good espresso and dark chocolate going on. Touch of maple pancakes but very muted. Overall kind of muted, was expecting it to smell sweeter Taste: espresso and dark chocolate right away. Touch of maple, but i almost have to try and taste it. Definitely a bourbon note as your nose goes in while sipping. Really good. Overall: really good but damn sure not worth the price. Expecting thicker with more heat and flavor and complexity. i honestly liked founders kbs and bs a lot more. Considering it was a dollar an ounce, i will pass if seen again. I enjoyed a 5 oz cbs for 6 bucks then walked out with a lagunitas imp stout bomber for 4 bucks... First review in the books!

I've had CBS maybe about a half dozen times before, at fests and bottle shares. I've never written a review before, because I either never drank enough of it or else my pallete when wrecked when I drank it. What I did have, however, was good enough to make me want to actively seek out several bottles from its recent, long-awaited re-release. It pours like a fresh, fizzy RIS. Very dark black, full body, wispy light head. Smells... more like a regular old RIS, and not nearly as maple-y as I recall. Smooth okay barley, strong and alcoholic but with big chocolate and minimal burn. Tastes, again, not nearly as maple-y as I recall. Still very good, though. Chocolate and light maple up front, sharp alcohol in the middle, and a finish of caramel, alcohol, and light bourbon. The maple is most present in the finish.
