Pours a nice golden yellow with a white frothy head into the tulip glass. Smell is hoppy - piney and citrus fruit, with a syrupy sweet Belgian malt character. Some molasses and brown sugar behind the hops on the nose. This beer goes down wayy too nicely for being 13%. Bubbly, but with a syrupy smooth mouthfeel going down. Sweet, but not cloying given the abv. The fruity hoppiness is balanced well by the candy-like Belgian malt, giving this beer a very juicy character. A very nice quad with an interesting twist on the American hops. Tastes like a Belgian imperial IPA. A real treat of a beer.

I tried this on tap at Federal Taphouse served chilled in a glass. The color is a beautiful golden with thick white head with fine bead and mild hazed clarity. The smell is very fragrant with both hops and yeast phenollics with a citrus/tropical odor and slight malt in the nose with sweet aroma. The feel is a little odd -full bodied with moderately sweet texture yet moderately bitter with lower than average carbonation for a belgian style -resinous with a semi-sweet finish w ith slight alcohol and bitterness lingering The taste has the hop profile of an American IPA yet there is certainly belgian yeast flavor there with a depth of malt that is not quite bready or sweet but there is a noticeable alcohol presence in the taste. This is a strange mash-up of Belgian Quad and American IPA/Strong ale that has to be tasted to be understood -it has a good amount of hop flavor but as far as the style of Quad goes it really only has the belgian yeast/alcohol in common with that. I liked it for what its worth.

March 2015 bottle served in a tulip glass at cellar temps. Appearance: nice artwork of a hop cone on the label. The beer looks much more like a tripel over a "traditional" quad. The color is a pale amber with a thin wisp of white foam on the surface. Plenty of carbonation from the glass and the cork gave a very satisfying pop when pulled. Nose: dank hops, fruity and strong. Very tropical, mango, pineapple, citrus, lemony, oranges, ripe fruit. Some alcohol. Taste: very hot and strong although it drinks very light for a 13% atom bomb. The tropical hops carry through to the finish. The beer is on the thinner side of things but it is nice. Crisp and fruity finish. Overall: what an interesting offering from Victory. Not at all a traditional quad but very enjoyable in the end. Because of the hop character I'd say that they want this one to be drank fresh however I do believe it will stay a while in the cellar. Very nice beer.

Purchased at shop at Victory brewing in Downingtown, can’t find the price info Undated 25.4 oz cork and caged bottle at 42 degrees, pops when opened, into snifter, allowed to warm to 50 degrees then to 55 degrees in hopes that some quad character will finally come out. Aroma – very weak Head average (Four cm, aggressive pour), off white, frothy, diminishing to three mm ring and very thin layer Lacing fair – narrow partial rings of tiny bubbles, mostly broken and drooping Body light gold, slight chill haze which disappears as it warms, slight effervescence Flavor – not much. Sweet, sugary, some hoppiness, no caramel, no maltiness, no yeast phenolics, no alcohol Palate full, syrupy, lively carbonation Appearance 3.25, Aroma 3.25, Flavor 3, Palate 4, Overall 3.5

Large bottle, caged and corked, and I could find no bottling date/freshness info Pours lightly hazed lighter amber, off white head is all fluffy and large to start, then going to a thicker film, collar and respectable strands and bits of lace left on the glass. Lots of lime and biting hop juices on the nose This a hop bomb with loads of lime, oranges and hop oils. Looks and tastes like a DIPA...a fresh, bold tasting and thoroughly hop infused DIPA, not really getting where the "Belgian Quad moniker fits in here....but I kike it

Look: Opaque jet black with a thick khaki head. No activity is visible. Smell: Rich fudge brownies, smooth bourbon, vanilla, espresso bitterness, and pronounced alcohol. Taste: Bourbon soaked fudge brownies on the attack. Then comes a decadent body of vanilla extract, espresso, dark chocolate, and a bit of oaky char. The finish is lightly bitter coffee notes with a smooth but pronounced alcohol. There is only a hint of maple on the end of the body. Feel: Thick. Sweet and oily. Big bodied. Smooth big booze. Mildly bitter roasty notes. Soft carbonation. Palate coating. Overall: A decadent dessert stout. KBS is a world class beer and seeing as the maple syrup is what sets this apart its a bit too subtle. However this is still basically KBS and it’s just as beautiful.

Tried on tap so I didn't have to open the big bottle if I felt like it needed aging. Glad I did as I will now be aging the two I got. Don't get me wrong, this is an excellent beer, as many reviews point out. But I expected a little more maple. My hope is that the bold-enough coffee flavor will tone down a bit and the maple sweetness will be enhanced. I'll let you know next fall!

2017 year as with any coffee beer, best drank very fresh. Thick black appearance with two fingers of head that slowly settles leaving behind plenty of lacing. Disappointing aroma and it is very weak. I do pick up notes of coffee, roasted malt, and faint booze. The beer picks up in the flavor however. I get bitter chocolate, vanilla, coffee, faint bourbon, and then the maple syrup adds flavor and sweetness in the finish. I definitely would of liked more bourbon notes in the beer as it is barely distinguishable. When the maple syrup comes through in the finish you also notice the effects it has on the body. Thick and luscious mouthfeel. Nice soft carbonation. A very good beer but hardly mind blowing or being a quintessential beer in todays market.
2017 bomber: Nice. All flavors are in harmony. Mouthfeel a bit thin. Alcohol well hidden. Sweetness is perfect. Not quite worth the hype or price but almost. Glad i tried but won’t buy again at $28.

On tap at The Three Monkeys in nyc. Tight dark head and good lacing. Sticky fluid clubs almost as much as the foam. Dark liquid suck in light and never lets go. Nose carries such a message of aromas that are so well integrated it's a deep puzzle separating them. Coffee hits first with an underlay of chocolates. Plural. Milk and bakers. Roasted malts and burnt sugars. Light maple. A hint of barrel. Earthy hops. Taste is a follow-up. Sweet and complex. Coffee, chocolate, maple. Bourbon gives light but firm kisses. Faint oak and cherries. Finish is mildly bitter and somewhat shorter and cleaner than I would expect for such a big beer on this style. A mild nuttiness lingers with the touch of maple and bourbon. Feel is the benchmark for this style. Thick and creamy while remaining light and supple. You almost don't want to swallow out feels so good in your mouth. But you do and you love it. This is possibly the best imperial stout I've had. It's that good. It's certainly in my top five. Outstanding!

So here it is, the legendary CBS in my possession at last. Put in fridge for 20 mins then served in snifter: Look is beautifully dark with a thin enticing lacing. The smell is maple and bourbon. But flavors are of bourbon, maple, chocolate, vanilla, caramel, coconut, toffee, coffee, oak, and hops. The maple isn't in your face as it comes from the barrel,and it's like it's brewed in a barrel that brewed FBS, KBS, maple syrup, CBS, and then Bliss hot sauce; can sort of sense it. It's almost like it got brewed in a barrel that has had its extended use. Great beer, but I'd prefer KBS. It has similarity to KBS with added maple but with staler bourbon although the bourbon in it is still delicious just seems a bit stickier vintage than in KBS. Either way glad to have tried it. I'd also suggest forget about the 20 mins in fridge just serve room temperature as long as you don't live in warm climate as it gets better the more it sits. It is easily drinkable, heavy feel yet super smooth, soft, and silky. It's worth trying at least once.

This beer pours an opaque cloudy burnt orange with a golden hue when held up to the light. The head is dense, 2 fingers and bright white. Retention is excellent and there are intricate patterns of webbed lacing all over the glass. Smell is orange, grapefruit, pineapple and dankness. Absolutely incredible. Taste is the same with a bit of bitterness on the finish. Feel is light side of medium, soft and juicy with a sticky finish. Overall this beer is absolutely immaculate. The best double IPA I've ever had by a pretty wide margin.
Oldest bar in America Bell in hand, had to get the bell in hand ale. A rich amber color, this beer was delicious! you can drink this stuff all day.
Good. Pub exclusive. When in Boston must try. Pairs well with the Sam Adams burger.

Pours crystal clear and pale, with a rocky head that dissipates with some spots of lace. Nose is quite grainy, and not much hops coming through. Certainly expecting a typical euro lager at this point. Taste is clean and simple. No off flavors or skunk, so that's a plus. Overall, a decent beer that you could certainly drink if you're out and there are no good options.

Hand-pulled half-pint during the 34rd Telford Beer Festival (Crown Inn Oakengates) on 4 May 2013. Amber, dry and hoppy with a malt fruity hint throughout. Looked good in the glass, poured in fine condition and tasty. Pleasant mixed bag of aromas and character, nice blend of flavours, a well made beer: I like this breweries products.

Had on tap at the Bell in Hand Tavern in Boston, right off the freedom trail. Appeared clear, light amber with very thin lace head. Smelled of light tones of citrus and hops. Had a light sweetness first taste with the citrus, caramel and hops and finished with a bitter tone. Poignant feel, sharp yet smooth. Overall a disappointment given the pomp and circumstance of being the official beer of the "oldest tavern in America". Hopefully this was not the premiere beer back in the day of the founding fathers!

L - Rusty orange/copper color. Murky body. A finger of white head. S - Sweet and resinous. Sweet hops, pine. Some booze. T - Equally sweet and hoppy. More pine. Hop resins and oils. Solid amount of sweet citrus with acidity. F - Syrupy, but has enough carbonation to movie it. Warming on each sip. O - Really good TIPA. Flavorful and not too intimidating.

Drank from a 1 pint can purchased at Mystic Brewery, Chelsea, MA 02/16/2018 Served in a tulip Outstanding appearance. The cloudy, apricot colored body was topped by a finger-tall, super tight and creamy, eggshell colored crown. Fantastic lacing. Drippy rings and streaky patches trickled down the sides of the glass and stuck around until the beer was finished. The aroma was solid but less exciting than I anticipated initially. Citrus was most apparent. Juicy orange notes dominated. Some tangerine too. Bit of honey-like sweetness. As the beer sat, the nose really intensified. Big melon notes appeared. Cantaloupe came through strong. Loads of honeydew as well. Dank, weedy notes were also detectable. Touch of peach and nectarine. The flavor profile was really hoppy and fairly sweet. Big citrus hop presence. Juicy orange notes came through strongest. Some candied orange peel perhaps as well. Peach notes were also apparent. The beer was anchored by a rich, sweet, malty backbone. With time, melon notes appeared and really intensified. Loads of cantaloupe and honeydew. Touch of peach. There was a dank, weedy quality too. The beer finished with more candied orange peel, a hint of bitterness and a kiss of alcohol. Nice rich, fuller bodied mouthfeel. Slightly syrupy. Creamy and slick on the palate. The liquid contained a fine, frothy, tongue coating effervescence. Triple IPAs often have a tendency to be very malt forward, and this one stayed just shy of being overly sweet. Post Apocalyptic Xanadu is a really nicely done beer that became significantly more punchy and complex as it warmed. Be patient with this one.

Look: Hazy honey gold with a moderate white head. Almost no activity. Smell: Pungent hops envelop the senses. Notes of ripe melon, papaya, guava, green mango, pineapple, and peach. Heavy and sticky on the nose. Taste: Aggressively juicy hops on the attack. Notes of papaya, grapefruit, guava, and pineapple. Then a second burst of hops hits in the body with more papaya, peach, and nectarine notes. This runs its course as a note of sweet honey malt gets slowly revealed then recedes to a lightly bitter dry finish. Feel: Medium plus body. Juicy and resinous on the palate. Soft carbonation. Deceptively smooth given the ABV. Mild alcohol warmth. Dry finish. Mild bitterness. Overall: A stellar offering from Mystic. It’s absolutely bursting with juicy citrus hops in soft smooth package. On par or better then anything I’ve had from the other big names in hazy IPAs. Brilliant.
Look: Orange, hazy, with two inch head. Smell: Orange, papaya, guava, and caramel malt. Taste: Orange, papaya, guava, and caramel malt. Overall: A great Triple IPA from mystic.
Pours black with a brown head. Great lacing. Aroma of milk chocolate and coffee grinds. Taste follows the nose with a light bitterness, light bourbon and a maple syrup finish.

Appearance: Medium golden color, with some haze. The head is snow-white, coarse, and modest, though it retains well. Fine-beaded lacing coats the glass walls. Numerous columns of fat bubbles rise to the surface, neither languid nor hurried in their pace. Aroma: Classic white bread and cracker note, with some grassy, clean hops. The aroma is very clean. Taste: Begins with abundant pale malt, having white bread and cracker notes. Soon after, grassy and herbal hops dominate, the latter being more pronounced. As the taste progresses, the hops assume a sharp bitter, metallic note. Finishes with a lingering medicinal note. Mouth feel: A touch thin, with a slight stinging carbonation. Drinkability/notes: What more can I say, a well-made example of a revered, classic style. Certainly the equal of the excellent Czech Pilseners. Presentation: Packaged in a 500 ml, 16.9 ounce aluminum can, served in a standard Pilsener glass. Beer number one (December 1st) from the 2017 Costco Advent Beer Calendar.

Pours a cloudy straw orange with three fingers of white head. Head formation is quick, with great retention and lacing. Aroma is pilsner and pale malts with herbal and floral hop notes. Straight forward "beer" aroma. Flavor profile is intriguing, with pilsner, pale, and bread malts opening it up. It develops a "wet-dog" note, before decaying into a bitter hop finish. Mouth feel is medium in thickness with a slightly effervescent feel. Overall, a strong flavored pilsner that doesn't produce the best of notes. Served in a 12oz snifter from a 16oz can.

Well it's December 1st so time to open 1st beer of the pack. Poured from can @ about 40-45 degrees and into a pokal glass: L: clear golden straw body that seems quite thickening for a pilsner. Great body with bubbly body that laces the glass. A: pure and fresh malty goodness M: medium creamy goodness. Take a dip and let it swish around. Take tiny sips, enjoy! This is as good as pilsners get. It does go thin but it's almost like it melts in the mouth and nearly dissolves. No after taste. Super smooth. T: creamy malt, grain, honey, barley, and lemon. Slightly bitter. O: best pilsner ever had hands down. Don't understand the low reviews. Maybe was poured in wrong glass and/or served too cold? This is German beer brewed with purity law. Sure it's not some crazy craft beer fad but it's brilliantly brewed for a pilsner. To give low score is almost like what did you expect? Why buy? This is German beer they will all be quite similar. For a pilsner this is delicious and don't think it can get much better.

From Costco. Can 50cl. In Bavaria hefe glass. Playing Sentience The Android's Tale. Watery, with an important grassy bitterness but not much taste and metallic. Avg 2.08. 28 Dec 2017. Bottle. From Costco. In Teku glass. Playing Bioshock Remastered. Much better than canned version,without the metallic thing and without so much grassy bitterness. More balanced and good feel but still flat
From the bottle in the Kalea Bier Advents Kalender, it pours a golden color with a modest head, soon reducing to a slight ring. Grainy scent and a mild bitterness in the mouth.

Canned 4/20/2016. Can saying: "Alright x 3". I can dig the Matthew McConaughey reference. Appearance - Living up to its name, Haze is... hazy. This is pretty much the de facto description of the appearance for all Tree House IPAs so far. It seems to be a little lighter in appearance than either Julius or Sap. The head is very foamy and long-lasting. Aroma - The nose brimming with juicy notes from the fresh hops and the peach aroma is through the roof. A pulpy orange note follows next like a glass of freshly-squeezed O.J. and just the faintest hint of pine at the end. Taste - Finally, a Tree House beer that tastes as good as it smells. The hops are obviously the most dominant flavor here, but it is all juicy goodness; there is almost no bitterness at all despite the high alcohol and hop dosage. Again, I'm getting tons of peach, orange, pine sap, and other tropical fruits that it's pretty crazy actually. Perhaps a tiny bit of malt backbone as well, but who needs it when the hops carry the flavor as well as this does? Mouthfeel - The mouthfeel is medium-bodied with good carbonation. Tree House nails the body perfectly once again, with a soft texture that accentuates the hops. This is probably the lightest DIPA I've had. Closing Arguments - Overall, this is far-and-away the best Tree House beer I've had so far that I could actually sit down with and analyze. Lights On may give it a run for its money, but that was at a tasting, so different circumstances there. Whereas Julius and Sap didn't live up to their billing, Haze carries the standard and doesn't relinquish it in the flavor. If I had this blind, there's no way I'd peg it as anywhere close to 8%. Dangerously crushable for sure.

L - hazy - as advertised. good lacing on the glass, lighter towards the top and grows deeper in the snifter. S- wonderful. papaya, mango, tropical, very very strong nose. T - the beer does not sip as strong fruity forward as the smell as the bite at the end is bitter and lingers. Lots of resiny earthy pine in the finish that lingers long. almost so much so that it overpowers everything else though the more you drink it the more the other notes come off the sidelines and take hold. F - does not feel like 8.2 at all, light, fluffy. very good here. O - this is my first crack at tree house and it is very very good. almost a jeckyl and hyde type situation where the smell is so citrus and the finish is so earthy dank but they pull it together nicely. the more you sip it the more you get from it too. great stuff.

Poured from a bottle into a Spiegelau Stout Glass. Aroma: Bold coffee, roast sweetness, oak/bourbon and faint alcohol. No maple detected. Appearance: Dark black, impressive mocha/tan head. Lacing persists as you drink. Looks really nice! When swirled, nice viscous look. Taste: Coffee is bold and dominant. Followed by roast malt and medium sweetness. Not much maple detected until the very end on the palate, but its quite subtle. Has a fairly harsh roast/bitter lingering on the finish. You get the oak and bourbon, but it's fairly restrained and nice. Feel: Medium bodied. Lively carbonation, quite prickly, actually. Overall: I desired more maple, all things considered. Well made beer, but the coffee at this point is a bit too bold and the bitter roast distracts from the balance of the beer. With time, I think this could age into something wonderful, especially if the maple pops a bit more as the coffee ages out. As far as maple/coffee stouts go, there are better out there if you want maple. I find Funky Buddha for example, being quite a bit more impressive with Wide Awake It's Morning and Morning Wood (along with Bacon Maple Coffee Porter, as well). Delicious beer... Would buy it all the time if it was always available or more easy to obtain, but not exactly worth the hunt with all things considered. Glad I ended up with a few bottles none-the-less, it's fantastic.

First off let's all thank founders for enabling cricket chirps when she's FT. 5/8 motor oil...the rest tight khaki foam that's still sticking all over the glass. Heavy coffee aroma. A sweeter version of kbs. No maple flavor and like kbs I don't get much barrel character..non bitter coffee flavor..chocolate is there. Lip smacking rich, sticky & smooth. Abv is there but half way through not so much (creeps up on you). Dangerously drinkable. NY wallet rape aside I enjoyed this.

Pours dark black with a 2-3 finger light brown head that lasts and lasts. Good, if not exceptional, lacing. Aroma was good but maybe less than expected. chocolate, lots of coffee, slight maple, bourbon and oak tones. Pleasant but doesn’t slap you in the face. Taste and subtle complexity is where CBS really shines. Big coffee, dark chocolate, licorice and maple on the backend. It’s doesn’t have in your face hops and booze like KBS. It’s very easy to drink. As it warmed the maple flavor came through even more. I would get the bottle temp to 45-ish degrees before opening then appreciate the flavor changes as it warms into the 50s. Other than the coffee, all the flavors are subtly blended and exceptionally smooth. One of the best but maybe just a tiny notch below Bell’s Black Note. Mouthfeel is really good. Velvety fullness with moderate carbonation. The maple is not cloyingly sweet but leaves a coating in your mouth. Overall, this is a great stout, worthy of the hype. It won’t change your life but certainly will be a beer drinking highlight. I’m looking forward to a second bottle and/or a draft tasting to compare with initial impression. Also want to see how my stash ages over the next year or two. Feb 2018 Note: second bottle was as good or better than the first. I let it warm a bit this time and the flavors really shined through. More coffee, more chocolate, more black licorice. Maple sweetness is always there but still subtle and in harmony with the other bold flavors. Still not a ton of nose but that may be partially the fault of my nose and the hotel room tumbler.

Very sweet, you can taste the coffee Maple and chocolate when it's cold but as it warms, the bourbon flavor comes out strong. It was a bit much for me but I see what all the Buzz is around this beer, very good and worth the price.
12oz Bottle from the LCBO for around $8
Much too sweet.

Rich deep aroma of chocolate, oak, vanilla, and a hint of maple. Pours an opaque black with a ring and dusting of tan head. Deep rich flavor of chocolate, oak, and vanilla, with a touch of roasted earthy bitterness in the finish. The maple is there as a hint, not overpowering anything, but working with the other flavors. Full body, with a silky mouthfeel. This is an exceptional beer, and I'm glad it got more distribution in bottles for this release of it.

L -- Pours a dark black, although not as dark as KBS. Good-sized light brown head given the ABV produced with moderate pour. Good retention and great lacing S -- More muted than expected. Maple, milk chocolate, coffee, oak, vanilla, toffee, bourbon. The oak and bourbon character is subdued T -- The sweetness of the maple offsets the intense chocolate, coffee, and bourbon flavors of KBS wonderfully. Turns a beer that I think tastes like an Irish coffee with chocolate syrup into a decadent, gentle sipper. The barrel character -- as others have pointed out -- is weaker than it could be. Perhaps a few more months in the barrels before bottling? F -- Wonderfully fluffy, velvety mouthfeel that dances across the palate. Medium- carb. Quite sweet, but not cloying O -- It's a great stout, worthy of the hype. Is it worthy of the price? Maybe a bottle a year..... 92/100
Lots of spices, but very sour. Floral and herbal. Green apples. Tannins. Oak barrel flavors. Lemon acidity. Sour and tart. This beer is easy drink and something I could definitely enjoy more of.
Beautiful golden hue. I get a very apple cidery type taste with a spicy ginger finish. Extremely drinkable. Well done.

Nice goldenrod sour that has a great amount of ginger in the nose. Then you get some good ginger forward notes with a wet finish. I feel like it whets my appetite to keep drinking. Very easy drinker. I wish I could have gotten more of the floral notes.

16oz tallboy can poured into a snifter glass. L - True to the name, Haze pours a very hazy, almost opaque orange, with a thin film of pearl-white head that dissipates and leaves some streaking on the glass and surface. The color and opacity resembles freshly squeezed orange juice, in a way. S - There's a distinct sweetness on the first whiff that reminds me of nectarines and peaches, followed by more subtle notes of papaya and a hint of orange. The sharper citrus notes that are typical of hop bombs are missing, and in its place is a slight touch of honey. As expected, there's a pretty strong earthy dankness backing up all of scents, making for an overall smell that's more warm and comforting than tropical and refreshing like most IPAs. Different, but still very nice. T - The tropical papaya notes come through pretty clearly on the first sip, which is followed by a slight maltiness. Not the most refreshing or juicy of IPAs, but definitely still very enjoyable. Finished with a strong dash of hop resin, which comes across slightly more bitter than crisp. It has all the right components of a great DIPA, but somehow, it's not making a huge impression on me. Admittedly, this might be because I've been drinking some fantastically fresh IPAs lately (Other Half Stacks on Stacks, Grimm Tesseract, Heady Topper, etc.). F - Mouthfeel is pretty consistent with all the other characteristics. Moderately fine carbonation brings a spritz that complements the hoppiness, and a slight viscosity of the liquid itself goes along with the smell and look. O - I can't exactly say I'm disappointed by Haze, since it's still a very good double IPA. Definitely not as impressive as the other Tree House IPA I've had so far though (Bright), and some of its contemporary DIPAs that I mentioned earlier. I would get this again, but there are other beers that I've had before that I'd be more keen on acquiring more of.
My favorite tree house beer. Haziness in the best possible ways

This is quite possibly the most vile, putrid, and over-hyped beer I have ever consumed. It smells of a sun-baked, two week overdue litter box and tastes like a combination of mango, papaya, and guava juice mixed with alley cat urine. I suspect the carefully selected hop mixture has a neurotoxic effect on the brain that forces formerly astute beer drinkers to stand in line for hours awaiting their Great Depression era rations of this sludge. Chemical engineering and marketing genius. Looks like beer. Feel is tough to judge because it is forcefully ejected from my mouth before I have much time to ponder the oral sensation of this prized brew. Three cans sampled over eight months.
Not my favorite offering from TH, but still really good.
Some of the best damn Stout I have had.
MUCH too sweet. KBS IS the real McCoy, CBS is just way too sweet.
Too sweet for my tastes, but man everything elese about this beer is amazing.
Too sweet

Poured into a Fremont small snifter. Pours pitch black, appearing opaque black in the glass with a fine, one finger, light brown head with great retention and thick lacing. Aroma of semi-sweet dark toasted malt, chocolate, latte coffee, bourbon, well balanced and inviting. Flavor follows, with mildly sweet dark toasted malt, chocolate, coffee, light maple and bourbon. Finishes with wonderfully balanced milky mocha and bourbon. Medium bodied with nice creaminess and excellent mouth feel. Well, this one has been on my want list for a long time, and I was almost prepared to be a little let down because of its hype and the long wait, but this really lives up to its reputation. It’s a little on the sweet side, which might be an issue for some stout fans, but tastes great to me and is not cloying as a syrup infused brew could be. As a matter of fact, the real story here is balance, a good thick malt body supports the coffee, maple, bourbon and chocolate flavors, but none dominates (maybe a little on the bourbon side, but I'll never quibble about that). This is definitely one of the best stouts I've ever had. My first taste was a 'wow' taste and that's always a good start. The only big problem with this one is the 750ml format; it's just too big unless you have a few people around to split this with. The beautiful balance is accompanied by well covered big ABV, making this dangerously inviting to keep sipping. But when life hands you too much of a good thing, it's best to drink up. This is definitely world class. Glad to have finally scored a bottle. Although our local market is full of excellent local IPAs and stouts, Founders has stood out as a welcome visitor. Since coffee stouts are bit of a dilemma for me because I drink in the evening (no "breakfast" stout for me) and respond well to caffeine, I expected this to be a one-and-done. Nope, I'll chase this next time it comes to town. I can see why this might be a bit on the sweet side for some palates, but for me, the overall balance of flavors with the great silky mouthfeel are hard to beat. Mmmm.
Wow, what a great beer. Lots of coffee, dark caramel and maple sugar, dark sweet chocolate and roasted malt. A bit smoky and prominent bourbon flavors. Really, really excellent, especially on tap.

Beer pours a nice foamy head that is dark brown and looks good. Beer itself is dark chocolate black with a nice syrup like texture upon view. It is delicious and inviting. Smell is very interesting and good. Light sweet and sugary maple syrup note. There is a bit of lightly smoked bacon. There is also a slight bitter dark chocolate but it gets lost in the syrup. Taste is good. Has a good maple syrup sweetness running through it with nice roasted malt undertones. The syrup is definitely strong and overpowers the other notes. Feel is good. Heavy body with a slight thinness and syrupy feel. Carbonation is tingling with a bit of biting but goes away quickly. Overall, a pretty good beer and definitely a bit overhyped. That being said, it is worth for the beer connoseur but not the average beer drinker.
Big flavors, but far too sweet, and all the adjuncts are fighting each other instead of coming together in harmonious fashion. Sometimes less is more.

Very glad to have been able to get a couple bottles. Its amazing how there are so many subtle flavors, with none overpowering one another, just a well balanced BA Stout. Slight barrel notes, slight fresh roasted coffee, slight maple, slight chocolate, well done.

Honestly, I was quite underwhelmed with this release by Founders. After highly anticipating it and managing to get a bottle of it, I was expecting something a bit better. While not a bad beer by any stretch of the imagination, there wasn't anything spectacular about it. Personally it tasted more like a regular Founders Breakfast Stout with stronger alcohol content. I tried it relatively chilled, as well as a bit warmer, just below room temperature, and the latter is the way I recommend. The maple flavor comes out much more when warmer, and overall makes the taste really flourish. At a colder temp, it tastes more boozey and most of the other flavors included into the brew become muted, nigh unnoticeable. A solid beer, worth trying if you are a fan of breakfast stouts, but you may be a little disappointed if you've never had it before and have been hyped up about it. Take it with a grain of salt.

I think I had my draft pour a little cold, because I got nothing off the nose. Maple for sure came through in the taste, even more so when it warmed. It did get a bit overly sweet for me when it came to temp, but that didn't stop me from having a second pour. For how hyped this beer was, I feel it may have been a slight let down, but still a solid brew.

Bomber poured into a tulip glass: Look: Pours a golden yellow with at least an inch of head with lacing present. Smell: Grapefruit, citrus, orange. Taste: Hop forward with grapefruit notes but then comes the sweetness and booziness towards the end with some lingering grapefruit notes. Feel: Medium bodied. Overall: Pretty solid "Hoppy" Belgian Quad from Victory! I would revisit this brew if they decide to offer it again next year.

Pours golden with lots of carbonation. Good head that fell slowly and left lace. Looks more like a tripel than a quad so maybe it's a belgian strong golden ale. Nose is hops tropical and citrus. Not really any phenols but a little clove. estery like pear. Sweet. taste is not very complex and very sweet. hops give their best but the beer is very sweet and pale. it has plenty of american type hop fruitiness but none of the dark fruitiness you associate with the quad. There is some spice, there is some clove though. Again a strong golden maybe. Finishes syrupy and a bit boozy.

(bomber poured into one wine glass - all except the lees in 2 pour stages) L: near crystal-clear (on the first pour - subsequent careful pours are hazier, with flaky sediment), orange-yellow metallic gold liquid... nice foamy pad formed on the pour, but didn't hold long... well, it's kinda has some elegance in the wine glass S: grapefruit and orange flesh... little hint of mint and black pepper in the back... really juicy - fresh-squeezed orange... mellow perfumy floral undertones, spiraling out tied up with mildly medicinal booze... bit of a candy sugar sweetness underneath, though it's a bit tough to get much distinct yeast esters with the hops so potent T: more of a rind citrus flavor, with a tiny thread of candied orange slipping down the back - big whoosh of sanded-down, semi-spicy booze immediately follows the initial hop smack... the leftover alcohol flavors are pure and clean, little bit of grapefruity bitterness lingering as well... the mid part of the sip has a subtle flash of the cookie-like malt, and the hops atop that in that brief moment seem to be the more familiar Chinook... the aftertaste - very nicely dry - is pretty much pink grapefruit massacre and unleaded fumes and malt gravel F: soft and dainty-light with a glassy core... the carbonation seemed a bit lax in this bottle... whisper soft on the palate... remarkably dry, with only the hop trails reminding ya that your swillin' suds O: the name is lame and this isn't a 3-4x IPA only because they used a Belgian yeast - a 'Belgian-style' quad would not be gang-banged by hops, so this is not Belgian-style, boys... whatever... it's executed expertly, but the hop noise takes away from what I love best about quads - the near-tropical, bruised-fruit profile from the yeast/booze and the soft-malty undercurrent... is Mosaic still a hot item? why do I see so many beers where it's blended with multiple hops? not so great on its own?... this is not a creative (hoppy) beer - should we be surprised?

Picked up a 750 ml caged and corked bottle from TW Arrowhead in late October for $8.99. Bottled on 08-31-2015. Beer poured a Quad IPA pale with a nice white head that has some nice hang time. Nose is citrusy and fresh. Taste is hop forward. Notes of citrus, peach, lemon, and a touch of peppery pine. Just a touch of alcohol heat felt in my belly after the first sips. There is enough hopping to keep the massive malt bill sweetness tamed. Feel is medium bodied and fantastically smooth yet fresh. Overall this is quite a nice brewing job by the folks at Victory. This is a Quad IPA all the way. Do not expect V-Twelve or any other quad you have had in the past. I am really curious as to the IBU's in this beer as it has to be in the 100-130 range to tame this monster! Cheers!

The last time I had a beer from Victory I was highly disappointed. So much so it has been years since I was willing to give them a second chance. Hoppy quad has made me change my mind about them. Weak on the nose, I can barely smell the hops in it, and was apprehensive before taking my first sip. Everything changed after that first sip. Mild in body, medium in hoppy-ness, solid on the finish. The after taste makes you want to take another sip right away, in a good way. It has this effervescent feel in the mouth that was equal parts unexpected and enjoyable. I picked it up from my local bottle shop for $9.66 + tax and for that price I would recommended picking one up for yourself, maybe one for the aging cellar if you are into that sort of thing or gift it to an up and coming beer geek friend/family .

Aroma is resiny, citrusy, and floral, with big pear and apple esters a and notes alcohol. Esters and hops are somewhat in balance, countering the sweet malt. Flavor is fairly sweet at the backbone, with complementing pear and light apple esters. Citrusy hops prevent it from being cloying, and the lightly bitter, spicy finish, rounds out the profile. A bit overly boozy.
Not a bad beer but nothing really to write home about. The hops are what saves this beer for me as I'm not a huge fan of Belgian styles. In spite of the high abv% it's not as boozy as you'd think.

If you're going to call it a "hoppy quad", then the only way to make the hops really stand out is to lighten the malt profile. But not backing down on the alcohol content, the character of malt has to take a lighter profile. Let's see what else that Victory brewers have in store... Their hoppy quad actually sells an imperial IPA appearance- its bright golden globe is laced slightly with haze and capped with a stark-white froth. With the nose hovering above, a bright citrus, orchard and tropical medley rounds out with a friendly floral perfume. Once its malty-sweet taste reaches the tongue, it is greeted with supple confectioner's sugar, rich angel-food cake, and an overall candied succulence. And as those hops unfold on the palate, its true balance takes hold. With subsequent pink grapefruit, ripe orange, pineapple, melon, lemon and mango taking their turns teasing the tastebuds, a bitter, leafy, grassy and herbal taste transpires. While the stone fruits of apricot, fig and date contribute an earthy and fresh tobacco leaf fruity tar, its clean and resinous sappy pine taste and texture rounds out the bulk of taste. To finish, the medium-full beer has a honey-like heft, begging for its succulence and lavish maltiness to be savored and sipped. Not for those seeking a fast and thirst quenching session, its long and bitter linger is adorned with citrus peel, root, and torn tea leaf.

Founders CBS, 11.7% ABV. Pours thick and black with a right pretty 2+ finger brown head that left thick foamy lacing. Nose is coffee, chocolate, maple, and a hint of bourbon. Taste follows, with moderate sweetness and slight bitterness. Nice amount of bourbon flavor, but not overly strong. I am revising this review; the first one was excellent, but not outstanding. Five months later, this one was incredible, with strong maple right up front. Excellent mouthfeel, overall outstanding.

Just insane. This is 8.2%!? Amazing depth of flavor. From bitter to sweet to fruit to grass and even a hint of spice. Balanced with just a hit of the booze here. Crafted. Not just a haze bomb, hop bomb, juice bomb or fruit bomb... all of the above.

Tasting my fourth tree house IPA ever. Only other ones I've had are green, alter ego, Julius, and this one. So I'll go head and make a few comparisons. Pour is a beautiful murky, cloud orange. Seems to be a little more straw yellow than the other offerings I've had. Nice tight white bubbles head, great lacing on the glass. Smell seems to be the medium in the most hoppy, resinous TH I've had (Julius), and the fruitier tropical Green. Soon as you crack the can, you get whiffs of peach, orange, tangerines and papaya. Then again you still get that slight resinous smell in the back end, reminiscent of marijuana and sweet malt. Besides the tropical fruit and hop resin I'm getting some nice honey as well. Taste is an interesting blend of all the smells I got in the nose, tropical goodness like peaches, papaya and tangerines. But the most unique about Haze is its honey/sweet nectar quality. Definitely has a subtle sweet floral taste to it. Hop profile definitely isn't dominant. Sweet malt profile as well. Mouthfeel doesn't come as a surprise. Not as much as a fruit dole feel like Green, but a more organic orange juice feel. Overall, quite possibly my favorite TH I've had so far. Not as much of a fruity bomb as Green, not as much hop profile as Julius. Kind of the medium, like alter ego. But with a more honey/nectar flavor. Lovely beer.

From 16oz can packaged 13 days ago, enjoyed in a swell tulip glass after coaching a BU14 evening soccer practice. This beer is a terrific value, as craft beer prices continue to creep up and up, you want to drink this one. L: pours a perfect cloudy orange HAZEy look, 1/2" head at pouring, dissipates to fine lacing after a minute. Looks great, had it a few times over the past 6 months and after a while it becomes almost hoh hum, another beautiful glass of Haze, very killah, repeat ability in batches is very important to me and it is demonstrated by the TH team S: Very juicy, love it, slight hoppy after the fruity T: wicked killah stuff here, great citrusy, piney with hop but not too big a hop hit, overall great flavor F: love it in my mouth, very fill all over flavors, very good length, taste it well after swallowing it, slight bitter ending not bitey, really nice O: well, it's wicked pissah and I love it, so easy to drink. At just over HALF THE COST of Trillium Mettle (which I like A LOT!) this is not only a REALLY great beer but a GREAT VALUE!!!

i agree with the other reviewer that the dry crisp nature of this one, with the equally prominent ginger component is an improvement on the sourtooth, which for me felt a little busy. this is streamlined a bit, and is quite a bit more sour if i remember correctly. it has a vibrant pink hue to it, but smells less floral than i expected with the hibiscus. its always so intense, so cool move to dose it so moderately here, let me be an accompaniment, not a solo. the ginger is spicy and raw and fresh in the aroma, and it translates over to the flavor nicely, its not hot, but it is very up front. i am impressed with the sour profile of this as well, its more than just lacto acidity. its insanely sour, but has a lot of flavor too aside from just the acid. the wood seems light and almost neutral, not dank and heavy like it sometimes can. for as flavorful as this beer is, its also very delicate in its overall impression. soft carbonation, light body, and a really nice union of some interesting ingredients under a brightly sour yeast profile. not too many beers of this quality out there for purchase. it reminds me of a more sour jolly pumpkin beer i liked a lot. great use of ginger here, top notch from these guys as usual.

Poured out of the bottle on 3.29.15 Wonderful color - pinkish-amber - and the smell is ginger with light floral (less floral than when I had it originally on tap). Taste - nice sour pucker without the sweet backbone that came with Sourtooth. Replacing the sweet is a nice crisp, floral finish. To me, it's a more refined Sourtooth.

Best word that can be used to describe this beer is epic. Flavors are perfectly balanced, and not overly sweet. The maple is subtle, yet present. Hints of coffee and chocolate shine through as well, but not overpowering. This truly is an amazing beer, and deserving of the hype. For a price tag of $24.99 per 750mL, I say it is well worth the money. Well done Founders.
0% Amazingly good after just a few months aging

This is a fantastic imperial stout-- one of the best I have ever been fortunate enough to sample!!! Grabbed 1 bottle this year but also tried it on draft at South Loop Binny's. So thick and flavorful. Tasting side-by-side with KBS was eye-opening also, as I USED to be a big fan of KBS!

Pours a dark black with a creamy dark tan head. Smells of bourbon, chocolate, and sweet maple. Tastes of semi-sweet maple syrup, somewhat boozy bourbon, dark roast coffee, dark chocolate, light wood, and light vanilla. The bourbon and chocolate really pop, and the maple sweetens as the beer begins to warm, and it becomes more enjoyable although its enjoyable the whole way through. Heavy silky body with medium carbonation. Overall, this is almost perfect. I don't get my hopes up for insanely hyped beers anymore after a few disappointments so I went into this not expecting to be wowed. But this beer definitely blew my mind. All of the flavors were perfectly balanced. Tried this on tap and I'll be trying it out of the bottle soon. Tried it out of bottle now and it’s even better. The smell and flavor improved greatly.

LOOKS: Jet black with a finger+ of frothy tan head, that sticks around; nice lacing down the glass. AROMA: Fudge brownies, coffee, bourbon/alcohol, coconut, and just a slight hint of maple. Oddly I get a nice big hit of maple syrup from smelling into the bottle itself. TASTE: Very smooth overall, nothing really stands out, so, I thought the maple would be more prominent, same with the bourbon. It is blended well, but I don't know that I would have guessed it contained maple....maybe yes, but I'm kind of going back and forth between maple and coconut; and, no where near the bourbon characteristics of BCBS. Chocolate, mild coffee, a bit of coconut or maple, and mild bourbon/alcohol. FEEL: Carbonation is adequate...medium. Feel is medium full, not as thick or sticky as BCBS, OVERALL: Certainly a decent beer, but I'm a bit disappointed with the very mild maple, the actual flavor of the bourbon, and the viscosity. Glad I found a bottle to try, at any rate. Edit: I came across a second bottle, and this time I didn't chill it at all. I'm still not loving the viscosity, but I am getting more maple, and the bourbon is coming out a bit more; overall, it's a fine, smooth brew, so, a bump in the score from my previous 4.28.

Had this beer both out of a bottle and on tap: A: Pours black as expected with a surprising amount of head formation. Beautiful dark and thick head that stays put. S: Overall very pleasant aroma, with very even amounts of chocolate, coffee, and bourbon barrel. The maple comes through but seems to only dance around in the aroma rather than dominate it. T: Similar to the aroma, the flavor profile is very well rounded and incredibly smooth. There is very little heat given that it is 11.7% ABV but there are mellow bourbon notes pleasantly on the back end. There is a presence of oak and vanilla but it is not very forward in flavor. This is not a bad thing as this is a perfect fit in this beer. M: Silky smooth and spot on. O: Overall this is a world class stout. My impression is that it does everything just about perfectly but was never meant to be a "huge" stout. It's a perfect breakfast stout. It is unfortunate that it had been so hyped up over the years because it likely won't get the credit it deserves. I was able to have '16 and '17 KBS next to this on tap and CBS was on a different planet. $25 a bottle is steep in price but it is absolutely worth buying a bottle to try. Get it on tap if you can.
Outstanding Stout. The stout that all stouts are measured to.
FINALLY!!

750 ml bottle, 2017, poured into a teku A- Black with a dense two finger mocha head that stays around. S- Rich dark coffee, maple syrup, charred oak, vanilla, some bourbon, dark chocolate, hints of milk chocolate. Very well balanced. T- Maple syrup, chocolate, roasted coffee, charred oak, vanilla, bourbon is mild, getting subtle hints of dark fruits, alcohol is very well hidden. M- Silky smooth, medium to full body, good carbonation. O- Sweet without being overly sweet, body is a little thinner than I thought it would be. Flavors are very well balanced and this is dangerously drinkable for 11.7%. Truly a world class beer lives up to the hype.

Pours a hazy golden. Pepper in color with 2 fingers of pillowy, long lasting white head. Aroma is melon, cantaloupe, mango, papaya, and bubblegum. Taste hits the same notes as the aroma, this is tropical fruit bubblegum. The cantaloupe and green melon are the only distinguishable fruit flavors here but there is a distinctly tropical undercurrent. This finishes lightly sweet like a fruit, it's shocking how well hidden the 10% ABV is. Medium+ body with moderate carbonation. Overall this is the most drinkable TIPA I've ever had, I just can't put this one down. I had the June batch and really enjoyed it but the consensus among my beer loving friend group is that this batch is "straight fire".

had this on tap, hazed gold color with a bright white head and some lacing - great looking brew. very well balanced, has some tropical and citric qualities, sweet malty notes, slightly floral and mellow piney bitterness. medium bodied, nice texture - would have guessed this was an 8% DIPA, drinks really easy and smooth for a triple. overall absolutely wonderful!

Fantastic. I usually am not a huge fan of triple ipas but this is a beauty. A hazy golden orange color with a head that dissipates overtime but still holds on ever so slightly. Hoppy but not hopped to the max, more fruit than butter coming through. The folks at Mystic have done it again.

When based on the style of a triple IPA, this is masterfully done. Citra and mosaic stand out and this drinks incredibly easy for a 10% hopped up to hell and back beer. I find most TIPAs too intense but this is so dialed in I would have a hard time guessing it wasn't 8%. Tons of fruity goodness, minimal alcohol heat or bitterness. Just well crafted, bravo, hope to see it again.
The hop profile is fine, but overall it's a bit boozy and abrasive. When you're down the street from Cellarmaker you gotta up your game.

In the brewery tap on 5th Feb 2013, during 'Strong Beer Month'. Pours a pleasant amber colour, clear, with a full beige head. Mixed bag of flavours and smells: hops obviously rule throughout but there is an undertone of semi-sweet caramel/malty molasses in the brew also. Citrus based hop aroma, comes through into the taste nicely but doesn't take over completely. The alcohol level is noticeable but not to the beers detriment, it suited the strong flavours well.

Review: Bottle of St Mel’s Helles lager, 5.0%ABV The Helles lager is the most popular of the three beers in the St Mel’s Collection, their best seller. It’s always a bit difficult when an Irish brewer tries to replicate a German Style beer but I think St Mel’s definitely have got the right balance of authenticity and respect to traditions here. The aroma was not over bearing, and was of a good bready malty smell, decent on the nose. On pour the head did dissipate rather quickly, leaving a golden brown colour with some carbonation. The flavour was of sweet pale malts, wheaty, a little bread, with some sour notes and fizz. The aftertaste was strong and slightly bitter, but enjoyable. It was a quality beer to drink and a beer I can imagine would work well with a nice meal. If a punter is going to try a new experience and drink a craft beer then this beer would be a great introduction. A good local Irish lager.

Had a 4 oz pour of this at Ballast Point brewery. A specialty brew of their Fathom IPL. From menu: "Made with Lemongrass, Lemon Thyme, Rosemary & Basil". Smell of herbs as suggested with a citrusy hoppiness. Unfortunately the taste of listed herbs don't all really come through which would be desired for a specialty brew like this. Refreshing and interesting, but below expectations, close to their regular Fathom IPL I'd say.
Another perfect beer by Tree House. Can't wait until they build their new facility.

Can shared by Curran last night, thanks man. This one pours a hazy (duh) and turbid honey orange color, with a half inch head, and a little bit of lacing. Smells fantastically hoppy and fruity, with lots of orange, and grapefruit, mango, and pineapple, with some dankness and pine and that sort of thing. This is probably the best Tree House beer that I've had. It balances pretty deftly the big juicy hop character that most Tree House beers have, with a nice level of dank marijuana type flavors, a hefy bitterness, but also a big juice blast. There's some grapefruit, orange, pineapple, and mango, and TONS of it. This is absolutely delicious. This has a nice crisp and creamy mouthfeel, with a great level of drinkability. My favorite beer yet from Tree House, a stunner.

December 2017 release, 750ml bottle. Enjoyable, but not mind-blowing, and perhaps with some flaws, even? The pour is gorgeous, with a nice finger of head and good retention and lacing. The nose is more subdued than I expected given the massive hype-train: a fair showing of bitter, dark-roasted coffee, high-percentage dark chocolate, and hints of syrup sweetness, but also some vegetal pepper. On my palate, the maple notes are inextricably tied to a dry astringency and roasted bell pepper suggestion, with the coffee playing second fiddle and chocolate fading as the beer warms. Moderately thin but with a very smooth mouthfeel that I enjoy. The finish is a bit off-putting to me, personally, especially after just having had some other big players in the BA coffee stout game. Certainly still a high-quality, enjoyable release, and my score should reflect that, but it did not come close to living up to expectations.

hype beyond hype right now.... never thought id get to try this beer and then turns out i was able to purchase as many as i wanted without even waiting in line, perfect!! pricey af though, really hoping this lives up to expectations. pour is gorgeous, no way a stout can really look better than this. pitch black in the glass with a dark tan head that is dense with soapy bubbles atop. great retention and ridiculous lacing. nose is maple, earthy roast notes, some mellow barrel character and the subtlest hint of boozy bourbon. palate follows perfectly with a smack of sticky maple up front, robust roasty and slightly earthy coffee notes, caramel and a creamy vanilla note, big big chocolate - some milk and creamy aspects to it ... oaky and a mellow hit of bourbon on the finish. mouthfeel is medium bodied - not sludgy, but still has a substantial texture to it nonetheless. overall I am wowed by this beer and would absolutely love to have bought a case if i could have afforded it. totally lived up to the hype and even exceeded - this is one of the best maple beers i have ever tasted!!

To me this is maple KBS. A: It looks great in the glass with a very dark brown almost black color, and a creamy brown head that disappears as I drink the beer, bit leaves some very sticky lacing. S: It hits all the ingredients well. All the coffee and chocolate comes through. To me the coffee is dominant. Subtle bourbon barrel notes such as bourbon, vanilla and sweet coconut, followed by a sweet maple note. M: Thin like KBS, at least more so than I prefer for a beer of this style and ABV. F: Again, maple KBS. Big notes of coffee and chocolate. I found the bourbon barrel to be moderate. No overpowering wood or bourbon notes. Sweeter than KBS due to maple, which is pleasant. D: Very drinkable. Not mindblowing, and no lt up there with my favorite maple bourbon beers such as Michigan Maple Jesus and Maple Bourbon Biscotti Cake Break. Overall a beer that falls on the low end of outstanding for me. Happy to have tried it, glad I bought only one bottle for the price.

Pours a thick rich black with a three finger lingering head of tightly laced bubbles. Smells primarily of pungent dark chocolate, then roasty coffee and malts, sweet. Taste is sugary sweet chocolate syrup, with some hinted bitterness.. so much chocolate it's undeniable. Coffee is definitely taking a back seat here. Not getting much syrup other than perhaps a source of the sweetness. ABV is definitely disguised as well, and not getting much in the realm of bourbon up front, just in the aftertaste. Thick creamy mouthfeel, not overly carbonated. Definitely has a lot in common with its sister beer, KBS, but this is a dessert stout as much as anything is. I was excited to try this one after so long, and while it was certainly no disappointment, a little tuning down on the sweetness separates this from something totally remarkable. Still, a real enjoyable treat.

This was amazing. Better than expected. Just the right amount of maple and light bourbon, with heavy coffee undertones. Glad to finally have had the chance to try this. One of my favorite beers I've ever had.
Really want to try and older vintage now. 2017 seemed overly bitter and lacking in maple character.
Early notes of bourbon and coffee with a subtle maple syrup linger throughout. Very smooth and very well done.

Red wine-tinted black with three fingers of lasting mocha head. Clumpy lacing. Rich coffee and chocolate dominate the nose, with hints of maple, vanilla, bourbon and oak behind. Big chocolate flavor up front, almost like a chocolatey milk stout, with coffee bitterness preventing the vanilla-maple sweetness from coming on too strong. Oak and some light alcohol burn on the backend. Coffee and chocolate bitterness lingers in the aftertaste. Oily, medium-bodied feel with modest carbonation. This is a really well-balanced beer for something with so many things going on in it. Overrated? Definitely. But still very good.

2017 Vintage; 750 ml bottle LOOK: Black with hints of brown and a light tan head SMELL: Chocolate and coffee up front, sweetness from the maple, next, a bit of the bourbon barrel last. Smells great, but way less maple and coffee than the 2014 vintage on draft. MOUTHFEEL: Soft and silky, low to medium carbonation, medium body TASTE: Follows the nose closely. Chocolate and coffee and maple sweetness blend in a very balanced way. Bourbon barrel lingers in this, but pretty subtle. Some boozy heat, but not much compared KBS. Overall the beer is very balanced with no specific character overwhlming everything else. I wish I got more bourbon barrel, as the beer is almost too mellow. It's a great beer, certainly, but it can't touch epic stouts like Kentucky Brunch, Assassin, or Barrel-Aged Abraxis.

Poured into a Dogfish traditional oversized snifter. Label says Bottled On: 31AUG2015. A- Pours a light amber color (which is pretty pale for a quad, I must say) with a 1/2 inch off-white head that retains well before becoming a thick ring around the edge of the glass and a large center patch of bubbly surface foam. Semi-resilient lacing leaves a broken ring behind. S- Boozy aroma of leafy hops, some Belgian yeast character and a bit of sweet malt. T- Neat duality between the fruitiness of the hops and fruitiness of the yeast with some toasty malt backbone and a big boozy finish. Pretty drinkable for the ABV though with some notes of vanilla and stone fruit. Moderate bitterness. M- Sharp from the hops and booze with medium carbonation and a body leaning toward the lighter side. O- First of all, this is not a quad. The only thing that makes it like a quad is the vanilla note. I would liken it more to a tripel, though I'm sure they called it a quad due to the ABV. That being said, this is a good experiment. You've got all the fruitiness and bitterness from the hops playing along with the yeast and alcohol quite well. Would buy again just to experiment with aging.

Poured from the bottle into a tulip glass. Big crystal clear body, golden mix of copper and brass, with wild amounts of carbonation everywhere. Streams all along the sides, a good middle column in the centre, and lots of pinhead sized fine bubbles everywhere. Populating head, manages a simple white off the pour, two fingers easily tall, and a collar that always manages a creamy half finger puck when drinking. Some light sheets of lacing. Aroma is hop forward and juicy. Big notes of tropical juiced citrus and pineapple. Lots of classic Belgian character is completely burried under this at all. Smell more like a simple new American IPA than anything else. Palate manages to save itself with providing some true Belgian character, with an American hop forward angle. Juicy texture, with also a bit of heat but not too overboard and less boozy sweet. Fruit front hop notes in the mid palate with a dusting of sugar. Tropical pineapple and citrus notes with a mix of classic Belgian sucrose. Finishes thick and rich, with a bit of American hop bitter. Accents towards honey and sugars as the sweetness dials down with warmth and heat. A good boozy warmth, but controlled and not too overbearing. This is a total style blur in so many ways, and should just be called an Imperial Belgian IPA or something. A fun brew but if you go by the moniker that this is a quad you're going to be in for a surprise.

Picked this up at one of the best beer stores ever, Bierhalle Deconinck. Hazy amber-orange pour with a quickly fading one finger white head with decent lacing. The nose is pretty one-dimensional and is dominated by the booze. Getting some subtle caramel and oak, but totally overpowered by the alcohol. The taste follows suite with the booze being king, but to a much lesser extent. Hints of caramel, vanilla, oak, cognac, and brown sugar manage to emerge from under the boozey dominance. The mouthfeel is medium bodied and slightly syrupy with medium carbonation and a subtle warming finish. Overall, this was a boozey mess. Little to no balance and the subtleties of the brandy and cognac barrels were lost amongst the booze.

As far as coconut beers go this might take the cake. 2 years old and still was a coconut bomb. Great smell that wasn't overly suntan lotion. Still a little thin, bourbon added sweetness but not a ton of barrel character left. Solid beer for what is was, just overly sweet.

asted from bottle side by side with Last Snow. Pours black with light tan head. Aroma is sweet bourbon, vanilla and just a hint of coconut. Mild to moderate bitterness with moderate sweetness. Flavors of bourbon, molasses, caramel, cocoa, vanilla, coconut. Just an incredible BA Porter.

Shiny black with thin brown edges and a tiny wisp of tan film consisting of the only visible carbonation. Smell is super fresh and abundant coconut, with cocoa butter, and even chocolate covered popcorn, transitioning to smooth, soft chocolate on the tongue with plenty of coconut, and not too much barrel actually, although it is quite strong and sweet. This is pretty darn tasty but I think the hassle of getting it, not to mention producing it, is not worth it, as I enjoyed the regular, even non-imperial version more.
This beer was bomb...if you can get your hands on it, get it...can't compare it to Last Buffalo.

10oz snifter at the taproom. A: Served a beautiful clear crimson with a faint white head. Wispy lace was left down the glass. S: Ginger and drying hibiscus on the nose with bright hints of lactic acid and flowers. Floral hibiscus is noticeable. Smells great. T: Definitely cosmic dust-like with drying and floral notes of hibiscus mixed with sour tooth tiger notes of ginger. I'd say definitely closer to cosmic in flavor. Not as epic drying though. Perfect amount of hibiscus. Ginger is present in the second half and is spicy and tingly. There is a mild stone fruit quality. Ginger continues into the finish alongside a nice tart lactic presence that creates a soft, subtle tartness. The aftertaste is spicy with lingering ginger and gritty from hibiscus tannins. Tingly spicy ginger lingers long after the swallow. M: Dry mouthfeel, medium body, mouthwatering feel, ample frothy but soft carb bubbles up and scrubs my palate. Some gritty tannins from the hibiscus linger. O: A perfect medley of flavors. Not crazy dry from hibiscus nor crazy spicy from ginger. Very balanced and exceptionally drinkable. One of the most refreshing beers I've had in recent memory. I immediately went back for a second glass. Makes you thirsty. I could drink this all day.

On tap at Mikkeller Bar in San Francisco. Served at 45 degrees Fahrenheit in a tulip glass. Surprisingly nice amount of head that kept its shape up until I began devouring this ale. I didn't catch much ginger or hibiscus, but I thoroughly enjoyed this beer nonetheless. It had just enough pucker. Wasn't sweet, which I hate. Not much bitterness. Carbonation was about medium. I'd drink this again, surely, but at the price and seeing that it didn't taste like ginger or hibiscus (little differentiation) I would be hesitant to fork over another $13 for 25cl at the bar.

Poured from a 750ml growler filled 3/19/16 into a 12 ounce tulip. The look is cloudy and opaque. It looks like pineapple juice but a little darker and more orange. Small, white head, which dissipated quickly, leaving moderate lacing. The smell is strong oranges - almost smells like orange juice - with a hoppiness coming through underneath. The mouthfeel is very smooth with medium carbonation. The taste is strong citrus - orange, and some grapefruit - but the hop presence is much stronger than I expected from the smell. In no way is any one flavor overpowering. This beer is incredibly balanced with no hint of alcohol. Overall, this beer is fantastic and very easy to drink. I completely understand the hype on the beer, and Tree House, if all their IPAs follow the quality of this one. Every taste gives me a little hint of different flavors. I'll definitely look for more from them, given the chance.

Fantastic beer that I most recently had on 4/7 canned 3/30. Whole depth of flavors including the papaya and peach that are advertised. Grapefruit, melon, pineapple as well. Very unique beer and VERY delicious. Hazy DIPA and what an amazing offering from TH.

To me, all of Tree House's releases are world class in that they contain the signature creaminess. This element really puts them above all the rest. Haze is no different. It's a nice rounded navel orange haze bomb with the aroma of grapefruit. The taste is much more tropical than most of their other releases. As stated in the description papaya comes through along with guava, dragon fruit, and some pineapple in addition to the citrus of grapefruit and orange. The feel is incredibly smooth with that chewy cream. Stellar beer.

Pours jet black with large fluffy mocha colored head that sustains for longer than I've ever seen out of a 11% BA stout. The aroma is dark roasted coffee, chocolate, maple. The bourbon notes are there, but are very muted and play in the background. Most of the bourbon aroma is vanilla oakiness. The flavor follows the nose coffee hits big up front before giving way to a big chocolatey sweetness. The sticky maple sweetness begins mid palate and continues through the finish. The barrel note is present, but this isn't a boozy BA beer. The bourbon isn't overpowering whatsoever, it's only throwing a bit of oakiness, some pipe tobacco and vanilla. The mouthfeel is the only thing I'm knocking this beer for, it's still amazing, but I would've preferred it to be chewier. Overall this is a crazy amazing beer, I just wish it was in 12 oz and affordable and I'd buy cases of it. It's an insane beer.

Been waiting a long time to finally try this and it was great. Not a lot of maple on the nose, but the decadence from the barrel smoothed out the coffee and the other flavors perfectly. Excellent beer and one I will be seeking out again

Poured 750ml bottle into snifter after letting it warm for 20 min. Color is a nice , dark black color with a thin tan head and no lacing. The smell has a nice and moderate bourbon aroma that blends with the maple syrup, coffee beans, and creamy chocolate. I imagine a nice cup of mocha espresso with, maple, and some caramel. The taste is fantastic. It's a nice combination of bourbon barrel, vanilla notes with dark chocolate with caramel. Hints of the maple and coffee are in the back. The feel is awesome. It's a heavy bodied beer with a very silky richness. The creaminess adds quite a bit to the beer's character. At $24 a bottle, I limited myself to 2, but it was well worth it.
Delicious, like pancakes and coffee

Paid $41 for a bomber in NYC; it was worth it. L: The only thing holding it back from a perfect score was the bubbles that were visible, not a pure foam. Midnight Black pour with a bright caramel (white at top) 2 finger head that lingers way beyond expectation. S: Fresh cup of coffee at first that mellows to a caramel and maple decadent smell. Dark chocolate and stone fruit come through at the tail. T: Coffee bite at first that turns into a dark chocolate covered cherry that is absolutely delicious and leaves you craving more. Maple and Bourbon come in the after taste/secondary. F: A bit strong at first that somewhat mellows. It's a crisp acidic bite, but you definitely feel the alcohol. Would'v liked it to be more hidden, but it is still enjoyable. O: One of the best stouts I've had, I'm honored to have been able to try this one after a while. Share the bottle with friends, it's absolutely fantastic, this is best enjoyed by the fire with family on a cold winter night.

2017 bottle, pours pitch black color with a 1-2 finger foamy brown colored head that faded slowly left really good spotty lacing. Nose is what I signed up for: bourbon, oaky notes, maple syrup, chocolate, burnt coffee grinds, dark chocolate, peat moss, earthy notes, pine cones, spruce, charred wood and roasted malts. Very complex with charred malts, rich chocolate, maple syrup and nice boozy bourbon making it lightly sweet and super dynamic. KBS with maple syrup, really impressive. Tastes like it smells with bourbon, maple syrup, oaky barrels, charred wood, chocolate, burnt coffee grinds, dark chocolate, peat moss, earthy notes, pine cones, marshmallow, campfire smoke and roasted malt. The chocolate dominates, with coffee and maple syrup adding nice accents to take the sweetness in stride and limit the bitterness. This could use some age to add more complexities, but it's still delicious at this early stage in the bottle. Glad CBS was released in NY this year, this is another white whale I can check off my list. 12/3/2017: Had on tap at The Lark in ENPT, NY and it was outstanding. More bourbon, more booze, amped up head and strong coffee and maple syrup added to the overall greatness and experience. The booze and bourbon/bourbon barrel influence on tap cut down the sweetness and kept it incredibly smooth. Raising the "Overall" score from 4.75 to 5 (which pushes the "Rating" score up from 4.65 to 4.7), but will hold off on adjusting the taste until I have this again aged from the bottle in 1 year.
Maple really comes out as it warms. Excellent beer.

Excited to finally try this one. I had heard that it got better as it warmed and that was definitely the case. After the taste was mostly maple and alcohol to start, as it warmed, the coffee started to come out. The coffee and maple eventually blended together to make it a very complex, enjoyable beer. It also had one of the better mouthfeels I can ever remember.

Look: Super hazy: light yellow-orange with very little translucency. Creamy head with small tight bubbles retained around rim throughout the drink. Smell: Citrus. Mango?. Definitely orange peel and maybe some lemon. Taste: More of those citrus flavors. Mostly getting orange and nectarine. Feel: Fairly balanced bitterness but still quite the citrus bite up front. Slightly creamy but not thick. Overall: It is a great DIPA but the market is flooded. This exceeds others because of how well it masks the ABV.

Overall while at the brewery I liked the normal version better, when I opened my bottle I liked this a lot too. Nice chocolate, pumpkin, oak, and rum mixture, the rum isn't overpowering but adds some nice sweetness to the beer.

Poured from a 12 oz bottle into a pint glass on a Princess Cruise. L: Pours a clear dark golden/amber color. Two fingers of off-white head. Reasonable lacing. S: Bready malts and brown sugar. T/F: Mildly sweet toasted malts... bready and rich, nicely balanced with some bitter hops. Traces of dark sugars. Medium mouthfeel and decent carbonation. O: A surprisingly good red ale brewed for Princess Cruise Lines by the Denali Brewing Co. Much better than I was expecting to find on the boat, and very sessionable.
Nice beer. Grab what you can get. Good for the non super hoppy fans. Enjoy

This is one of the best double IPA offerings I've ever tasted. It has a predominantly citrus scent, tastes like grapefruit/peach/fresh hops. Similar to other Tree House IPA's, but this one boasts a higher ABV which makes it a little more impressive to me. Overall, an outstanding beer.
This is the best beer that I have ever had!

This would normally be 5's across, but Very Hazy exists. L: Incredibly turbid, murky pineapple with tons of head. S: Tropical fruit juice, bubblegum, hint of dank. It's a little subtle, but most TH beers are, which is different at first, but really grows on you. T: It's not technically a 5 as Very Hazy is just a hair better, but it's better than 4.75. Tropical juice, pineapple, bit of dankness and greenery to balance. Somewhat subtle, but it makes the beer crazy drinkable. It's hard to not chug. F: Perfect. Full and creamy with light carb. O: My favorite standard TH beer. I enjoy it more than Green as it has a robust hop dankness as opposed to Green's zesty, clove like hop character. It's nearly just as good as Very Hazy, but that's just a hint more intense.

Pours a super hazy orange with a finger of white head, very reminiscent of orange juice. Aroma is very tropical, lots of mango, pineapple with some grapefruit, peach, and melon. Taste is much like the aroma with huge mango notes upfront, changing to pineapple, with melon in the finish. Good mouthfeel, medium-light body and moderate carbonation yield a pillowy mouthfeel. Overall this is another great example of a New England style IPA from Tree House but I just find this to be too juicy for my tastes.
Peach Julius

This is more a imperial IPA brewed in the style of a quad. Smells really good and looks more an DIPA. Tasty and rather good for me I would have liked it more in the quad style than ipa but still fun and tasty overall.

Lovely fruity and flowery aroma with that whiff of the barnyard. Clear golden amber-tinted brew with plenty of foam. Deeply fruity and full of mango and papaya flavors. Rather sweet, but it seems to fit with the strong sipping beer. The sprightly carbonation seems to help. Just acidic enough to go with the yeasty dry finish. I would have to agree with some who think this is more of a Tripel than a Quad, if it makes any difference. It's a full-flavored beer with lots of Belgian character. But the American styling makes it all the more interesting. From the 750 ml bottle purchased at Bottlecraft in San Diego for an exorbitant price. Still, it's good.

Bought a corked & caged bottle from the retail shop in Downingtown on 10/29/15. Didn't see a bottled on or drink by date on the bottle. Pored into my Bruery snifter for review. Pours gold with nice persistent rocky white head with a bit of haze. Carbonation looks nice & steady. Decidedly hoppy upfront with notes of lemon, pine, tropical fruit, and some hop resin. Some faint malt notes of biscuit & toast. Alcohols seem in check for 13% ABV. No off aromas noted. Smells like a double IPA. A wired orange Tang marmalade flavor hits upfront followed by a ménage of hop flavors and citrus punch. Malts seem light but somewhat caramelized. Combined with hop flavors, it first strikes me as odd and clashing. Belgian quad flavors seem nonexistent. Tastes medium full with an upfront dryness that finished sweet and a tad cloying perhaps from the hop resin. Fairly bitter upfront that gives way to hop flavors & resin. Alcohol seems well in check for 13%. Overall, this beer seems like a double or triple IPA, not a quad by any means. I wonder if Victory played around with their Dirt Wolf recipe to make a bigger badder beer. I don't get any of the Belgian or Trappist qualities. Perhaps they're there but I think they are masked by the hips if that is the case. For a hoppy IPA, this one satisfied as the alcohol is well in check and the hop aroma and flavor is very upfront, nice and enticing. For a quad, this one definitely missed the mark. Perhaps a rebranding of this beer is fitting in the near future.

Appearance: pours an orange color with a 1/2" head. Some mild lace develops. Smell: loads of fruit sweetness and alcohol is easily detectable. Taste: loads of fruit sweetness as mango, pineapple, pear and orange is up front. A floral bitterness and the alcohol rounds it out. Mouthfeel: heavy in body. Light crispness to start, smooth at the finish. Overall: a slow sipping beer that is very sweet and had a nice hop bitterness.

750 ml corked and caged poured into Spiegelau glass no bottle A: light amber body leaning toward yellow with great clarity. Has a big chunky head head but it fell down to almost nothing S: big tart fruity smell like mango but acidic some big clove but cut in half by the hoppy floral nose T: Wow the alcohol is in your face and not too overwhelming with the banana and clove as I feared but a nice dose of hops but they are more floral and herbal than fruity M: medium to a little fuller O: This is a lot better than I was expecting but the alcohol is over the top wow is this boozy tastes absolutely nothing like a quad none of that deep fig raisin toffee taste its more light light clove with lots of floral and a touch of fruitiness. Has a lot of a burnt sugar residual taste too. I don't love it but I don't hate it.

On tap at Smoke and Barrel - Washington, DC Belgian Quadrupel with Chinook, Mosaic, Cascade, and Citra hops Appearance: This is a gorgeous, but confusing beer. It's only slightly darker than Pilsner. A light orange with yellow hints. Good clarity and impressive head retention. Nothing approaching the color of a Belgian Quad or BSDA. Nose: Very interesting nose. Almost boozy Belgian-IPA esque. Definite Belgian yeast character. Lots of vanilla/woody character. Peaches, citrus, and hints of pine and tropical fruit. The sweetness gives everything a sort of candied aroma. Some booze, but not overwhelming for 13% Taste: Lots of perceived sweetness, but thankfully a fairly dry finish with only moderate lingering sugariness. Lots of fruit and yeast character. Lots of yeast-driven fruits: apple, pear, etc as well as hop driven flavors: peach. tropical, pine, resin. Again, intense vanilla that I struggle to totally place. No dark or toasted malt character whatsoever. Feel: Medium bodied given the ABV. Carbonation keeps it from ever being cloying, though it does lean a bit sweet. Overall: A beer with some very nice qualities that is extremely mislabeled as a quad.

Closer to DIPA than a Quadrupel if you ask me. The nose is bursting with tropical fruit and piney hops. There is a Belgian character on the palate from the yeast but make no mistake, this beer is about the hops.

Appearance - Pours jet black with nice tan head that dissipates to a thick ring around the glass. Spotty lacing at best but leaves a slick coating all around the glass. Aroma - Huge balanced notes of maple, bourbon, chocolate, vanilla, coffee and oak. Taste - The maple seems to hit first then the other flavors chocolate, vanilla, and coffee. The bourbon and oak hit toward the end. All of the flavors are very well balanced. Feel - Smooth creamy and slick soft carbonation with just the right amount of heat from the bourbon. Overall - Probably one of the most balanced BBA stouts I have tried the flavors are great and it is very easy drinking.
