2017 release with the all of the hype I needed to try this one. Poured too cold for the style with a semi gentle pour and this beer gave me a finger and a half of a mocha colored head. Subsided rather rapidly and left a huge amount of lacing clinging to every surface of the glass. So dark that no light penetrates. Smell is decadent chocolate, oak, vanilla, maple, bourbon, coffee and maybe some dark fruit. Taste WOW. The hype is not over rated! I don't care who owns the brewery this stuff is awesome! Starts with decadent chocolate and strong coffee. Vanilla and oak from the barrel kicks in then the subtle maple and Bourbon follow up, The finish is bitter chocolate sweetened by maple syrup with a slight warming with vanilla and bourbon notes. As it warms a little I am also getting breads, fig and barley. Just perfect. Feel is slightly chewy, lightly syrupy and the perfect amount of thick and medium carbonation. Overall; One of the best, If you can get it try it.

OK so I l-o-v-e this beer. I also love KBS, and I love Hopslam, and I love Zombie Dust and Gumballhead, and I even love Storm King. I guess I'm a relic. On the bright side, I can't stand Bourbon County and never could. Want to talk boozy, gimmicky mess? Talk Bourbon County. I got a perfect pour into a four ounce snifter. I've seen some youtube video where folks got explosive heads of foam, not me. Black as hell with a persistent quarter-finger head. Beautiful. Smells like an American imperial stout absolutely should. Easy on the nose, not a whiff of alcohol and not too much coffee. One of the few imperial stouts that are touted as being coffee and chocolate forward where it isn't coffee first and chocolate a distant second. Exquisite. Smells essentially like KBS which is a compliment. Mouth feel is slightly, and I mean ever so slightly, thin. This is still a satisfactorily thick imperial stout but I would not describe it as chewy. Tastes perfect and I mean literally perfect. I am not assaulted by coffee, bourbon, chocolate or maple syrup. Magnificently blended. Great, great beer. I picked up one bottle of 2011 from Half Time, enjoyed it but at this point in my beer advocacy I was not satisfactorily able to appreciate what was in front of me. This time around I think I'm vibing with this beer perfectly. Glad I have four of them, still giving two of them to friends for Christmas, sort of (selfishly) wishing I wasn't. BCBS SLAYER. I think the same thing when I think about any KBS from 2010 to present excluding 2014, but I think this is other-worldly. Does the 2011 release proud.

Hype-worthy. As one of two beers that passed through my area without my knowledge back in the day (the other was their Better Half), I had thought this would be a beer I never got to try. This 2017 release was a real surprise and despite the high sticker price, I grabbed two bombers. I let this beer sit out of the fridge for 20-30 minutes before popping the cap. Black-bodied beer produced a big, creamy dark foam head... Aromas of chocolate, bourbon, maple, vanilla, and coffee were all well-expressed, and supported by more of the same on the sip. Really impressed with how clearly the maple bourbon came though. The body was full and smooth, more sweet than dry or roasty, basically what I had anticipated. Better than KBS...
easily one of the best stouts I've had. rich bourbon on the front, and just a touch of maple notes. I've heard that before the beer was too sweet but I think they mailed it this time around
I have tried over 100 barrel aged stouts and this is one of the top three if not number one.
The bourbon wasn’t overpowering as it can be in some bourbon stouts - I was left with more of a chocolate and coffee taste and thoroughly enjoyed it !

2017 Bottle, poured shortly after purchasing and tossing it in the fridge (it was friday after work...) Super excited to finally try this one. Pours thick black which builds a good 1"+ thick mocha foam. Smell is surprising not all that interesting, some oak and bitter coffee. Taste on the other hand is fantastic. Super chocolatey and fudgey with a nice roasty maple finish. Well balanced and the maple is quite restrained and not overpowering. Overall, this is a high quality stout, far superior to KBS and many other maple stouts as well. The right balance of flavors, good to great body and it holds up nicely as the beer warms. Happy to watch this develop, But also happy I tried it Fresh!

750ml bottle poured into a chalice. A: Amber-orange color with a very mild haze. Fine-bubbled white head settles into a thin slip. Pencil thin ring of lacing. S: Lots of pine resin and earthy hop aromas. Cedar. Grapefruit zest jumps out. Lemon peel. Leafy. Mashed mango. Underneath the hops there are whiffs of musty yeast. pepper, clove and ginger spice notes. A touch medicinal. Vanilla. Tropical esters complement the hops. Angel food cake and fleeting notes of bread pudding. T: Earthy up front with hop notes of bark, cedar, and pine resin. Leafy. Peppery hop spice. Mango and grapefruit rind. Chalky yeast. Spice notes of black pepper, ginger, and clove. Pear. Vinous white grapes. Alcohols go in the direction of hot but stop just short. Treacle and caramel from the malt. White bread crust. Trailing alcohols and spicy and mashed mango hop flavors. M: Medium-light body. Full, round, and whipped in texture. It fills the mouth with an airy and silky feel, but stays very light. Sharp scrubbing carbonation cuts through like a knife. Big warming alcohol. O: The balance of power perhaps favors the hops a little, but they play pretty nicely with the base Belgian beer. Not the most complex Belgian ale around either, mainly because the hops do hog a good deal of attention. Obviously it takes many liberties from a style standpoint, but that's the point. Taken for what it is, it's still pretty solid.

Pours a pale, light honey, straw color. Definitely not the color I was expecting. Looks like an IPA with a LOT of carbonation streaming from the bottom of the glass. Very sweet, hoppy notes on this one. Lemon/lime zest, resinous pine, tropical citrus fruits, candy peach gummies, sour apple, strawberry, peppery spice, sweet honey and caramel malt. I was expecting something very syrupy and cloying but this was very smooth. Nice carbonation with lots of sweetness but it well balanced by the bitterness of the hops. There's more booze evident in the taste but its more warming than biting. Definitely doesn't drink like a 13%. You get some Belgian yeast banana notes, tropical citrus, dankness, peach, black pepper, honey sweetness, and caramel. I'd put it in the triple belgian IPA category.

This was a clear, shining golden color and it poured with a thick, creamy head. This was bursting with tropical fruit aromas of pineapple and mango, plus lots of melon. The "hoppy" part of the name is no lie. I did find some fruity, Belgian yeast esters that I would call more tripel than quad. The candi sugar was prominent while the 13% abv was not. This was both incredibly hoppy and incredibly sweet. The hops were very much fruit forward, mostly melon and pineapple, with very little bitterness. There was a minty dankness to the hops as well. I found plenty of candi sugar and strong, fruity esters as well. Nothing in the flavor profile was quad-like. The body lush, chewy, and silky smooth. Overall this was an odd beer that was oddly misnamed in my opinion. I just didn't find any quad characteristics here. But on the other hand, I have had a dark tripel, so why not a light quad? I enjoyed this well enough, but 750ml was a LOT to get through. I would recommend this to a friend with one shoulder raised and my head cocked to one side in a sort of half shrug of ambivalence.

From the corked, caged 750 ml. bottle. Sampled on October 23, 2015. The pour is golden with decent clarity and a foamy white head. Looks more like a Tripel. The aroma emphasizes the tropical fruit, melon, grapefruit characters of a Double IPA rather than the deep, bold sweet malt and spicy characters of a Quad. No booze - so that's worth noting. Light to medium body. The taste: can you say hoppy grapefruit and melon? I know they market this as a hoppy Quad and at least for the hoppy part - I give it high marks. But come on, I would have liked just a hint of raisins, licorice,Belgian yeast, or sweet malts that usually define a Quad with perhaps a big hoppy finish. I did not get it. Maybe my bottle was bad considering the high grades this is getting.

A - This pours a medium amber gold color that's not a Tripel color and not a Quad color, thick white creamy lacing ring. S - Spicy citrus rind with tropical presence. T - Citrus, melons, spicy lemons, honey, earthy, yeasty M - Heavy, thick, and full bodied and very smooth. O - Holy crap, this is a weird little monkey. Quad color? no. Quad taste? no. I'm ignoring the name of the beer - Victory is screwing with our mind!!

750 ml bottle into a Wine Glass. Ok, I am reviewing this based on a High Gravity Hoppy Brew and not a Belgian Quadruple. Victory is pretty much saying "Style Guidelines Be Damned!". Well enough jibber jabber, let's get it on! While I popped this baby's Cork, she made the most sexiest sound possible. It was a rich Pop! I had to put that in here because it was other worldly the sound this brew made. So now I pour this "Quad" into my Wine Glass, she Pours hideous for a "Quad". Yet, again I am judging this on a HG Pale Ale and not the Dark Malted Beverage we've grew to love. She pours a nice Copper Tone on the verge of being Bronze. Nice looking really. She was crowned with a huge soapy white head that lasted a few seconds. Looks Belgian enough! Aroma Therapy should tell me which direction we are going in! Wow, first waves of Citrus being Molested by some Tropical Stone Fruits. Picture Oranges and Lemons with the back up of Grapefruit being Raped by Honeydew Melons, Pineapple and Un-ripe Mangos. Some ripe Berries getting in on the action too! Yeah this brew is pretty enjoyable to smell. Let's taste this Biatch! First hits you with Malt sweetness that flows into heavy Citric tones of Oranges and Grapefruit. As it follows through notes of Lemon Zest gets to present itself in diligence. As this party continues Blueberries comes in for a visit yet gets broadsided by some Pineapples and Passionfruit. Then Honeydew Melon shows up wearing a toga bringing that refreshing Quality. This finishes Dry with some Booze but not offensive. Fruity esters in the aftertaste resembling Orange Fruit and subtle Tart Berries. The feel is Medium Built With that Soft Carbonation. Feels pretty on the Palate. Overall: I'm not rating this on a BSDA/Quad style because it's neither. Yet this is helluva Hoppy Brew. So I'm grading this on a IIPA or "Quadrupel" IPA, if you will. This outshines a few brews in that field...hence my score. This is enjoyable for a Hoppy Brew so don't let the Style Nay Sayers get the better of you. This a nicely crafted brew that showcases Four American Hops and Belgian Yeast. That's all I went into while rating this. This brew is Worthy.

Corked and caged 750mL bottle from Sherlock's (Marietta, GA). 8.99. Bottled 8/31/15. Served in a Barrel and Barley teku. Pours a hazy, pale amber with a tall, three finger pilar of white foam. Looks very pale for a quad. Retention amounts to some sparce surface splotches and a full halo thats only resulting lace is near the top of the glass where the head rested. Aromas of citrus zest, melon, caramel, papaya, a little hint of apple and a vague note of fruity Belgian yeast. The nose has more in common with an imperial pale ale than any other quad I've encountered but smells great nonetheless. Flavors are vibrant and full of both hopy and yeasty fruit notes. Mandarin oranges, golden raisins, melon, peach, apples, berries, papaya, caramel, faint chocolate, a little toffee and a noteworthy alcohol punch. The Belgian base elements seem to lean a little closer to a strong pale than quad but as in the nose the net result pleases me so I'm not complaining. Despite the booze heft this is surprisingly easy to drink considering the 13% abv. Full body, somewhere between creamy and resinous with softly fluffy carbonation. Peach, orange, caramel and raisins linger in the aftertaste. Victory's Hoppy Quad is a bit more of a hoppy Belgian strong ale than quad but was still quite tasty. I found it to be a worthwhile brew and interesting style mash up but will pass on buying more unless it makes it into four packs of smaller bottles.

One of the best beers ive ever had in my life, Right up there with VR, Prop 13, etc....Coconut bomb. 1000x better than Last Buffalo. if you are able to track one of the OG bottles down, do so. You wont be disappointed

Beer was very dark with no light passing through. No head on top of it. Smells very sweet with the bourbon and and coconut. Tastes even sweeter than last snow. Can't taste the bourbon, only coffee and coconut.

A dangerously good tasting beer but not a traditional quad - colour is too light, not enough yeast flavour - but who really cares! It's creative, distinct - and alarmingly easy to drink for such a high ABV. Yes it has malt character and some year flavours and of course hops but it's not a Quad in the traditional sense.

750 ml bottle into chalice, bottled on 8/31/2015. Pours slightly hazy/cloudy deep golden yellow color with a 1 finger dense white head with good retention, that reduces to a thin cap that lingers. Nice spotty lacing clings around the glass, with a fair amount of streaming carbonation. Aromas of big lemon, peach, apricot, mango, melon, berry, pineapple, pear, pepper, pine, light honey, white bread, herbal, and floral/grassy earthiness. Fantastic aromas with great complexity and balance of bright citrus/tropical hops, fruity/spicy yeast, and moderate pale malt notes; with great strength. Taste of huge lemon, peach, apricot, mango, melon, berry, pineapple, pear, pepper, pine, light honey, white bread, herbal, and floral/grassy earthiness. Good amount of peppery yeast spiciness and piney bitterness on the finish; with lingering notes of lemon, peach, apricot, pineapple, mango, melon, berry, pineapple, pepper, pine, light honey, and herbal/floral/grassy earthiness on the finish for a while. Fantastic complexity, robustness, and balance of bright citrus/tropical hops, fruity/spicy yeast, and moderate pale malt flavors; with a great malt/bitter/spiciness balance and zero cloying flavors after the finish. Good amount of dryness after the finish for the ABV. Medium-high carbonation and medium bodied; with a very smooth and moderately crisp/sticky mouthfeel that is great. Alcohol is very well hidden with only a small warmth lingering after the finish. Overall this is an incredible pale quadrupel style. All around awesome complexity, robustness, and balance of bright citrus/tropical hops, fruity/spicy yeast, and moderate pale malt flavors; and very smooth and crisp to sip on for the huge ABV. A highly enjoyable offering.

L: Pours brilliant burnished gold under a 3” white, very finely bubbled, mousy foam stand that produces Belgian window lace and takes over 3 minutes to descend to 1/3 its original size. S: Moderate hop aromas consisting primarily of citrus, some faint resin, some biscuit lies faint in the background, traces of stone fruit. T: A big, layered citrus palate with contributions from more than one variety of hop in addition to the yeast. Medium stone fruit supported by a medium to medium high hop bitterness and a layer of malt. Traces of tropical fruit. Good balance between the slightly warming alcohol, the malt sweetness, the yeast flavors, the hop flavors and the hop bitterness. While there is a light sweetness though out, the finish is dry with a little juicy tartness. F: An absolutely delightful texture. Medium body and medium high carbonation. Very creamy with almost a wild yeast character. Does not taste or feel like 13% abv. O: Exceptional beer.

750 ml bottle. Incredibly clear golden body with a fluffy white head. Great retention and lacing. Despite a killer appearance, this certainly no where near resembles a 'Quad.' Aromas of pale malt, dough, hops, tropical fruits, yeast esters. Flavor is clean light malt, yeast, citrus fruits and a nice slightly bitter hop note. Strange but good beer. Does not drink anything like 13%!

750 ml bottle poured into a snifter. Appearance Gold with 1/2 finger of white head that dissipates quickly. Hazy with some yeast sediment. Moderate carbonation. Nose Honey, candy sugar, light toffee, slight banana bread, peach, pina colada, tangerine, and pine. Taste Big honey and candy sugar maltiness. Slight toffee and butterscotch. Balanced hops with flavors of peach syrup, pina colada, and tangerine. The Belgian yeast flavors are kept to a minimum with slight banana, earth, and spice. Finishes with some lingering pine resin. Some alcohol heat is present. Mouthfeel Medium bodied, crisp, oily, semi-dry, and warming. Overall Sweet, fruity, and warming. Unique with a nice hop profile.

Wow, what an outstanding brew! Jet black beer in a glass, mocha colored head. The lacing sticks to the glass like glue. The aromas I am getting are black coffee, espresso, milk chocolate, maple syrup, oak, and bourbon. As far as the taste, this brew is quite a treat. The flavors go very well together. Coffee and chocolate are most dominant, with a maple syrup finish that sticks to the palate. I hope you were lucky enough to get your hands on a bottle.... or ten.

A: pours up pitch black with an off-white to brown head, it looks as it should S: as described but, the maple and bourbon dominate as a pair to a staggering degree, accentuating and reinforcing one another, along with chocolate and coffee of course T: Bourbon first, then maple syrup, then chocolate, it is important to note that this is much sweeter than kbs M: thick as thick can be O: Better than KBS, but not by much, and not nearly as different as I thought it might be, the only real differences I found were surface ones (the bourbon/maple syrup mix, and the sweetness), excellent, but not any more essential than KBS
This is even better than KBS with a fuller feel and a tad sweeter. I was not expecting this amount of flavor while still being approachable. The only drawback is cost and availability.

Pours a dark brown color with a beautiful, creamy brown head with good retention and lacing. Aroma is sweet and not as boozy as you might expect. Bourbon is there, but more maple syrup, molasses, slight coffee and rich, candy, chocolate notes. Taste is big, bold, and complex .Creamy, sweet, and flavorful. Sweet molasses, maple, caramel, bourbon, milk chocolate, lightly roasted coffee. Flavors really linger on the tongue. The maple syrup does a nice job of balancing out the 11% alcohol, giving it a nice balance of bite vs. sweetness. This is big and filling. Coffee notes intensify as the beer warms. Sweetness doesn't fade (a welcome trait for such a delicious beer), and finishes surprisingly bitter on the back end. Moderate-heavy body, big aftertaste, well carbonated. This beer is a meal. Drink it on an empty stomach (as I did) and it'll do some damage, or drink it after a meal and it'll fill you up. Definitely more of a sipper, but it is a very drinkable beer. As step up from the already legendary KBS, this one is a must try for any beer aficionado. Big and boozy, this is as dangerous as they come.

Somehow, I just knew I was gonna be the asshole on this one... CBS pours a nice and deep dark brown, almost black. It has a slightly tanned white head with mild retention and even less lacing. Aromas of chocolate, bourbon, vanilla, oak, mildly roasted coffee, and toffee (syrup?) Fill the nose, but none are overly assertive. The flavor starts with a tingly coffee note. Chocolate, burnt toast, oak, and syrup follow in that order. The syrup seems to linger. The feel is smooth and rich. This may be the best part. It's roasted qualities lend a balanced feel, however the syrup sweetness stays, and stays with that same initial tingle. I'm ecstatic to have tried CBS, and quite frankly humbled to have the opportunity. I feel it is a very good beer, but not the end all be all. Would I try it again? Absolutely, for $8 a glass, but the $25 bottle price tag is a bit steep in my opinion. Cheers.

Look: Black with medium khaki head. Has low carbonation, Smell: Dark Chocolate, oak, sweet maple, candy, and marshmallows. Taste: Dark chocolate, oak, sweet maple, candy, and marshmallows. Mouthfeel: Medium light. Overall: A great barrel aged stout, but a little light on the maple.
I went into this one expecting it to be overhyped. Wow was I wrong. This is the real deal!

almond head is THICK with almost magenta hue smells like a 100 Grand candy bar tastes unreal. chocolate pancakes. surrealistically smooth. near waterlike first sips. a little boozy. overall. hype worthy. 100%.

S: Maple syrup, coffee, subtle chocolate. It smells wonderful. Interestingly there is no bourbon on the nose. T: Once warmed up a bit after taking out of the fridge the notes settle to a pervasive maple syrup dominance, chocolate, coffee bitterness, and bourbon burn. It is interesting to see how this beer changes amongst the temperature regime between refrigerator chilled and room temp. In my opinion, in the middle of the range the beer has the best maple forward flavor but also a much more forward coffee bitterness. It is interesting to see how the green pepper/chili pepper characteristics from the coffee come forward during the duration of the tasting as well as the dark fruits. It was a roller coaster while tasting this from a bomber and taking time to do so. Absolutely fantastic and unique. M: Creamy, but also lighter bodied for a stout. I would say it is borderline imperial porter/imperial stout in terms of mouthfeel, but it does not take away from the beer whatsoever. O: Definitely worth going out of my way to get. I suggest chilling this beer to equilibrium in a refrigerator, but do not let the initial sip skew your opinion. As this warms up it changes dramatically and becomes a phenomenal sipper.

One of the most unusual stylistic craft beer combos I have tasted in a while. Is this a Quad or is it a combo of styles? Pours a light copper-golden color. 2F head. Carbonation bubbles from the bottom of the snifter. Semi-Pilsner in appearance. Aroma: not strong. Tropical fruit. Malt. There is a tart bitterness to this beer. The taste is mostly tropical. With warming new fruit flavors settle in. Tangerine. It's almost like a tropical fruit punch. The style throws me off: tropical fruit, malty, light body, quite hoppy. Is this a Quad? I am not used to light body, tropical fruit, and bitter hoppiness in a beer, Very dry hoppy finish. Overall- quite unusual. I like unusual. Not your standard fare. Check it out.

c&c 750ml into a Duvel tulip at fridge temp. Look: golden orange with a thick head that dissipates after a minute, leaving some spotty lacing. Smell: I'd say banana and lemons, which is true, but it's a bit sickly, like cleaning products (or something you'd use cleaning products on). Taste: lemon candy, grass, banana, booze... all with a distinct post-digestion tinge. Not quite drain-pour-worthy, but not pleasant. Feel: on the thick side of medium, juicy, alcohol heat. In another beer, this mouthfeel would be great, but here, it just serves to amplify the bad aspects of the flavor. Overall: what a disappointment. I love a good Belgian IPA, and a good TIPA (and a good quad, for that matter); this is just sort of a mess.

This exceeded my expectations on every account and basically stole the show during a recent visit to Victory. It's certainly not a Quad - more like a Belgian triple IPA. Juicy and sweet (but not cloying) and only mildly phenolic. The nose says big american IPA, while the flavor profile adds mild banana and spice to the big hop presence.

On tap at the Victory brewpub in a tulip. Color is pale orange-gold with a slight haziness. Good head that leaves an avalanche of lacing hanging off the lip of the glass. Smell is very floral with some citrus. Taste is some mix between a Belgian IPA and a big old American DIPA. Has a distinct orange juice aspect to it. I think the Belgiany-ness comes through mostly on the finish where you get a hit of sweetness, but not malt sweetness. Lastly, the alcohol is just not there on the taste at all. I had one, would have had a few more, but that didn't stop me from feeling it in an hour. Dangerous in that regard.

Agree with the others - this is no quad, but a damn tasty beer. If I blindly tasted, I would say it is a hefty Belgian IPA. Maybe a new style - Belgian Barleywine?? Anyway, it's quite good and would gladly have another. The 13% ABV is almost criminally well hidden and the hops work well with the base beer. I love the effort by Victory.

Look -slightly hazy golden/amber with a ridiculous amount of head poured from a 22oz into a pint glass...dissipates quickly...good lacing Aroma - definitely the pilsner malt and belgian yeast (that I unsophisticated categorize as the Belgian-style), hop complexity without one standing out...not an overwhelming citrus smell but there Taste - definitely has a hop complexity with a slight alcohol aftertaste (but much less than I expected for the ABV) probably driven from the sherry (with is noticeable). Surprisingly, this beer doesn't retain a lot of the American "Belgian-style" stereotypes in its taste. Flavor - medium bodied with good carbonation. Has a slow sipping creaminess. Overall - Very nice mix. For a traditional DIPA lover and non-Pilsner, wheat, Dubbel fan, this is a very nice blend...The ABV is well masked in this beer and the hop complexity is nice. Not sure whether the sherry is an add or an unnecessary component.

This definitely doesn't look like a traditional quad at all: it's golden in color, with a tall white head. It does look good otherwise. The hop profile on the nose throws me for a loop - they're very citrusy and tropical instead of piny and bitter. I don't get much in the way of Belgian yeast, however. Its flavor doesn't throw me for a loop, it's exactly what I expected. It starts with some nice citrus flavors, while it finishes with hints of bread, black pepper, and gentle dark fruit. The depth is pretty nice, though not world-class. Being a 13% mammoth, a little bit of alcohol comes through, though nothing excessive or harsh. Same with the sweetness level: the finish is slightly sticky, with the hop level keeping things just dry enough. The way the shocking lightness and warming fullness somehow intertwine perfectly is just jaw-dropping. Although it's not very quad-like, it works ridiculously well as a massive Belgian IPA. 4.07/5: Best quad bastardization ever!

Pours an almost entirely black color with a fluffy, big, dark brown head. Has a fantastic nose, full of roasted coconut, flowery, earthen coffee and a smack of toffee. Offers a hot chocolate quality with lots of melting cream in it, topped off by a slightly spicy, still floral barrel. Very convenient on the nose, with a prominent coconut-coffee interplay. Drinks creamy soft with a sparkly hint to it, lighter mouthfeel, malty sweet and complex, due to the well integrated barrel and the adjuncts. Tastes of toffee, earthy coffee with a roasted, dry hint to it, topped off by rock sugar. The barrel adds a warming note to the flavors, enhancing the already established coconut sweetness, together with a flowery note and a spicy bite. A prominent creaminess softens the barrel and brings out rock sugar even more, complimented by a wooden coffee dryness. Finishes with alcohol soaked pralines, fudge, maintaining coffee and a hint of toasty coconut, long and tasty. Pretty tasty and well composed, apart from its thinner mouthfeel. The barrel itself acts as a link for the different adjuncts, smoothing out the different flavors very well.
Good mouthfeel and decent nose of coconut. Felt like all the flavors were there, but a bit muted. Not sure if it is falling off or not, but still a delicious brew

Poured from a growler. The beer pours a deep black color with a dense, tan head that lingers, leaving thick lacing. The smell has tons of bourbon and strong coffee. There is a sweetness underneath. The taste follows with a strong coffee and bourbon presence. The sweetness and chocolate really come through strongly making this taste like a chocolate-covered espresso bean. There is a slightly bitter chocolate finish. The mouthfeel is perfectly smooth with a nice thickness. It coats the mouth nicely, although it may be a bit thinner than some of the other huge BBA stouts. However, that doesn't detract in the least. This beer is basically perfect. I'm excited to try it with a little age. If the coffee and bitterness fade slightly I think it will get even better.

Having this on-tap at Lizardville in Bedford. They are only doing 5 oz. sample pours in snifters. This beer is a very dark brown, almost black color with a tan head that quickly settles to a thick ring lining the inside of the glass with a big cluster swirl in the middle on the beer's surface and good lacing. Aromas of toasted, roasted caramel malt sweetness along with a strong whiskey oak presence, some maple, and that's pretty much it for the smell. The taste is pretty much the same, with roasted caramel malt presence and a very nice whiskey oak flavor and maple that adds a nice balance and some additional sweetness. This beer is not overly sweet in way at all though despite the total lack of a hop presence as far as my palate is concerned. Really very nice and good! Some similarities yet so many differences from the many bourbon barrel aged stouts I have had. This is one of a very few, and quite possibly the first, whiskey barrel aged stout I've ever had. Has a slightly crisp, so incredibly smooth, silky and delicate, yet just slightly prickly medium to full bodied mouthfeel with moderate carbonation. The 10.6% ABV is certainly well masked, that's for damn sure! Has a very clean and smooth finish. An amazing beer all around! Eric

2017 back stage series Look: motor oil black, 1 inch khaki head Smell: maple syrup+coffee+bourbon, it smells amazing Taste: huge coffee and maple front but fades quickly, middle is strong dark coffee, bourbon and maple. Body: moderate carbonation and a moderate body, not as velvety as ud want.

0% 2017 version poured into a snifter. Opaque dark brown color with a fairly robust tan head. Incredible aroma - fresh coffee, maple, bourbon, chocolate, some vanilla. Smooth as silk on the palate. The coffee was front at the onset with a melding of the maple, bourbon and chocolate. Just fantastic. Not too sweet and not boozy.

This beer is so smooth. I get a good amount of maple syrup in the nose. The taste is a lot of bourbon, chocolate, and maple syrup. I get a lot of bourbon as it warms. One of the few whales that lives up to the hype!

Pours jet black. Aroma, bourbon, coffee, fudge, kinda jammy, toasty. Taste- light coffee, light milk chocolate, nice sweet taste after those. Raisins. Nothing off putting or harsh. Not overly bitter. Has a sweet finish. Mouthfeel is thick and smooth. Overall this is tasting mighty fine! Honestly one of the best adjunct stouts.
This beer is more or less perfect.
Draft

Poured from a 750 ml bottle into a tulip glass. The pour is pitch black, like straight motor oil, with a healthy finger of thick mocha head. The head literally does not go away, instead electing to settle into a blanket that envelops the top of the beer. The aroma brings a hefty wave of maple syrup, roasted coffee, vanilla, oak, and sweet milk chocolate. Pretty much exactly as advertised. The flavor is just stupid. Holy mother of all that is good in this world. Loads of milk chocolate notes flirt with the palate before a huge wave of coffee comes and seals the deal. But the night's not over. Coffee brought his friend maple syrup along and they're planning a menage a trois with my taste buds. My mouth just got laid. The feel is full-bodied with soft carbonation. Very creamy and smooth, yet a touch syrupy and sticky. But that's what happens when your mouth has a threesome. Overall, this is absolutely one of the best beers I've ever had. Call me a slave to hype but I fell in love after the very first sip of this nectar of the Gods. It brings everything to the table yet stays remarkably balanced and restrained. The maple syrup dances beautifully with the sweet chocolate, while the coffee keeps the sweetness in check like a strict chaperone at a High School dance. I'm so happy I got to try this.

A bomber bottle shows 2017 release at 11.7 abv poured into a tulip glass. Look- A awesome dark black with two solid fingers of brown foamy head. Nice lacing down the glass. Smell- The coffee is slightly more dominant than the succulent sweet chocolate. Just a hint of alcohol which I’m guessing is from the bourbon barrels. A fantastic mix of aromas. Taste- The coffee is not as dominant as the smell indicated. The maple syrup really blends with coffee and then a fantastic hint of bitterness. Feel- Light carbonation with slightly sticky feel. A nice sweet aftertaste that leaves you wanting more. Overall- Definitely a world-class stout. A great taste with a big abv hidden in it. I’m going to age one of these and try to wait a year to try it.
2017 vintage drank on draft on 11/30/2017 great beer overall, the maple and coffee were molded together uniquely, nice chocolate and oak

Hazy tangerine color, beautiful lacing Mango, melon, citrus, dank Sweet stone & tropical fruits upfront, pine, so freakin juicy Slick mouthfeel with enjoyable bitterness Definitely one of the best dipa's I have ever tasted!

Can from jc1762. Thanks Jon. A passionfruit donut beer? And with cocoa nibs and lactose? Just why? Why? Why? Why? I guess this is the proverbial straw that broke the camel's back for me. Odd, sweet, wrong. Can we stop trying to make beer that tastes like tropical donuts and just make an honest and delicious beer?!? There is no way I can enjoyably tolerate more than a couple of sips of this. Gimmicks. Marketing. Sales. Being different for the sake of being different. Just because you can, does not mean you should.

Served on-tap at the brewery. A - Pours pitch black with a nice one finger tall off white head, dissipating down to a light film, leaving small trails of lace down the glass. S - Smells of raspberry pulp, dark chocolate, vanilla, dash of hops and some dark roasted malt. T - Starts off with some dark roasted malt quickly giving way to hints of juicy tart raspberries and dark chocolate sweetness. Some vanilla, day old coffee and light hop bitterness round things out. Finish is fruity with some dark roast, lingering on the palate long after the finish. M - Heavy body with moderate carbonation. Dark, fruity feel from start to finish. Booze is hidden well, only really showing itself toward the end of the glass. O - This one was spot on from the description. It had plenty of raspberry to offset all of the dark flavors yet it remained quite drinkable. Definitely worth a shot if you get the chance.

On-tap at the Troegs Brewery. Appearance: The head and lacing are light tannish. Th head disappears quickly after pouring. The beer itself is an obscure and dark black with a shade of light red. Smell: The beer mainly smells like a chocolate raspberry cake. The chocolate and raspberry mix well with a bit of hops poking through but barely. Taste: The beer mainly tastes as it smells. The raspberry and dark chocolate tastes mix very well with the bits of roast malts and teeny bit of hops. Mouthfeel: Biting carbonation with a silky feel. Heavy bodied. Overall: An incredibly unique and delicious stout that I hope gets rebrewed and made into a seasonal for the winter or at least becomes more widely distributed.

This poured like black, shiny syrup and very dense foam. Aromas of cacao, malt and honey please the nose. Flavor-wise, there's plenty of dark chocolate, sweetness but not too much like seems to happen in many chocolate stouts. The beer is surprisingly well balanced, has a medium-thick body, and does a great job of hiding it's 7.5% alcohol content. Very nice overall.

Town Hall Outlandish arrives an opaque black color. The head is a balf inch of tan foam that lingers awhile. The aroma roasted mal, toffee, and milk chocolte. The taste has more chocolate than the aroma. There is still a ton of roasted malt, but the chocolate really carries the beer. The mouthfeel is medium bodied with appropriately low carbonation, and a creamy texture. Overall, there is a lot of flavor packed into this stout, and I really like that.

Deep black, small head. Intense aroma and flavor of roasted malts and dark chocolate, with a slight hint of smoke. Doesn't taste sweet but the lactose and lack of hops mellow out the intense roastiness, which could be too much in a dry stout.

Got to try this at the Columbus Microbrew Fest last weekend. Sadly it was the only one of the special rotating taps of CBC's that I got to try. Nice to see something completely different from CBC though, and on cask no less! Pours a heavy black with a tall mocha colored head. Smelled of dark toasty malts and some mild coffee notes. The coffee could have been a little stronger on the nose for me, but this certainly did smell like an inviting porter. Plenty of charred toast, dark bitter chocolate, and coffee flavors in this beer. In a catch-22 I had had some Founder's Breakfast Stout the night before so I had both a good baseline for comparison and at that, a baseline that set the bar way too high for this beer to ever hope to reach. The coffee tasted thick and cold brewed, I would have enjoyed a more robust and fresh flavor to it. The beer was medium bodied for a porter, slightly chewy, and silky smooth due to the cask. This was pretty drinkable for me though, had I not had to leave for the OSU game I would have certainly come back for a second glass of this. Overall a great new beer from CBC. With a little tweaking (or turning this into a heavier stout version) I would gladly buy this again and again - you hear me CBC? Please make more! :-)

This was really the only special CBC beer I got to try at the Columbus Microbrew Fest. Served from a hand pump. S- I wouldnt say the coffee here is quite as delicious smelling as I would like it. Its getting close to that wet coffee grounds smell. All is not lost though. Some subtle chocolate notes come up from below and give the aroma a boost. T- Coffee isnt in your face. It isnt terribly fresh tasting either. The finish is the best part though. Thats where the chocolate and coffee mingle and give it a nice smooth, creamy finish.

That 's what they call it-- an "Imperial Vienna Lager." It's a dark coppery amber in the snifter with a decent foam. Less fizzy than a lot of lagers. Mouthfeel is rich and full bodied. Taste is rather sweet with a lot of caramel at first sip. Malty and full of roasted grain, mellow, and smooth. There is even a little butter and a hint of caramel popcorn. Interestingly, the carbonation seems to be a fine-grained, slow-release affair that adds to the tremendous drinkability. Quite refreshing with the lager parentage in spite of the surprising alcohol level. On tap at the brewpub in far east Denver.
Perfect.

This is everything I'd heard about it and more. Scored a couple of bottles of it @ a pretty hefty price. (turned out to be worth every penny) as well as having some on draft at my local "boys" club in Port Orange, fl. ( A gem called the House4Beer and certainly not for just "boys").

I had high expectations for this beer after loving Last Snow. It did not disappoint! Awesome smell of coconut, vanilla, chocolate with a touch of bourbon. I find the smell quite intoxicating. For clarification, this is not the same as Snowed In as it is aged in Buffalo Trace barrels.

This one had it all! Nice dark thick stout (thicker than other FB stouts Ive had) with tons of cocoa, coconut and vanilla on the nose and the same on the palate but with some espresso thrown in. Nice bourbon barrel notes as well but not overpowering!

Unknown vintage; drank 9/23/15 @ World of Beer Evanston. Black/brown appearance. Tan head; decent lace. Milk chocolate, clove & sea salt notes in the nose. Creamy medium thick mouthfeel. Red licorice & fresh earth flavors up front; milk chocolate notes on the finish. Sweet cherry settled on my lips over the course of the quaff. Unique & very enjoyable!

Bottle poured into snifter. Dark color with modest carbonation and little to no head. This was originally called "snowed in" - the nose is greeted with coconut and hint of whiskey. This medium bodied beer is well balanced! The buffalo trace whiskey is subtle as is the coconut. Better than Last Snow!!

650ml bottle, 2016 release. Served in a snifter glass. Pours a dark chocolate brown body, mocha head comes up to about one finger, good retention, thin film, nice lacing. Smell is intense roasty coffee, more coffee, milk chocolate, touch of white chocolate, and bourbon sweetness. The coconut isn't really there. But the coffee is great. Flavour is more intense roasty coffee up front, transitioning into a milk chocolate, white chocolate sweetness followed by bourbon and a dash of coconut. That's pretty nice. It's all there for you to taste. Mouthfeel is medium bodied, creamy, smooth with a nice coconut and white chocolate sweetness on the backend. Another hit from Funky Buddha, I think I like this batch compared to last year's Snowed In.

It's a shame that this beer rarely sees the light of day. Much better than KBS in my humble opinion (CBS hid the booze better). Beautiful aromas of maple and chocolate and a mild peaty-ness. Tastes like a true Imperial Stout should. Creamy richness with mild maple and coffee notes. Glad to have had this.

12oz draft pour, served in a Great Raft snifter. Pours midnight black with just a ring of creamy beige foam that persists throughout. The smell is amazing- toasted oak, bourbon, and vanilla. The taste follows suit, with the oak, bourbon, and vanilla coming together in a perfect balance. The creamy mouthfeel intensifies the experience, leaving just enough behind to keep you coming back for more. The 10% abv is completely hidden in the smooth deliciousness that is Old Mad Joy, well done Great Raft!

This beer pours a completely opaque jet black that is darker than Satan's soul with a 1.5 finger, sudsy, coffee with cream colored head. Retention is excellent and there are tons of spots and chunks of lacing left all over the glass. The smell is very rich and complex. Every time I take a whiff it seems as though a new flavor has come to the forefront. Sweet maple syrup, brown sugar, bitter black coffee and chocolate all take turns battling it out for their share of the spotlight, complimented by a touch of bourbon dancing in the background. Taste is the same. The flavors compliment each other so well. The sugary sweet maple syrup is kept in check by the bitter coffee and the richness of the chocolate adds incredible depth. Sweet, but in no way cloying. Again there is not a ton of bourbon character, but definitely enough to make you stand up and take notice, especially on the finish. Feel is outstanding. Full bodied for sure, but still very smooth and creamy. The finish is definitely sticky, but less so as the beer warms. The amount of heat from the alcohol is minimal for the size of this beer. Overall this beer is absolutely fantastic and lives up to it's cult status 100% in my book. I will say that I prefer my BA stouts to be well balanced and not too hot. So if someone is looking for a beer that tastes like "licking the barrel" they may be disappointed, but for me this one is perfectly balanced and ticks all of the boxes.
Blis maple syrup smothers the coffee grinds down to it's chocolatey, rich core. Glad I had the chance to experience this legendary brew. World class stuff here boys & girls!
Very dark appearance with tan head that disipates quickly. Nice sweet coffee caramel aroma. Taste is also a nice sweet coffee caramel without any hint of alcohol taste

Only had the 2017, and although it was very great, not sure it lived up to the built up hype or actual previous version. Would buy again and again for sure, but had the BCBS coffee a week before and couldn't get enough of that on tap; this CBS I would stop after 1 or 2.

Loved this beer. I’m more into sweeter stouts with the barrel acting as an addition, not overpowering. Some like barrel dominant barrels, to each his own. Chocolate, coffee, barrel, and maple. Delicious with a mouthfeel that coats and lingers.
Good but, Ive been spoiled with a few other maple items that will top this. Hopefully will show up in a few years on this list.

Tasted from draft. Pours black with a beige head. Lot of lacing. Aroma is incredible. Maple syrup, chocolate, coffee and a hint of bourbon. Taste also incredible. Moderate to heavily sweet with mild bitterness. Huge flavor of maple syrup, caramel, toffee, dark chocolate, coffee. Creamy and chewy mouthfeel. Coats the palate and lingers. Astounding beer!
very good.

Had two glasses of this at a tapping. Tasted pretty good at first but half way through that maple syrup was just overwhelming and covered most every other character it may have had. 100 points, naaaa I don't think so. That's just the rarity talking. I felt I could have taken a KBS or even a Breakfast Stout and poured in half a shot of real maple syrup and come pretty close to it's flavor. BC is head and shoulders better.

A nice strong porter, if a bit hoppy for me. Bourbon and oak come through well on the nose and as it comes up to temperature the beer is sticky and bittersweet. Was hoping for more as I love Great Graft, but really can't be picky about a 10% brew that's unique and tasty.

Appearance: The body has a thick opaque gold color which makes in so that unless you hold it up to the light in the exact right way, you will barely see robust carbonation. However, you know it is there because the finger of head in produces stick around for some time. In fact, I'd go so far to say that I can't recall the last time I found a beer with head that suck around that long. It also manages to produce some lace, as I would expect. Smell: Has a dry white wine smell to it that dominates the nose and is backed by floral and a touch of biscuit malt. It is very powerful, and doesn't require any warming to come out at all. Good stuff. Taste: Unsurprisingly it has a very strong fruity yeast presence that seems to favour wine and grape as it quickly overwhelms some mild biscuit and dry bread taste which then encounters a slight sweep of earthy hops to round out the experience. Mouthfeel: I'm not certain if it is the carbonation or the dry yeast and hop notes that are to blame for it, but after the lovely wine aspect, it takes on an almost club soda like quality I'm not a big fan of. Thankfully, it doesn't carry over into the aftertaste which is a mild earth and floral hop note that never gets out of control. As the carbonation seems to settle down, it takes on a nicer creamy quality as well the mitigates that odd club soda presence. Drinkability: That dry note really does hamper it quite a bit, but thankfully because the aftertaste doesn't really stick around very long, it seems to cleanse the palate quickly. It certainly comes across as very light bodied, which I'm not sure if the best thing for it. That said, it's remarkably easy on the system. Final Thoughts: When I started drinking this, Duvel immediately came to my mind. However it seems this offering trades the unconcealed booziness of the beer in favor of a much lighter experience, but at the cost of that dry note that seems out of place. I'm kind of left wondering if a bit more malt was present to raise the ABV slightly, how would it fair. That said, I'm not a brewer, I'm a drinker, and this is certainly one of the better Belgian experiences I've had come out of Ontario. I'm certainly intrigued as to what the Dubbel, Tripel and Quads will be like now.

2018 release with a 13% abv... Deep, dark brown body is basically opaque in the glass; center-pour into a goblet only produced a brief fizz of tan foam across the surface that quickly disappeared... On the nose presents a nice boozy dark fruit aroma, like prune and date and fig, soaked in bourbon with hints of vanilla... Similar flavors on the sip, soft fruits, a little bourbon, with a mild tannic note and some suggestions of oak barrels... Has an appropriate sweetness but doesn't approach anything cloying, and some impressions of chewy orange peels and treacle add a great edge to the flavor profile... Body is medium-weight, retaining its integrity as a quad despite the potential thinning effect of being barrel-aged... Smooth and graceful, a touch of stickiness, little to no bitterness - and a slight herbal spice toward the finish to put a little tickle on the tongue... Any trace of that 13% abv is buried in the basket of rich fruits and sugars... A very elegant quad...
Wow! Wonderful!

Poured from a 2017 bottle into the test glass, served at cellar temperature. A - Deep dark backdrop, a quick to recede cap leaves traces of rings on the glass 0 S - Vanilla, dark fruit, bourbon thread, saturated fig dessert, cigar wrap tobacco. Exquisite. T - Follows the aromatics closely, add a bit of anise, merlot grape skin, toffee, complex only begins to describe M - Slick start, full in body, a dark chocolate dry spell exists in the middle, finish is semi sweet and luxurious O - What a delightful offering from a very talented brewery, worth every effort to try

Sweet smell, candy, toffee, caramel. The taste is acid initially, then a bit sour, sweet and crispy bitter in the end. Bourbon feel, planty, caramel, toffee, creme brullee. A nice surprise with a sweet mellow finish!

Tasted from bottle. Pours very dark brown with minimal head. Aroma is sweet bourbon, caramel, dates, toffee. Chewy and sticky mouthfeel. Flavors of bourbon, caramel, toffee, dates, maple. Very nice BA quad.

Pours a very dark amber / medium brown with minimal head, some lacing. Huge aromas of caramel, molasses, brown sugar, vanilla. Rich and smooth, loads of caramel, molasses at first, sweet but not cloying, dark fruits, dates, some raisin. Bourbon barrel aging rounds this off nicely and softens the beer. Thick and chewy with appropriate carbonation. Overall this is an outstanding beer, big and a little boozy, in a nice way. Hard to believe there are so many flavors in this beer without using adjuncts. 1/31/18 375ml bottle, 3/2017 bottle date 4.5 rating

Golden amber in color. Thin, bubbly head. Some lacing. Slight haze. The smel is light malt, faint hint of orange, honey & yeast. The noble hops bitterness give it a bit of herbal and earthy tones. Smooth and malt forward overall. Some sweetness initially followed by the bitterness. Crisp mouthfeel and dry finish. A decent APA in my opinion.

I bought a six-pack of Hopfen Spring in a grocery store. Poured in to a pint glass. Pours a shiny yellow/ gold color, clear with a this white head. Smell is faint, a bit of a sweet bread aroma. Taste is light on the malt giving way to a spicy bitterness. Pepper and dandelions as opposed to citrus and pine. Mouthfeel is light crisp and clean. Overall one of the better Pyramid beers. There are better pale ales out there but this one is passable.

Growler filled 2/16/17. Enjoyed 2/19/17 in my TH tulip. Look: Golden haze. This is the perfect beer. (10/10) Smell: Swamp, fruit, hops, sweet, sweat, funk, sugar, cotton candy, bubble gum. (10/10) Taste: Perfectly sweet, reminds me of a milkshake. Hoppy, Malty, perfect balance. Cotton candy, Bubble Gum, Spice, Herb, Weed. (10/10) Feel: Mediocre bite at first that mellows out with sweetness. Just enough alcohol, hops, malt, yeast. (10/10) Overall: This is my favorite offering from Treehouse. A stronger DIPA with a nice fruit complexity to balance out the Malt and ABV, it's hard to stop drinking this one. If you have the opportunity to try this one, I highly recommend it. Like MBC Dinner with an explosion of fruit and candy. (10/10)

As perfect a beer as I've ever had. Poured into a tulip, nice cloudy deep orange with a finger of foam. Melon/citrus smell and taste. No hint of the high-ish alcohol level is tasted. Usual silky Treehouse feel. Outstanding. This and Green are my top two choices from TH. I would change nothing.

Sweet Mississippi pours a black color, with a little head. Aroma is sweet, but light. Flavor has a nice creamy base, lots of sweet lactose and hints of chocolate are mixed in. Watery body. Overall, watery, but good flavors that are present.
A nice oatmeal milk stout that features plenty of cocoa, mildly roasted malt, and a sweet finish. Body is full for the ABV with a luscious finish. I would buy again.

On tap at the Red Paddle Bistro - Gunflint Lodge. Poured an opaque, jet-black color with a small, tan head of foam. It smelled of milk chocolate, caramel and floral note. Sweet chocolate and caramel flavors with a hint of bitterness.

Poured from a 12oz can into glass. Canning date is marked on can bottom as '06/29/17'. Can notes: "A THICK, RICH AND DANGEROUSLY DELICIOUS BLEND OF ROASTED MALTS, FLAKED OATS AND FAIR TRADE COCOA NIBS FROM EDUADOR." Very dark, opaque body. Bubbly tan head settles into strong cap and ring, minimal lacing. Smell of roasted malts, coffee, and sweet chocolate. Taste follows smell, with lots of sweet lactose. Very little bitterness. Mouth feel is medium. Oats provide silky, mouth coating. Very quaffable. A tasty sweet milk stout with lots of chocolate flavors.

Poured from 12 oz can into shaker pint glass. A: Pours a nice dark brown with 1 inch bubbly tan head with good retention. S: Chocolate, milk, and roasted caramel malt. T: Chocolate, milk, smooth oatmeal, roasted caramel malt, and a hint of vanilla. M: Medium body. Excellent smooth oatmeal feel. Creamy and darkly sweet. The clear highlight of the beer! D: Excellently crafted. Not complex, but doesn't have to be. Good sessionability too. Great job, Beaver Island!

6.5% ABV. IBU is 27 full bodied. Very dark, almost black in color. creamy, velvetty-smooth chocolate oatmeal milk stout. scent is cocoa. Nice tan head. Tasty stout with a nice cocoa balance. very drinkable if you like this style (and I do.)

A rich and somewhat boozy milk stout (6.5%)....big notes of milk chocolate, lactose, light coffee, and cream. Body is medium to medium full...creamy..just a hint of a splash of alcohol on the finish. Aroma brings java and chocolate with a light nuttiness as well. Impressive beer. Finishes clean. Has to be one of the states best milk stouts.

Can 16oz ABV 8.2%. Canned on: 3-16-16. Consumed 3-17-16. Not as fresh as I'd like. Poured into Game of Thrones: Ours is the Fury pint glass. Half inch offwhite foam head, fine bubble composition. Head persists at the time of this review. As hazy as advertised. Appearance akin to fresh urine from a patient with acute urinary tract infection. Also resembles apple cider. Aroma: grandmas peach cobbler, college buddies weed, unpasteurized Tropicana. Obvious prunes, figs notably absent. Taste: deconstructed Fig Newton reduction with peach glaze. Juice notes dominate the front end, gradually giving way to THE DANK TRAIN. Feel: perfect carbonation. Soft and pillowy like a tempurpedic (tm) in liquid form. Overall: definitely stirs the loins. Lives up to its name. on a scale of danker to wanker, I would drink this again. #wankerthoughts #blessed

Canned 3/01. Pours a very turbid, hazy orange color with a nice finger head that leaves a ton of lacing on the glass. Smells like a fresh bowl of mashed citrus fruit with a strong herbaceous note mixed in. Tastes like a fresh fruit smoothie; citrus, orange rind, peach, nectarine - awesome. Mouthfeel is pretty creamy for an IPA but I think Green still takes the cake. A killer offering from TH.

On tap at the really good beer stop. A: awesome cola like dark brown to black. Pools into a viscous and luscious shape in small amounts. S: huge coconut with a lot of creamy vanilla and a solid chocolate aroma. Smells like a delicious sweet treat of chocolate and coconut. T: Amazingl, the coconut and all that sweet aroma are present in the taste but not overpowering for what a great stout should be. Extraordinary balance in the flavors. The finishing taste presents some notes of coffee which was not as noticeable in the aroma until after tasting this delicious stout. M: Hard to find anything to dislike, this goes down so easily that this is truly a dangerous drink... I might finish a keg alone tonight. O: A real favorite for me among stouts. I have had some really good stouts and this plays well with the best of them. It definitely is a bit sweeter than some of my other favorites but that is just a nice change and characteristic of a lot of things Funky Buddha produces. They really hit a home run with this one.

Poured from a 22oz bomber into a Funky Buddha snifter. Thanks Matt for this bottle. Pours a deep brown body with a one finger off-white head that reduces pretty quickly to leave a ring of foam. On par for a porter. Aromas are rich and potent - the "almond joy" aromas that everyone describes are definitely there but it's much deeper than that. Vanilla, whiskey, and roasty coffee are also present in addition to heavy coconut and chocolate. On the tongue.. chocolate covered coconut macaroons upfront, followed by an almost smokey note, roasted coffee, milk chocolate, vanilla-bourbon, caramel, finishes charred and again, a little smokey. Mouthfeel is slightly thin, but this is a porter not a stout so that's OK with me. Low carbonation. Overall just as described. Worth a try.

On tap at ChurchKey for 2014 DCBW. Snifter glass. A: Pours blackish-brown with a finger of beautiful dense and well-formed dark brown head. Big swaths of lacing and excellent retention. Hard to imagine a better looking porter. (4.75) S: Loads of toasted coconut up front, ample melted white chocolate and dark coffee, fair amount of roastiness. Definitely not for the faint of coconut. Smells appealing, but is really, really heavy on the coconut. (4.5) T: Dark roastiness blends nicely with toasted coconut, which is again very prominent. Light to medium dose of coffee and charred roastiness which imparts a slight bite. A touch of sweetness adds to the palate, which unfortunately becomes a bit cloying over the course of a glass. (4.25) M: Medium-light, fuzzy carbonation and medium body. Mouth coating and a bit sticky on the lips. (4.25) O: Very nice, but the huge flavors and sweetness really limit the drinkability. Would be good in 4oz as after dinner digestif along with a dessert that pairs well with coconut. (4)

Look: dark cola, Dark brown pushing to black, no head Smell: it smells amazing, big coconut front followed by fresh vanilla and chocolate, finishes with a slight bourbon Smell Taste: it's a mound bar in a glass, but seriously it's huge coconut and chocolate followed by hints of malt, coffee and vanilla with a hint of barrel at the end. The Barrel isn't overly present but smooths everything out and comes in at the end as a sweet good night kiss. Feel: If this was easier to drink it'd be well impossible. It's medium body, light carbination and silky smooth Overall: one of the best beers on the market

Pours a crimson-hued mahogany with a sliver of fast-falling tan head. Viscious, scant lacing & less head retention S: Bourbon in spades, figs hiding around the edges, a little chocolate T: Follows the nose, a little vanilla, caramel & oaky dryness up front. A little fig, caramel, dryness, & Bourbon, plus vanilla & a touch of chocolate too. Finishes with figs, a touch of apricot, Bourbon, vanilla, & oaky dryness, plus a little dark cherry & just a little leafy hop MF: Medium bodied, near zero carbonation A nice take on the style, quite frankly I was expecting more, but well worth seeking out

L - Pours a dark brown body with a two finger medium tan head. Good retention and lacing on the carbonation. S - Some roasted malts and oak up front, mild bourbon and dark chocolate on the back side. T - Great mix of roasted malts, bourbon, oak and bitter dark chocolate. F - Medium bodied and medium carbonation. It has a wet finish and is very smooth. O - For a BA baltic porter, it's legit. Not mind blowing and the flavors are a bit muddled at first but open up as the beer warms. But for a young brewery, it's pretty well done and very drinkable for 10% abv.

Thin mouthfeel, prevailing bandaid taste, very little barrel character. Some roastiness, very long and bitter finish. Medicinal as hell. Wanted much fuller mouthfeel, brighter and more specific barrel character. A disappointment.

Bottle shared by Zack. Thanks man. Happy NYE! Dark brown body with a thin cap that fades to nil. Aromas of coconut, chocolate, bourbon, oak, roast, char. Similar flavor. Almond Joy candy bars. Medium bodied with light sweetness, balanced by roast and char characters.

Pours like cola, no head Nose is like diving head first into coconut flesh, almond joys dabbing on your olfactory nerves, pure coconut, chocolate, and coffee, unreal how they extract this flavor First thing that hits you is the barrel, caramel, vanilla, maple. Finish is dark, bitter sweet chocolate, baking cocoa, and toasted coconut. Sticky sweet and full feel. A pinch of heat. Best coconut adjunct beer in the game. Funky Buddha hits a homerun with this one. If you like coconut and dark ales, this should top your wants.

22oz bomber bottled on 12/16/16 opened for NYE. L: Pours motor oil black with head that settles to a small mocha ring around the glass. No light shines through whatsoever, even when held closely to the light. S: Wow! Cheesy to say, and likely overused, but it smells like a mounds candy bar... chocolate and vanilla covered almonds with bourbon soaked coconut wafting from the glass. T: Tastes follows suit and delivers on the promise of the mounds aroma... milk chocolate, vanilla and coconut come in big waves with a little subtle coffee flavor balancing it all out. F: The chocolate, vanilla and coconut flavors keep developing as they sit on the palate, smooth and silky as can be. Overall, it's amazing. It's sweet... but as is the case with all decadent barrel aged beers, the truly world class use coffee in a subtle way that prevents the beer from becoming too sweet, and balances it out, instead of hitting you over the head with it. Hype is legit.

If you have had the pleasure of drinking Funky Buddha Last Snow, then you would definitely love this Imperial Porter. Rich notes of coffee and coconut and aged just right in Bourbon Barrels. If you have the chance to find this you will not be disappointed. IMO Top 5 Bourbon Aged brew.

I picked up three of these at the bottle release,at Funky Buddha Brewery in Ft Lauderdale.Poured from a 22 oz bomber,into a Funky Buddha snifter. Thick,creamy head,that is both brown,and light khaki during the pour,then turns a lighter shade of khaki upon settling.Dark black in color with no light showing through the glass.Very light carbonation. On the nose I get coconut,coffee,mocha,some toffee and chocolate.Also getting some vanilla and cocoa.The bourbon is there but it is very well hidden.The nose is pretty complex. The palate is mocha,chocolate,coffee up front,with a huge blast of bourbon in the middle.The bourbon is not overpowering or offensive.Tons of coconut,with some chocolate,and bourbon on the back end.I am also getting vanilla,cocoa,mocha, and toffee mixed in.There is a smokey aftertaste as well.The palate is insanely complex. The body is heavy and thick,and leaves a sticky chalky mouth feel.Nice warming alcohol finish. I waited in line for an hour an fifteen minutes to get my 3 bottle limit and it was well worth it.I typically hate all coconut and coconut flavors, and I'm not a huge fan of bourbon either.But this beer is fantastic.The coconut and bourbon is so well blended with all the other flavors,it actually makes the coconut and bourbon enjoyable.I can't wait to try another bottle of this in six months.

Had this at an epic coconut stout tasting: Prop13, Decoherence, No Rules, Last Snow. This was the best beer there. Snowed In had the most dominant coconut flavor of all the beers we had and some of that is lost in the barrel aging, however I think it improved greatly. Aromatic rich whiskey, coconut oil, coconut flakes, fudge, barrel, caramel. All comes together really well without being too sweet. For the base being a porter it has a great viscous and slick mouth feel.

most recent batch drank in a snifter on 11/5/2016 Look - not super thick but more than expected, black with a light tan head. some lacing Smell - coconuty greatness! sun tan lotion was used to describe this but in a big time compliment. great balance with the oak, bourbon, milk chocolate, and some coffee Taste - follows the smell. really amazing. oak opens up more in the taste as does the coffee...toasted coconut deliciousness Feel - not super thick but this is incedibly drinkable and the flavors are nice and bold and lingering Overall - spectacular! i've thought most of the FB beers are overrated, but this is certainly not. I was excited as heck to try this and it exceeded my expectations. really phenomenal and whether or not you like coconut, i find this a beer hard for anyone who likes BA beers to not love.
A hot syrupy sugar bomb. Where's the bacon?? I'm a smoke beer fiend and this one was totally lacking. There was no nuance or complexity. I'd happily pour this on a waffle, though.

Finally. Last keg in the region. Tapped march 2017, from 2015 release. We had an official countdown from Founders. Midnight syrup black with almost no head. Not much on the nose, could be my environment getting in the way. Some maple syrup and cocoa. As it warms I'm getting more of a nose. Sweet bourbon. Light nail polish. Scores adjusted. Oh shit. This is incredible. Huge waves of bourbon, maple, and black licorice just invade the palate leaving syrup and booze behind. To say it's good is an understatement. The alcohol grows astringent but not for long as it turns to black jelly bean. Feel is huge, viscous, thick, syrupy...all the above. I'm having a 2015 KBS side by side and CBS is to KBS what KBS is to FBS. A killer.
would love to have this fresh

I visited Founders yesterday with my wife and my buddy to drink the wonderful rare beers that Founders had tapped for their annual Cellar Raid. Founders did not disappoint! The highlight of the day full of highlights was the tapping of CBS. Look - first glance of CBS was like many many other stouts that I have enjoyed in the past. Founders served their 8 ounce pour of CBS in a snifter. The beer had a slight head on it that quickly disappeared in a minute or two. Smell - you taste with your smell first and I knew I was in for a special treat with CBS. Coffee was the dominant note accented by the sweet maple and bourbon notes of the beer. No detection of hops whatsoever. Taste - I'm amazed that all the flavors in CBS seem to feed off one another. I hope this makes sense but the final product ends up even better than the sum of its parts. Just an exceptionally balanced imperial stout beer with the coffee, maple syrup, bourbon and chocolate. Feel - phenomenal aftertaste that stays with you. But it doesn't stay long because you want that next drink almost immediately. Not too heavy, not too light with a slight chew. And just carbonated enough to know it's there, but really, who cares? Overall - this is a beer worthy of making special plans to drink. You know a beer is special when it is introduced by parading the Canadian flag around the taproom while playing the Canadian national anthem. CBS is definitely worthy of being on everyone's beer bucket list.
One of my top 3 ever.

Smell: It's heaven in a glass huge milk chocolate and vanilla smooth bourbon with a fresh maple syrup sweetness that just makes this beer smell absolutely incredible! Taste: Holy shit this is the best beer I have ever tasted. It tastes just like it smells huge milk chocolate vanilla and maple dominate the beer. Never gets overly sweet balanced and a smooth bourbon booziness rounds Everything out. Feel: full body so smooth and creamy the beer melts in your mouth. Overall: like I said above the best beer I have ever had I'm at a lose for words!
Original review dated May 30th, 2015 got deleted somehow. Rating based on a draft pitchers at FW Invitational 2015 and 2017 bottles.

pours like oil. fresh coffee, and Bakers chocolate are the overlying flavors. can taste the maple on the backend but would like to see that taste come out more in the front with more of the ALC catching you on the rear.
Drank 11-13-16. On tap. Amazing!

Bottled November 2017; drank 2/13/18 @ the Yarchives. Black/brown appearance. A rough pour yielded a huge tan head; thick, frothy lace. Chocolate syrup, banana & faint smoke notes in the nose. Creamy, medium thick mouthfeel. Chocolate syrup, oak & mild honeydew melon flavors up front; a mild hop bite on the finish. Faint bourbon heat emerged as this warmed. Balanced & pleasant; not a mind-blower but a very nice barrel aged stout.

Poured into a Gulden Draak tulip. Pours a slightly hazy, medium golden amber with a nice two finger white head with good retention and lots of lacing. Aroma of bready malt, citrus hops with hints of tropical fruit, light stone fruit and light Belgian yeast. Flavor is sweet malt, orange family citrus and light stone fruit, especially peach, citrus hops with light pine. Medium bodied with light creaminess and peppery carbonation. This really does taste like a hybrid between a fruity Belgian quad and an imperial IPA. The IIPA hop profile kind of dominates the Belgian part, but since both are well done, this works fine. A lot going on here, with interesting interactions between the citrus and stone fruit flavors as well as the citrus from the Northwest style hops. Less piney than I'd expect from this hop bill, but still distinctive. Interesting and a worthy alternative to an imperial IPA. Not a classic quad, but does not pretend to be. Quite enjoyable. ABV well covered. Can't go wrong with Victory.
This beer is sweet and fruity. Tastes like Mad Dog 20/20 made with hops. I call it Quad Dog 20/20.

1. Motor oil meets chocolate. 2. Soak a Mounds in bourbon for weeks. 3. Coat it in more coconut and chocolate. 4. Little bit of crack for effect. 6. Liquify the above 7. Add powdered sugar for sweetness and thickening. 7. Mix with a touch of bourbon and milk-heavy cocoa. 8. Add marshmallows. Allow to dissolve. Yep...

I realize that this is a coconut beer but this has incredibly too much coconut. It's like a chocolaty Pina colada or a full bottle of sun tan lotion. It has more coconut aroma and flavor than an actual coconut.

2014 on tap at Barcade in NYC. Beautiful looking beer. Looks rich, gooey and still. La Brea Tar Pits in a glass. Smell and flavor show a sugary sweetness, roast and black licorice. I don't detect any coffee at this point really, though vanilla and some dark dry fruit may be residuals of that. Body is thinner than BCBS, but plenty gooey and sticky and with the sugary quality there's a distinct texture. Drinks easily.

Had 11/09/16 at a Founders event at Barcade Brooklyn. Won't go so far as to say it's the best stout I've had but it is in the running and deserves all the accolades it gets. Very smooth thick feeling beer with bourbon hitting your nose before notes of chocolate come into play. The flavor has bourbon, coffee, chocolate, and just a hint of maple. Complex amazing stout, hope to get lucky enough again someday to have it again.
On draft. Warm and smooth, mellow on the front, but a wave of coffee and maple on the back.

First had 3/8/15 at a tap takeover at the Tavern on Liberty. It was everything you want in a barrel aged stout. I look to find some every year along with KBS. Chances of getting a case or even a bottle of each every year are slight.

Pitch black, thick, small tan head and little to no lace. Coffee, toasted grain, sweet maple, and bourbon aromas flood the nose. Sweet toasted maple soaked grain, light bourbon, bitter coffee, vanilla, oak, light coconut, and vanilla. Nice thick feel, highly drinkable, coats the pallet completely and a touch dry on the finish. Otherworldly amazing stout. Great experiencing this. Stout Day 2016.
2010 vintage (in 2011), on tap in a short glass, smoooooooth, sweet, coffee... mellow, in a good way. Been looking for another bottle/glass ever since.
Best beer I've ever had. An awesome stout, the maple just pushed it over the edge. 2015 vintage on tap at the lionhearted pub in Albany. I wish I could get more.

22 oz bottle. No bottling info Pours an almost clear golden body with a white head .Some retention lasted till the last sip, some lacing Not a lot going on in the smell department. A very faint malt, That "Pyramid brewing" malt-yeast thing that I smell in most of their brews Taste follows in that there really isn't a lot going. A little hop bitterness I enjoyed the feel but it was a little round for an APA. More like a winter warmer Overall; To some extent a lot of pyramid beers are alike. This was like a bridge between Snowcap and Thunderhead IPA. It was ok but I won't necessarily seek it out...

Well, it's interesting, I'll give it that. Dark golden color with a white head. Juuuuust reddish orange. Not much happening in the nose apart from a bread crust. Taste is an immediate spicy, bracing hoppiness with a very slight treacly almost bubblegummy note. Feel is a little sticky & heavy for me. This is a weird one. I picked it up thinking it was some American advertising chicanery meaning it was a Kölsch. Nope! It finally occurred to me that this is basically a Märzen fermented with an ale yeast. If that sounds like your thing then go for it.

From the 12.7 oz bottle in a snifter via the brewery in Athens from our visit. This fantastic Belgo style beast pours a murky dark brown mahogany with a light head of off white foam that settles to a thin ring with subtle lacing. The nose gives rise to a multitude of mellow bourbon, dates, oak, vanilla, brown sugar, and mild Belgian spice with a touch of cherries. Flavors---wow....rich bourbon that has all the flavor without the boilermaker taste rides on a wave of brown sugar that mingle with raisins, dates, and vanilla with a mellow oak note. Subtle cherry and cranberry display themselves with warmth as well as a light hint of Belgian spice and toffee. Excellent mouth feel; full body, lightly sticky, lightly coating, warm, boozy, meaty, beaty, big, bouncy, low carbonation, smooth, and sweet on the finish without being overly cloying. Flat out fantastic. Cheers

This was poured into a chalice. The appearance was a nice dark brown color with some lighter brown hues closer to the top sitting just under a quickly dissipating finger's worth of white foamy head. Barely any lace. The aroma presented a wonderful blend of sweet bourbon woodiness over some caramel malts, Belgian sugars, some allspice and clove, Belgian chocolate, dark chocolate, some dark fruits (plums more so), and ended with a little bit of clean earthiness. The flavor was a fantastic blend of spices to sweetness running through all of the prior mentioned aromas and then all coming together enthusiastically in the aftertaste. The mouthfeel was about medium bodied with a fine sipping quality about it. Nice enough grip from the spices along my tongue but not so much distracting, just noticeable enough to prevent any stickiness, slow mobility I like to say. Carbonation felt right on par. ABV felt appropriate. Finish was somewhat sticky, but nice enough sweetness from the Belgian sugars and chocolates. Overall, very nice bourbon barrel-ed quad - fantastic in it's entirety and would make an absolutely wonderful sipper for Winter.

12.7 oz bottle poured into nonic pint. A: Almost no head whatsoever. Body is a rich dark brown leaning toward black with just the barest hints of light escaping. S: Vanilla, caramel, figs, dates, honey, and a little coconut. T: fairly sweet, lots of figs, honey, caramel, and vanilla. M: pretty thin almost watery no carbonation. O: the flavor of this beer is astounding, it’s got the best characteristics of the bourbon. Yet, it has some of the flavors of a great quad. This beer is worth checking out and a name to make you want to drink it.
2017 edition, 12% ABV. Fenomenal.

Bottle: A darker brown, seems to have maybe a slight haze, but darkness hides clarity decently well. Very thin rim remains with some time, though it was medium thin for a little while. No lacing. Nose is is a pecan accented quad - date bread with nuts, perhaps. The bourbon is light but noticeable, along with a nutty maltiness. Flavor is a little sweeter than the nose indicates, but I am okay with it. It's not overpowering, and includes the accent of the bourbon, including vanilla. And these are accents... noticeable but not overpowering. I keep thinking pecan pie, and while this is much less sweet than the dessert, I can't shake the thought for some reason. I think there is a light bite that acts as the spice, a mild nuttiness, and the bourbon quells but sweetens the date notes. Truly enjoyable, another beer where Jackie O's adds barrel notes subtly but enjoyably.

Dark brown lacquer with a minimal, thin tan ring. Smell is caramel, toast, fig, brown sugar, smoky maple and pumpkin pie--spices, crust and all. Taste is prune, caramel, chocolate, nuts, raisin and oats through a crisp, medium-full slick body with a sticky, semi-dry finish. Notes of mapled bourbon, toasted coconut, and warm peach cobbler emerge as it comes to temperature. Even though this one was a single element of the blend, I liked it better than Cellar Cuvée 11.
Holy coconut

Wow. And I thought Last Snow was good. This is elevated to another level entirely - such wonderful flavors and the nose is incredible. I really hope to grab another one this year, it is quite possibly Funky Buddha's best.

Wow, 2nd time having this beer, first time rating it.. Look- pretty thick with a small mocha colored head that vanishes quickly Smell- bourbon coconut chocolate, smells like if you dipped an almond joy in a glass of bourbon and took a whiff, coconut more prevalent as it warms Taste- literal bourbon almond joy, follows the smell to a T. I can't get enough.Adjuncts definitely more prevalent after letting sit out of the fridge for 15-20 mins Feel- solid mouthfeel originally, becoming a little syrupy as it warmed, not too bad though Overall- definitely one of the favorite beers to date. Haven't rated much on here but over 600 check ins on untappd. Funky Buddha is quickly becoming one of my favorite breweries out there, it's unfortunate they don't distribute to New York because I'd love to get last snow and their other porters/Brown ales

Poured from a 22oz into a snifter. Pours black with no head. Nose is full of coconut with bourbon poking through. Tons of coconut in taste followed by coffee with hints of chocolate and vanilla. Smooth barrel finish. Taste sticks around for a little. Great beer!

22oz bottle poured into a snifter A- pours a nearly opaque black color with a small foamy white head that reduces to a thin film and a ring around the edge, a bit of lacing left behind S- aroma is a perfect meshing of toasted coconut, spicing oak & bourbon barrel. Undertones of caramel, milk chocolate & vanilla T- spicy bourbon and and coconut dominate up front with a sharp spicy oak flavor. Mid-palate brings sweet cocoa, caramel, vanilla and dark fruits.
