The finish brings more coconut and toasted nuts, along with a linger of bourbon M- medium body and carbonation produces a somewhat thin mouthfeel with a foamy finish, abv bidden well O- bourbon is a nice addition to the coconut, only thing missing is a bigger mouthfeel

L: Inky black opaque hues with a thin sandy, tan head and moderate lacing S: Enormous coconut, mocha, and chocolate aromas with a bit of bourbon barrel - I don't want to undersell this. Snowed In has one of the most enticing, flavorful noses of any beer I've ever had - incredible T: In line with the nose, toasted coconut, rum, coffee, and milk chocolate flavors follow F: Moderate to thick mouthfeel and light carbonation O: Phenomenal imperial barrel aged porter. This beer encapsulates the sensation of drinking a decadent, thick caffe mocha with a shot of run whilst sitting underneath palm trees contemplating the transcendent, ethereal qualities of a rich, barrel aged porter. In short, Snowed In/Last Buffalo is a gorgeous and exceptional porter. If you can't find one to taste, at least grab someone's glass and smell it - this is one of the best smelling beers you'll come across - untouchable

Half finger chocolate brown head on a jet black body. Aroma full of coconut which wasn't lost in the BA process. Same goes for the flavor, coconut holding strong. Like morning wood I didn't get as much barrel flavor as I hoped. The barrel did more for the mouth feel, smoothing this one out and making it more oily. I wasn't a big fan of last snow but this beer was incredible.
Amazing double IPA. The smell and taste of this beer is incredible, orange and pineapple. Dark hazy color looks great in glass. Exceptional mouthfeel. One of my absolute favorites.
Poured from a can into a teku. Peach and tropical fruit in both the nose and taste. Classic TH mouthfeel, which sets some of their offerings apart. Worth searching out.

L: Murky, and yes hazy dark yellow orange. A beautiful glowing orb with some light behind it. Gorgeous pure white head leaving sticky lacing. S: A huge burst of spiced and hopped pineapple, orange and passion fruit. These folks need to make their own brand of candles. T: Bursting citrusy hops, amazing blend of sweet fruit and dry hops. Spiced orange on the finish. F: Very bright with huge hoppy feel and solid presence of carbonation. O: This is my new favorite TH offering. I wouldn’t change a thing and I’ll make the trip whenever this is offered.

There's not much I can say about this beer that hasn't already been said. I really love this beer! It's got all the great characteristics of a Tree House beer, but with a bit more attitude. The mouthfeel is absolutely perfect.
Fantastic. Treehouse classic.

Canned 03/01/16 Reviewed 03/02/16 Straw/lemon yellow and the name does not disappoint, hazy and murky. Thinnish, 1 finger white head almost like a nitro. Smell slightly underwhelming. Fruits Pineapple and mango BOMB, no malt backbone to be found yet not bitter at all other than a little grapefruit deeper into the pint. Delicious. Well carbonated and not cloying, edging on dry for the ABV. Fantastic beer. Can't wait to share with others.

Similar vibe to Julius, which I had just a day earlier. Same juicy flavors on the nose. However, unlike Julius where these orange and mango flavors are the star, in Haze the hops take center stage and the juice is the supporting cast. Same great unfiltered look and lovely mouth feel exist here as well. Very nicely done.

Not usually a big fan of IPAs or IIPAs because they are so often bitter more than anything else. This had plenty of lush citrus flavours, good acidity, and lush mouthfeel to balance out a surprisingly modest bitter finish. I could drink this and Heady any day of the week with no complaints.

Easily my favorite Tree House IIPA. It has the unmistakable Tree House creaminess and amazing smell when you pop a fresh can. Juicy, but less bitter than their other IIPAs. Definitely tastes better after a week or two like most canned hops, IMO.
0% The best stout I have tasted are there any better?

Had on tap at the Scuffer in Burlington, VT during the 2016 VT Brewers Festival. Absolutely delicious and incredibly well balanced. If you can find this unicorn I highly recommend it Just had 2017 version....even better than i remember
Fantastic beer. Really came through as barrel aged coffee stout. The barrel is beautifuly blended. The maple was lacking a bit for me. Overall a delightful treat!
Vintage 2017. Dark roast coffee, milk chocolate and subtle maple accents. Mild barrel presence. Nice balance throughout. Full texture with medium carbonation.
I want some more, I want some more
Dark pour with great head. Nice bold flavors with a taste of maple syrup. Amazing beer.
Just a whole lot of get in my belly goodness. Only had one time but WOW! So smooth and complex but not over the top.

2014 on tap at engine room. A: jet black, nice tan head and great lacing down the glass. S: Lots of bourbon on the nose with more coffee and chocolate at the end. T: Extremely smooth. Bourbon, coffee bitterness, some chocolate sweetness, and a little bit of maple. Wish there was more maple. But this stout is extremely well balanced. Compared to good morning its alot less sweet and more balanced. F: perfect, it's smooth, thick not sticky. Amazing O: very smooth well balanced stout with some amazing flavors.

Black as night. Coffee and maple on the nose. 2014 on tap for KBS release. I was expecting more maple favor but it mellowed with the age, so very smooth, drinkable coffee and chocolate sweetness with a subtle maple taste and still quite boozy.

Have had multiple times on tap at the brewery. A fantastic beer, but a just little too sweet for me. Definitely prefer KBS, but would take this over almost every other beer I've ever had. Definitely a beer that I would go out of my way to get again.
I am primarily and IPA drinker and am not a fan of coffee flavored or infused beer. So, in that vain, I did not enjoy drinking this beer. I think that there are other beers I'd rather be drinking.
This is the best beer I've ever had in my life. Had it at snallygaster last year and I literally couldn't believe what I was drinking. I've been chasing after it ever since.

Lives up to the hype. I've had it on tap twice. This is one of those few beers that I'll drop whatever I'm doing and go get a glass if I hear it's on tap somewhere in town. It's hard to go back to a plain RIS after drinking this beer. I find myself pouring maple syrup into glasses of Ten Fidy to make it palatable.
Good stuff. A bit overhyped but good

On tap at founders tap takeover. Pours jet black with small caramel color head. Smell was all bourbon, vanilla and hints of chocolate and maple syrup. Taste was immaculate. Kbs x10 is truly the best you can say. The sweetness from the maple gives it a taste and feel.that is top notch. Does not linger and keeps you wanting more. Overall the best stout I have ever had.

Sample at Mikkeller Beer Celebration Copenhagen 2017, green session. Aroma has toffee, bourbon and dried dark fruits. Taste is balanced. Lots of toffee, butterscotch, raisins with a light toffee sweetness. Aftertaste lingers with smooth bourbon.

Taste: crisp, semi sweet, caramel malts, some very gentle hops. Bready wheat, floral nose. Golden hue, clear, with white head and some lace. Medium body. tasty solid Pilsner with out bitter notes. 27 IBUs

On tap Pours a deep brown, small foamy khaki head. Smells of brown bread, caramel/toffee, dark fruit, bourbon & oak. Tastes of dark brown bread, fig, raisin, fruitcake, bourbon juice, oak, caramel, toffee and earthy wood. Viscous body with moderate carbonation, thick And creamy creamy mouthfeel and finish. Outstanding

Pour is a dark murky ugly brown with a small amount of tan head that dissipates immediately. Nose is heavy bourbon and some charred wood with faint notes of sweet candied sugar. Flavor is also heavy on the bourbon and wood, actually in a nice way. The quad doesn't make a ton of appearance, malts are actually fairly rich, a hint of malty sweetness in back. Fuller body, fairly dry, a touch chalky in the feel.

Bottle #136 out of 325, 2014 batch. Vanilla earthiness, caramel and oak in the smell. Lots of vanilla, toffee, caramel, and earthy rich sweetness. Some dark fruits. Nicely balanced between barrel and quad flavors.

Appearance - The beer was a murky brown color with some bubbles clinging to the sides of the glass. Smell - The beer had a nice bourbon nose with malty in the background. Taste - The bourbon makes the initial impression. Chocolate, caramel, tobacco, and make big impression with a slight nuttiness that is masked by the other action. The aftertaste is warming with the bourbon and chocolate staying strong. Mouthfeel - For a quad, I would have expected a little more thickness. That said, the beer meanders across the tongue. Overall - This is an elite bourbon barrel quad.

500 ml bottle, Morissons, Bristol - Pours clear amber with a thin white foamy head, which quickly dissipates. Medium carbonation. No noticeable lacing. Aroma - Sweet citrus notes - orange, grapefruit. Taste - Sweet forefront with a zesty citrus notes - orange, grapefruit leading to a long dry bitter finish. Saw this in the local supermarket, supposedly hard to get so gave it a go. For some the clean filtered character will appeal but not really for me. Feels like an upped ABV version of Oakham Ales Citra, a great beer which made me love US hops but since moved on. Nothing badly wrong with this,but personally too clean for me, even in the aroma.

From Labirratorium. In Ikea's pint glass. Playing Brothers A Tale of Two Sons. Fresh and refreshing, zesty, grassy,with citrusy citra notes standing out but still maintaining an english highly-drinkable character. Some sediments.

Bottle. Golden amber. Quickly dissipating head. Sweet phenolic hop aroma. Tangerine and grapefruit. Some malt is just discernible. Taste reflects the smell. Finishes with a light bitter bite. Nicely boozy. Medium carbonation and body. A high ABV beer that doesn't reach the flavour it deserves. I far prefer Proper Job.

L: -pours a clear golden-orange with a small to medium,offwhite head -low to medium carbonation visible S: -grapefruit,oranges,tangerines,grassy,spicy,peaches T: -Follows the nose plus honey -noticeably watery throughout the finish -low to medium bitterniss for the style F: -medium carbonation -light to medium body O: I drank this 2 weeks past it's best-by date, so i give it a bit of leeway. This is mildly decent overall, though a bit underwhelming.
L - hazy light orange S - hints of peach, some tropical fruit T - some fruit, slight bitterness, delicious! F - good carbonation, thick mouthfeel O - fantastic!

This is a special drink. Admittedly, I haven't had the base to compare it. Traded for this one due to my love of grand ma. The barrel definitely takes a back seat here. Orange is subtle. Possibly the greatest head I've ever seen, like cool whip. Booze is mostly absent, just a strong and well balanced wheat wine. I have trouble calling this a beer, but no trouble drinking it again. Nice job on this one.

I am now CANtinuing the seCANd phase of Happy New Against the Saugatuck Grain Beer Sunday (Week 699) & I am happy to be adding to The CANQuest (tm). From the CAN: "Saison style Ale"; "Brewer Owned"; "Art & Design by RobbyDavis.com"; "Strut Your Stuff!"; "Vous estes le Coq de rien! Suffice it to say, some beers are meant to be the cocks of walks. This sessionable saison is just that, striding confidently along that most fateful walk. Brewed with a dash of spelt and late hop addition, this frothy delight is bright, rich, and juicy. So, finir son verre!" Je parle un peu de la Francais, so the name means "Cock of the Walk", but then they go on to tell us that "You are the Cock of nothing!" The last bit means: "Finish your glass!" I had read that this one tended to be active so once I Crack!ed open the vent, I performed a gentle Glug into the awaiting glass. It initially formed some fizzy, foamy head on its own, but I was so engaged in my own actions that I failed to really take note. An in-glass swirl raised just under two fingers of fizzy, foamy, tawny head with very limited retention that quickly fell away to wisps. Color was a very pretty Golden-Amber (SRM = > 5, < 7) with NE-quality clarity, enticing The Gelt Gang of Mammon, Midas & Croesus to drop in for a taste. Nose had a light funkiness and a cracker-y maltiness. The CAN mentioned "spelt", which makes sense. Mouthfeel was medium, but very fizzy with loads of carbonation. The taste was kind of odd, very malty and as @metter98 said, more like a cross between a Kolsch & a Saison. There was a light funk and a light spiciness, but it was very dry and refreshing throughout. Warming, I began to taste apples, pears & white grapes. Finish was dry, almost champagne-like, especially given its carbonation.
Ordered a snifter at Hopcat in Grand Rapids. What I received could only be described as a salt lick, simply awful.
I felt like this was over carbonated.

What a disappointing brew. Tastes more like a kolsch than a farmhouse, it has the underlying sweetness of an adjunct lager, its body is similarly thin and the hops, which you do taste at at the finish, are almost there as an afterthought. Bad offering from an otherwise solid brewery.

A thanks to the founding father of the canquest, woodychandler, for this beer. Poured from a 16 oz. can. Despite no agitation, this beer came oozing out, resulting in a golden color with a 2 inch head. Smell is of lemons, some funk. Taste is unusual, green apples, lemon zest, musty, some hops. Feels medium bodied in the mouth and overall is a mediocre beer.

A: The beer is very clear yellow in color and has a moderate amount of visible carbonation. It poured with a half finger high white head that died down, leaving a large patch of bubbles on the surface, a narrow collar around the edge, and some lacing down the sides of the glass. S: Light to moderate aromas of green grapes and bready and crackery malts are present in the nose. T: The taste has flavors of bready and grainy (presumably from the spelt) malts along with notes of green grapes and faint hints of spices in the finish. M: It feels medium-bodied and somewhat crisp on the palate with a moderate amount of carbonation. No dryness is perceptible. O: This beer seems to taste like a hybrid between a Kölsch and a saison. It's easy to drink. Serving type: can

I live in Grand Rapids...and go to Founders weekly. Its very very rarely on tap, but when they do tap it, its gone within 20 minutes. I've had a lot of really good beers, but to be completely honest this is the best I've ever had and its not even close. The combination of maple syrup, coffee, chocolate, and bourbon barrels is unreal. This is 10x better than KBS and that's saying a lot

For being mainly an IPA drinker, I had the opportunity to try this beer, and for not liking stouts all that much, this is easily the best beer I have ever had, hands down. 10 times better than the KBS

Randomly on tap at a nearby bar... was extremely lucky to get over there and grab an 8 oz pour of it. Pours jet black... like motor oil (as anticipated). You get a decent amount of chocolate with nice hints of the maple syrup. The roasted coffee flavors weren't as pronounced. There is definitely some underlying bourbon, oaky and vanilla flavors as well. Mouthfeel was a little thinner than I expected; low carbonation. Overall, this one definitely lived up to the hype for me! Cheers!

Just an amazingly perfect beer. I love everything about it--from its complex nose and flavor profile of coffee, chocolate AND vanilla, maple and bourbon to its unbelievably smooth feel. I can't say enough good things. This beer truly deserves all the hype.

Notes from draft pour. Happy to add another to my list of Founder's stouts that I love. Great hit of coffee, chocolate and a nice hint of bourbon. The maple adds depth to the mouthfeel, for me it's a bit sticky but at 10.6% this is a really enjoyable stout.

Had on draft at Ashley's Ann Arbor, and more recently at the Wurst bar in Ypsilanti. Both served in small snifters. This elusive beer is worth seeking out. I long for the day they release it in bottles again, although it may cause a few BAs to commit all sort of crimes to get their hands on a few to stash. It is sweet, playful, and after two tastings, I long for a third.
Sweet, rich and warming. I was really excited to finally try it on draft a couple months back. I felt like a lot of the hype was warranted. Great Imperial Stout.

Bottle at my birthday celebration at CBC, London. What a great birthday surprise it was when Bruce pulled this out of his Tesco shopping bag (no, this beer isn’t sold in Tesco). Pours black-brown with a creamy, tan head. Sweet, dark malt nose, some chocolate. Big sweet flavor, dark sugar, chocolate cake, moderate roast. Full bodied with fine to average carbonation. Restrained warmth on the finish, very sweet and chocolatey, light maple notes, some wood. Lasting dark chocolate, dark sugar and baking cocoa. A powerful beer with an incredibly cohesive character. That’s really the strength of this beer, the fact that all elements seamlessly come together. I would say this beer is worthy of the almost universal acclaim it receives. I really hope to try this again sometime. Excellent.

man, this is one crazy beer. had on draft in savannah. poured a nice brown color. aroma is briney and chocolate and basil. taste is basil, chocolate and brine, finishes with definite shellfish. crazy.

It may have been the batch, it may have been the length of time that it had sat on tap, it may have just been the wrong day for my tastebuds, but this was one of the most undrinkable brews I have ever set to my lips. The nose spoke of stale lobster and burnt chocolate, while the taste reminded me of what a chalkboard might taste like if it was served as an entree at Long John Silvers.

L: Black with hints of brown at the edges, caffe latte head. S: Incredible. This is the most pronounced and natural coconut I've smelled on a beer. Much more present than Prop '13. Rich bourbon and chocolate to back it up. T: And it tastes just as good! So much natural coconut, rich bourbon and chocolate. F: As good as in imperial porter can get. I don't mind it though, and makes it pretty drinkable. Not think or chewy, but medium, slick, silky and a bit sticky. O: This is the best coconut beer I've had and one of the few that was worth the hype to me, more so than Prop '13.

My personal favorite beer ever from funky Buddha..... Mounds of coconut come through in this barrel aged version of last snow, dark chocolate and heavy barrel make this so incredible. The only thing lacking is the carbonation and head retention

Popped this bottle at an epic Omaha, Nebraska bottle share. Poured into a teku. What an amazing beer. Amazing flavors... very complex. It's the best Funky Buddha beer out there to date... Highly recommended!
Really dug Morning Wood and I enjoy Last Snow so I was expecting to love this, but the smell just came off as suntan lotion and I couldn't get past that and sweetness.

Pours golden and crystal clear with a white, frothy head that fades quickly. A bright fruitiness kicks off the aroma followed by a suggestion of spice and then a bready undertone. The flavor follows suit, characterized by a balance of juiciness, spice, and bready malt. The classic saison spiciness is more subdued in this beer, balanced but not overtaken by malt and hop flavors. The finish is dry with a lingering, medium bodied mouthfeel. This is a tasty saison, very balanced and particularly drinkable.

an enormous thank you to my man jeremy for sharing this rare gem, talk about being stoked to crack a bottle! what a furiously delicious beverage. thick like motor oil, shiny like anthracite coal, with very little residual head after the initial pour, and frankly with a value probably far higher than any fossil fuel now that this thing is so famous. huge coconut nose, almost so intense as to be artificial, but it isnt, and its awesome. toasted and sweetened though, its pretty far removed from the milky pulpy flesh of the fresh coconut, but its desserty nature is welcomed at dessert time. i get less chocolate here than it sounds like others have, but i sure do get the bourbon. vanilla sweet on the nose, with the booze not shy either, and obviously the sweetness that would have to be in a beer like this. incredible depth of flavor, much more than in the nose, with the coconut still way out in front, but this time more coffee, bitter and even a little acidic to help cut the density. the booze helps there too, and the chocolate has a bitter note as well, so everybody is trying at least! the beer is bigger than the barrel treatment too, which i was worried from the smell that it might not be, but it is, and i am glad. the bourbon is an accent, and the vanilla it brings out is awesome. it really does taste like a candy bar, but i still taste the grain through the sweetness. in some ways i like the base beer better, i think it holds up better with temperature, and i think its not so shockingly sugary, but the barrel adds more than one layer, and has made this a pretty coveted treasure for the palate. as much coconut as can exist in a beer. if you drink a bomber of this by yourself, you are missing the point. to be shared and sipped and savored, even when it isnt snowing out. just short of memorizing, but really really tasty and special

Pours a dark chocolate color. Has funny aroma it pick up chocolate or lobster. Flavor is meh, it's an ok porter with a weird aftertaste. I pick up no chili ate or lobster. This is just a mediocre porter to me.

Fascinating beer. Certainly in the realm of possibility for Dogfish Head and no one else. A porter with basil and (live!) lobsters. I'm not even a fan of lobster in food form (too much money and effort), but I'll try this gimmick. Def some salinity going on (maybe they should try a seafood gose?), and a sweet, fishy finish. Had the chance to drink one and it was a hoot.

Kinda feels wrong to harshly review a beer like this, as it's obviously not about winning competitions or even pleasing all palates -- in an exercise in creativity. Funny thing is, for the first 4/5 of the brew, it tastes like a well done porter, perhaps a touch of the smoky/salty brine sneaking through, but mostly just some nice, mildly creamy roasted malt taking charge. But then there's the finish... Oh my, the finish. You swallow, breathe through your nose, and suddenly a wild blast of fishy/briny sealife swirls through your sinuses. Insane. And, sadly, not super pleasant. It's not terrible either. It's not undrinkable. But it's also not something I'd readily order. Fun idea, but I just can't abide.

Porter is my favorite style so take that into account as you read this review. Not a flavor bomb like a lot of Dogfish brews. But more than just a rather nice porter-wise. What makes this extra special is the nose - the lobster adds a briny aspect that enhances the quality of the brew. In the middle of NYC, I feel like I'm having a relaxing beachside drink. Well balanced and really well made without relying too heavily on the lobster aspect. Highly recommended!

Lots of carbonation. This is the champagne of beers. Very light in color light in body. Lots of head that quickly died. Flavor was pretty mellow not the most out spoken saision I have ever had. some spice some fruit not a lot of sweetness to the beer a lot more on the dry side.

Just finished my second can and have to say it was much better with an extra two weeks age on it to me. The slightly overwhelming green onion flavor in the two week old can faded greatly to a very pleasant bitter dankness. On a different note, I would never have gotten guava flavor unless I was told that it was used in the brewing process.

On tap @ Corner Pub in Reedsburg, served in a tapered pilsner glass. Review from notes. Thin cap of tan foam, with a sticky ring of lacing at it's edges. Reddish amber body, with slow trails of carbonation visible. Nutty, woody aroma, with clean malt notes showing through. It retains its Scotch Ale base without letting the bourbon dominate. Maple, light oak, peat smoke, vaguely grassy/herbal, dry bitterness and a nutty/woody note in the end. Warming hint of alcohol also in the aftertaste. Sweetness, not a clear bourbon taste, but more oak, and mild old char. It's dry with mellow carbonation that foams up a bit with each sip. Nice to try, it's fairly mellow as far as barrel aged beers go (oak chips maybe?). One was enough, probably wouldn't drink more.

Another superior Tree House offering. A little less fruity and a little more hoppy at the end than Julius or Alter Ego. Has that cloudy honey-orange color that announces that unfiltered goodness is on the way. Fantastic nose - mango, citrus, touch of pine. Taste says tangerine and pine to me with some softer fruits. Strong hops bitterness follows. Mouth feel - nice carbonation, then soft flow over the tongue, finishes with a lingering bitterness. Fruit flavors emerge more as beer warms a bit. Nice, appropriate carbonation. Bottom line - another world class beer. For me, among the citrus-style DIPAs and IPAs, Tree House is the absolute king of the mountain. Now if they could only move closer to Virginia....

A: Pours a hazy (wait a minute....just got the name!) dark golden color with a one finger fluffy cream colored head. S: Citrus, pine, mango and passionfruit with a soft malt backbone. Smells pretty amazing. T: Super smooth and just a great mix of citrus and pine. Some tangerine, mango and just a touch of honey malt. Really, really really love this one. Might be my favorite I've had from Tree House so far.

Can into tulip. 2/10/16 all in my brain. L. Light orange/dark yellow. 2 finger head of tight bubble with thick lacing. S. I get a good amount of sweet candied fruit in the onset, which segues into some nice pine notes with tropical fruits mixed in as well. Touch of alcohol on the back end. T. A good amount of haze and pine, more so than on the nose. Some nice sweetness on the finish. F. Nice medium mouthfeel and great carbonation.
Clear golden beer with thin off0white head, low retention. Smell - candy, floral, Taste - dry, rather bitter, herbal, astringent. Medium body, soft carbonation, tad strict and austere for the style.

Bottled and bottle conditioned rich amber bodied and good frothing foamy white head some citrus on the aroma the flavour reminds me of a fruity flavoured chewing gum of the juicy variety it didn't seem to be as solid as the abv would suggest but bearing in mind I picked this off a supermarket shelf, it would compete with a lot of stuff I paid more than twice for in speciality bottle shops

A: Dark gold body with a dissipating head. S: Not a lot going on here. T: Not as good as I was expecting, considering how much I love Proper Job. Nice and earthy, and despite being packed with 'as many Citra and Centennial hops as we could get our hands on' it doesn't taste particularly American, or overly hoppy. Has only a subtle amount of hoppy perfumeyness, but lots of lovely satisfying earthiness. For 7.2% though I'm wanting more. It is deliciously dry, but I think it could benefit from a bit of sweetening malt. That would really bring out the bouquet. O: Dissapointing based on my expectations, but a good beer regardless.

Half litre bottle, poured into pint shaker. A: Golden, looked like continental apple juice, very clear, small thin head which disappeared fairly quickly, not much lacing. S: Citrus fruits and Cascade hop, wasn’t the most pronounced aroma I’ve ever smelled from a beer. T: A bit of a grapefruit bomb, hints of wheat, decent amount of bitterness, hid the booze well. M: Crisp, decent amount of carbonation, went down well. O: SNPA on steroids, nicely done, not overly in your face but interesting.
Massively hopped (as it says) strong American APA. Worth trying.
Pours a light golden colour, almost like a farmhouse ale. Strange lemon and yeast on nose. Bitter palate but again an odd yeast flavour. Perhaps an off bottle.

650 mL bottle poured into a snifter. Appearance - Deep brown body. Medium khaki head. Thin collar. Smell - Lightly fruity, but a lot of caramel. Kinda buttery. Oak and vanilla. Taste - Lots of oak and vanilla. Dominates the flavor. Caramel. Lots of brown sugar. Oaky and bourbony finish. Mouthfeel - Medium heavy. Low carbonation. Boozy. Overall - Simple, but nice.

Just another day at Jackie-O's.. Pours dark with nice amount of bubbles. Smells of bourbon, figs, raisins, slight vanilla and caramel. Wonderful and of the wall in terms of taste. Bourbon in the front, dark fruits and spices through the middle with a nice vanilla/caramel finish. Head was nowhere to be seen after a few sips, but luscious from front to back. Super tasty, super interesting take on a style. Seems to be the calling card here at Jackie O's. Glad their home is in Ohio. We're lucky to have 'em.
Pale gold-yellow, no head, excepting some small bubbles rising from the bottom. Smell is apple, and little clove. Taste is similar, plus a touch of stale mint, and some barnyard funk.

Bottle gifted to me by the brewer and shared with family at an Afghan restaurant (because where else, right?) Looks dark-brown, cocoa coloured, small head with beige-coloured foam. Leave some decent lace. Not bad looking for the size. Smells tropical and fruity. Lots of pineapple with coconut and lots of dark fruit too. Currants, sultanas and cherry skins. Yeah, oak sweetness, cherry and sorbet. Pleasant, boozey overtones. Taste is more vinous. Notes of red wine, with coffee roast, then gets coconut on mid palate, sweetness on the back with big booze notes to finish. Blended well with flavours and not too hot, just rich, and maybe slightly oxidised. Dark fruits with raisins, prune and a touch of pepper. Big beer as expected, well reined in with a lovely touch of oak to add sweetness and an extra dimension. Bit sharp towards the back, but otherwise decent body for the style. Flat, which is good. I like a good eisbock, and this is a good eisbock.

Tried from a bottle blind from @LaitueGonflable to accompany an Afghani dinner. Pours a deep, volatile, boozy brown with lots of hazing in the body. It's quite fluid and liquid in the glass, but with a sense that it's big. Only minor head on it: it settles out very quickly. Lots of phenolics and esters coming through on the nose. I got banana, weizeny spices and serious booze which gives of raisins, rum-soaked dates, and banana leaf. There's a slight sulphur character as well which isn't all that welcome, but otherwise it's pretty impressive. Taste is thin and hot, with a withering ripeness and strength to the booze. Lots of dark fruit characters coming through but always pitted against that boozy sharpness which pierces and eviscerates it. Some stewed raspberry on the back along with a darkness that's almost inseparable from the booze. Finish is long, boozy and extremely sharp. It's intense stuff. Feel is sharp, hot and boozy. It almost hurts. There is impressive weight and heft of alcohol to this, and it plays with it well enough. The sharpness precludes it from being anything else but a sipper, but when you do sip and savour this it has stacks to show off.
Had on draft at breweries. Varied A LOT depending on temperature. Started out super hoppy, not at all fruity. Mellowed nicely as it warmed; became smooth and yummy after about a half hour.
Java Jack is being brewed again as this is the third rating in February. A very pleasant stout. Oatmeal smooth with coffee smell. Could have again.

Served in a shaker pint glass at the brewpub. Entertaining time watching this beer get poured... Anyway, it pours a solid black-brown topped by a finger-and-a-half of dark-leaning sandstone foam. Lovely. The nose comprises lots o' coffee, light roasted malts, light toasted oats, and light chocolate. The taste is pretty much more of the same: It's all kinda like the ancillary flavors (the roast, the oats, and the chocolate) blend together to collectively compliment the coffee at different times. Trust me on this one, it all works pretty well. The body is a seemingly floating medium, with a rather light carbonation and a ridiculously smooth feel. Overall, a very tasty coffee oatmeal stout that really embraces the cask-conditioning very well. Possibly the best thing I've yet had from this brewpub.

Exclusive on tap at the brewpub Pours jet black with a tan thin head. Smells of roasted coffee and chocolate. Flavor is of roasted coffee, wood, cocoa and a weird earthy sooty element. Thin body with minimal carbonation. This beer is pretty meh, the taste is weird and the body is pretty disappointing. Wouldn't have this again.

0% Had on draft at the new Portland location. The bartender seemed knowledgable of the beer and stated that this was a single batch offering. A: Unfiltered hazy Orange color similar to wet hay. Had loads of lacing from top to bottom. S: Citrus bomb on the nose. Strong hops and a little sweetness. Slight malt but almost unnoticable. T: As indicated in the nose... Lots of citrus and grapefruit with a dry finish. M: Medium body with the carbonation providing alot of small prickly bubbles which detracts a little from the experience in my opinion. O: A very tasty IPA the I would defiantly try again. As stated in previous reviews it is very reminiscent of the Frys Leap with a little additional fresh hop flavor.

Served in a tulip shared with my wife golden amber with a nice head to start. The aroma is wonderful fruity citrus smooth with hints of malt. The taste matches the aroma starts fruity with citrus then carbonation comes in and dissipates to becomes dry with a hint of malt and slight bitter. Very nice This is like a more fruity fresh Fyes Leap
Amazing beer! Had this on tap during Founders' Cellar raid 2016. Wish they would bottle the stuff but I doubt that will happen anytime soon.

Had [email protected] Capitol Beer and Taproom in Sacramento, CA. Keg dated 12/2014. Appearance - Served up in an 8oz tulip with a thin layer of cocoa-colored head. The brew itself is black with cola brown edging. Lacing is mostly spotty with a few broken webs. Smell - Chocolate and maple syrup. Lesser coffee roast. Underlying bourbon aroma. Taste - Follows the nose. Chocolate and syrupy sweetness, adding up to a bit of a Hershey's chocolate syrup character. Lesser coffee roast comes through soon after, along with moderate molasses and maple flavors. Bourbon notes creep in near the end, adding notes of vanilla and oak. The aftertaste rings with a mild sweetness. Mouthfeel - Full in body with low to moderate carbonation. Thick, sticky texture with a warm, drying finish. Overall - This one definitely lives up to the hype. The thickness is a huge plus; many BBA stouts suffer from thinning out too much during the aging process, but this one holds true to a genuine impy body. Definitely one my favorite BBA brews I've had, and I look forward to trying it again when the opportunity arises.
Absolutely the best hands down
had this on tap a few months ago. it was great, sweet but very tasty. overall good beer

Amazingly had this 3 times during SF Beer week. Looks fine, dark with small head. Aroma is wonderful, sweetness of maple comes through with coffee and chocolate. Taste is incredible, slightly sweet, coffee, chocolate, some barrel, and maple is subtle (at this point). Its delicious. One of my favorite stouts.

Had three 12oz pours of this at Birch Hill Tavern in Glastonbury, CT. This was one of my top 10 wants, and I got 3 huge pours of it. ALL maple on the tongue, but was hoping for more of a balance to everything. Would definitely seek this one out again though!

9 oz pour on tap. Drank a little colder than ideal temp but who could wait? Nice black color with very small tan head Smell is very sweet like candy and vanilla not as much coffee as BS or KBS Taste is outstanding. The maple syrup and bourbon blend perfectly. There's not a ton of complexity but the handful of flavors that come through are perfectly balanced. Tastes like donuts or chocolate covered caramels. Very sweet from the syrup but not overly sweet at all. Hands down one of the best beers I have tried. Believe any and all hype

This lived up to the hype for me. A pitch black pour with almost no head. Smells wintery... like sticky sweet maple. Chocolate and of course oak and bourbon. Taste is much the same and does not disappoint. A little thinner than I was expecting but not thin by any means. I want more...

Bottle 170/341 out of the '12 batch. A: Pours a very dark red with some brown in there. Big fluffy and effervescent light brown head. Minor spots of lacing but not much. Quite decent head retention, however. S: Decent bourbon but nothing overpowering. A nice caramel and dark fruit medley, mainly with grape, raisin and fig. Touch of brown sugar. Nice. T: Again, decent bourbon up front but it's not huge. Really nice sweet caramel and toffee notes with vanilla I'd say. Mixes in with the sweet dark fruits quite nicely. Again, mainly raisin and fig but definitely some grape and maybe even cherry? Just a hint. Vanilla, brown sugar and caramel make everything very sweet well into the middle. Sweetness fades just a bit in the finish, giving it more of a dried fruit flavor with some oak and some earthy belgian yeast character. A bit of drying oak and yeast linger between sips with hints of pure bourbon. No noticeable booze at all, very smooth. M: Relatively low carbonation, nice medium/heavy body. Smooth. O: This is really an awesome quad. The barrel aging isn't overpowering like some Jackie-O's beers (or barrel-aged beers in general if I'm honest), it just adds some mild but noticeable character to the beer. Mainly contributes a very nice coating caramel and vanilla sweetness to everything and gives another aspect of flavor to enjoy.

258/341, 2012 A - Pours a deep brown/amber with a decent tan head. It's a bit darker and a bit less cloudy than I expect from this style, but still nice. S - Nice big chocolately dark fruits, vanilla, bourbon, warming alcohol. Holy balls this smells incredible. T - What's nice about this is that all of the elements in the nose are in play on the tongue, but in a different balance. This is really heavy on the dark fruits (plums, cherries especially), but the rest of these things come out to varying degrees. It's pretty sweet M - big and smooth, nice. O - kinda boozy, pretty sure this one is over the advertised 9.4...not sure if it would exceed Ohio's limits. But it's a good beer. By far, the best part is the nose, but it's good all-around.

Received as an extra in a trade. Canned 8/23/18. A - Poured into my Duvel tulip a nice hazy milkshake pale straw hue with a thin one finger head that fades slowly to leave sudsy wisps. S - Aromas of dank earthy hops, citrus peel, orange jam. Light sweetness, some green grassy hops. Flashes of vegative onions though thanks to the Mosaic. T - Taste is similar to the nose, quite dank, loads of sweeter citrus peel. Like an orange marmalade. Flashes of strawberry too, maybe some light dank overripe pineapple. Tons of oats as well. Finish is slightly strawberry sweet. Flashes of onion vegative notes but thankfully the sweet jammy citrus drowns it out. M - Mouthfeel is nicely carbonated, creamy, the oats definitely are noticeable. O - Overall this was a solid New England IPA, or milkshake IPA, whatever you want to call it. The mosaic clashes a little bit with the citra (with the vegetative onion notes), however, there are enough positive qualities to offset that. Very solid hoppy beer. Serving Type: Can

Pours a stupidly gorgeous golden-orange color with a great looking fluffy one plus finger head. Great lacing. Aroma is a bouquet of tropical fruits mixed with just a kiss of dankness and pine. Lots of peach and melon with fresh orange Zest sprinkled in. Taste is soft and creamy with a kick of hip bite at the end of the sip. Definitely tropical and with lots of citrus. More of an east coast beer with some remnants of the classic west coast. Overall, wren House is killing the IPA game in AZ. In my opinion this is there best yet. Perhaps the beer is a bit undercarbonated. I see this pairing well with almost anything, including more delicate items like fish. It gets a 94.5/100.
Flagship beer and the best they have.

Pour is two fingers of fine, white head settling quickly into one finger, with not much lacing. Dark golden colour and slightly cloudy. Initially, aroma is very promising. Strong pine, slightly citrus full and pungent. Initial taste is softer than expected. The pungent hoppy aroma doesn't translate to the taste or mouthfeel, and it's all quite smooth and subtle. Not as BIG a flavour as I would have expected. Overall, a very drinkable beer, and hard to believe it's ABV as it's so easy to drink, although not as BIG a flavour as I expected from the nose.

Shared it, and got thing I did because it's just strong. It pours with a clear and golden color and a decent and not really thick white head. The aroma is extremelly pleasant. Sweet and fruity thanks to the citra hops (on of the best aromas out there). The taste is completely different, especially after such a smell. It's bitter, hoppy, bitter and hoppy. A very strong taste with a bit too much bitterness for me. The aftertaste is also very bitter and I can still feel it. A good beer, but not really for me.

16oz can poured into a tulip on the same day it was canned, 2/10/16 Look: Hazy and orange, but a bit darker than other Tree House brews I've had. Almost looks like a non-alcoholic apple cider. Poured a half-finger of white head that quickly fell into almost nothing. Sparse lacing. Smell: Peach and apricot off the bat. Definitely get some tangerine, guava, and mango too. Noticeable pine too; not as much as Green but more than Julius. Probably the best balance of fruit and pine characters of the TH beers I've had. Dankness really cuts through as it warms. Taste: Just as balanced as the nose. Pine and citrus working in almost perfect tandem. Extraordinarily bitter aftertaste. Not unpleasant, but noteworthy, in my opinion. The fruit really comes to the forefront as it sits out and warms up a bit. Feel: Fairly high carbonation that dances and explodes in your mouth. Medium to thick mouthfeel that foams and froths, coating the mouth. The finish is clean and a little alcoholic. Overall: Another top-tier beer from Tree House, surprise surprise. It seems that these guys and gals can do no wrong. Not my favorite offering thusfar, but honestly it really becomes a splitting of hairs when you're dealing with beer of this caliber. By no means would I decline the opportunity to purchase this in future visits.
Had this for the first time. It won't be the last. Got better as I got to the bottom of the can. Great feel on the mouth. You could really taste the hoppy juiciness of the this beer.

A slight tilt of spice over fruit, of earth over cleanliness, of dryness over sweet; it's the aura of white wine that nudges Against the Grain's farmhouse ale into the proper fields of saison. Coq de la Marche pours with a soft golden glow, lightly hazed and crowned with an arid creamy froth. Bright with white grape, citrus, pear and melon, the beer soon counters with a tingle of peppery spice and vinous white wine. Malty-sweet with pilsneresque charm, the taste is bready, confection-like and with a kiss of honey. Swaying from the floral upstart of honeysuckle, the ale soon relies on the balance of spice over fruit to sell the show. Drying apple, orange, lemon and pear begin to trail off just as the winey spice shares a tangy acidity that brights white pepper, clove, coriander and vanilla to the foreground. Moderately biter, a taste of grapefruit and grassiness rounds out the middle palate ahead of a semi-dry finish. Medium-bodied for saison, the beer's creaminess overshadows the traditional racy carbonation and the beer's softness takes command over earthy dryness. Sharp, spicy and grassy, the beer trends more saison-like than of Belgian-style pale ale with the aid of wine acidity and light oak nuttiness.

Big, bubbly white head with good retention and patchy lacing. Nice, pale straw gold color, slightly hazy. Flavor has lemon zest, yeast, and some very moderate mustiness and funk. Tastes pretty good with the mustiness adding abit of the complexity needed to make a Saison interesting. Mouthfeel is crisp and tart and refreshing. Overall a fairly good Saison.

Poured into a tulip. A very beautiful hazy almost copper color with a very full dense head with decent retention and left good lacing. The aroma was of light citrus and an earthiness that I can only assume to be the yeast, but a very pleasant aroma. The taste was citrus with some slight peppery notes particularly on the back end. It had a wonderful mouthfeel and the level of carbonation was very lively and pleasant. Very drinkable.

16 ounce can into tulip glass; no can dating, but is a recent release. Pours slightly hazy golden yellow color with a 2 finger fairly dense and fluffy white head with good retention, that reduces to a small cap that lingers. Spotty soapy lacing clings on the glass, with a moderate amount of streaming carbonation retaining the cap. Aromas of big lemon, orange zest, pear, apple, white grape, apricot, melon, peppercorn, light banana, wheat, spelt, biscuit, herbal, floral, grass, and yeast earthiness. Very nice aromas with good balance and complexity of fruity/spicy yeast, citrus/earthy hops, and bready malt notes; with great strength. Taste of big lemon, orange zest, pear, apple, white grape, apricot, melon, peppercorn, light banana, wheat, spelt, biscuit, herbal, floral, grass, and yeast earthiness. Moderate yeast spiciness and herbal bitterness on the finish; with lingering notes of lemon, orange, pear, apple, white grape, apricot, melon, peppercorn, wheat, spelt, biscuit, and herbal/yeast earthiness on the finish for a good bit. Damn nice complexity, robustness, and balance of fruity/spicy yeast, citrus/earthy hops, and bready malt flavors; with a great malt/bitter/spiciness balance, and zero cloying flavors after the finish. Moderate dryness from bitter/spiciness; lightly increasing through the glass. Medium carbonation and body; with a very smooth, fairly crisp, and lightly creamy/grainy/sticky balanced mouthfeel that is great. Minimal warming alcohol as expected of 5.8%. Overall this is a very nice saison. All around nice complexity, robustness, and balance of fruity/spicy yeast, citrus/earthy hops, and bready malt flavors; very smooth, crisp, and easy to drink. A very enjoyable offering.

Black with a mocha head. Smells pretty good, mostly briny with a standard porter underneath. Taste is less briny and the porter & chocolate come out more, dark chocolate, some roasted malts, earthy, finish is briny with a very slight hint of seafood/lobster. Pretty full body for only 5.6% ABV. Over all a nicely done porter with a nice salty/briny quality. Very happy I was able to try, would buy it again given the chance.

Interesting take on a porter. Had in a flight. Did not get any lobster at all on the nose. Looked like a typical stout but was a porter. Smelled of coco and roasted dark fruit. Taste is full bodied for a porter and a great beer at only 5%. The lobster kicked in in the finish and lingered with a buttery note. For what it is it's perfect. Too much and it would overpower but they got the flavor they were going for. Would have gone good with a nice seafood dish or white coco dessert.

Man this beer just wasn't for me. Looked typical of a standard stout; very dark brown/black; tan head; minimal carbonation. The smell was a mixture of brine and vomit, while the taste matched the smell though to a less potent extent. Overall the lobster-taste vastly overbalanced the standard stout-ness I was expecting. This one is more interesting in theory than in practice…I'd probably try again on account of how idiosyncratic it is but this is the first DFH experiment that just didn't do it for me.

10 ounce goblet - $9.00 at World of Beer in Kennesaw, Georgia. Appearance: Served up a very dark brown, near black body with an inch of dark khaki foam. Smell: Roasted malts, coarse baker's chocolate and briny lobster drippings. A touch of underlying dark fruitiness, a hint of spicy basil. Taste: Roasty, scantly ashen malts backed by a bitter chocolate quality and relatively light sweetness. Touch of prune. A salty, savory, fishy quality is certainly detectable from the precious lobsters who gave their all for this beer. Roastiness sustained on the shellfinish. Mouthfeel: Medium-bodied. Medium carbonation. Overall: I'd feared for a bizarre and unpleasant creation, but it was alright (at least for ten ounces worth).
I have no idea how, but this was definitely drinkable. The salty and sweetness played well together

Though I had to give up more than I would have liked in a trade for this, I was not disappointed upon opening it. Last Snow has always been one of my favorites, so the thought of trying that but essentially barrel aged, excited me. Despite my desire for more bourbon, the coconutty goodness that tickled my tastebuds made it permissible that it wasn't as profound. Not too much heat but not overly sweet either. If you can attain one of these, it is worth it.

Melted almond joy. That's the best way you can describe this beer. I love coconut and this beer delivers it in the best way. Makes DBC seems like sun tan lotion. Nose is huge coconut and coffe with vanilla and some bourbon. Taste is straight coconut and chocolate. Just outstanding. Finish leaves vanilla and dark chocolate coconutty goodness. Weirdly it doesn't come off overly sweet like it's going to break your teeth (ala Black Tuesday) just perfectly sweet with all of that toasted coconut. If you get a chance to try this do not hesitate.

The pour is sultry yellow with a big head of white foam that dwindles. The color has a little golden edge to it. A stream of bubbles, soft haze. Fruity with melon husks sweet grasses and light lemon. It's fragrant with a soft flower petal and the nutty perfume from the spelt malt is like the musk on this citrusy fruity beer. Sharp little bit of pepper. Drinks softly and very elegant. The malt sinks into a bit of crackery softness with a touch more flavor than you were expecting. the citrus becomes prominent in the drink but it's heady with dry lemon. Sweet grasses and alight touch of sugar finish this one dry and with a subtle cheek from bitterness. It's put together very well and has the perfect bubble. You don't notice any bite and the malt is very lush to the palate. I think there is a little dry funk on this beer too but I can't prove it. This is a lovely, malty saison with a bit of nutty flavor from the spelt malt and a vivacious late hop addition gives it presence on the nose. What I like about this style of beer is that it has a hearty character. The fruit is not easy to name and has a quality that sometimes I think you can only define by a color. Cool green like melon, mixed with a peppery herbal , lemon, a touch of tartness - its' all compliments and that's balanced. The bittering hop is strong and could take you to the aspirin like bitterness in a DIPA like heady topper, but in this one it's softer than that. It does have a sharpness. This is not a big IPA with lots of slick feeling to the body so a crisp sharp bitterness accents dryness. It lingers but not longer than the faintly nutty malt and with the light lemon in the aftertaste. Your palate is not all the way reset because of the spelt and the sugar. You want to pair this beer with aged or soft cheeses and a variety of artisan breads and sandwich boards, smoked turkey with melted cheddar and apples.

16 oz can w/o freshness info Pours lighter, near clear amber, ligting an initially huge off white cap, quickly going to a tin splattered film and leaving just a few splotches of lace.. Cilantro, lemon and grassyness are what I get here on the nose and on the palate...meh..not the greatest saison out there...lacking in style, taste and intrigue
Aroma is earthy, Belgian yeast and light lemon/berries. The flavor is lemon/berries, Belgian yeast, malts, earthy and a slight heat/spices in the finish.

fashioned as a session saison, this is pretty good beer, sort of a session pale meets like a belgian single or light wheat beer. its not real interesting on the yeast front, clean and fruity, more belgian than farmhouse to me, a little acidic, white wine, peach, that sort of thing, but much more hop than yeast driven anyway. juicy limey zesty citrus hops, plenty of bitterness too, really stands out in such a light beer. clearish looking too for something called a saison, but its cleanness is a nice feature in hot weather, it drinks lighter than even it is, and the flavors are rather robust. i taste a little less of the wheat malt than i usually like to in a saison style, but it does have just a bit of body to it, so its contribution isnt that minimal. i love the freshness and citrus forward hop flavor, coming on real late and lingering nicely. likely mosaic and citra, or some similar combination. great carbonation and very refreshing overall. not the most out there or adventurous brew, which i really have come to expect and look forward to from these guys, but its well made and easy drinking and perfect for summer.

Drinking side by side with a king Julius, and its damn near as good!!! Very similar, just less tropical and a tad bit more hoppy. This is of course a world class DIPA, but even near the top of that group!

Deep, black pour with a finger of brown/caramel head. Not much lacing, but as expected with a barrel aged beer. On the nose, the maple syrup is the star, so strong. Hints of chocolate, coffee, and bourbon. On taste, the bourbon hits you first, boozy and delicious. Just like KBS, you get that coffee, chocolate, and barrel. The mouthfeel is full with a medium-low carbonation, very nice. So glad I finally found this on tap!

Had this on tap at Cellar Raid 2016. L: dark brown/black, minimal head S: sweet maple syrup, caramel, coffee T: maple syrup/brown sugar, coffee, bourbon F: on the heavier side, lightly carbonated, & incredibly smooth This is one of the best beers I've ever had. Actually lived up to the hype.

On tap at Ale Arsenal for SFBW. Stoked, the legendary CBS here at my local beer bar. L: black/brownish. S: Lord have mercy. Smells like a delicious pancake breakfast with the finest possible ingredients. Caramel, chocolate, maple, goodness. T: follows nose. Rich maple, chocolate, dark and roasty malts, caramel, nougat, glory. F: Medium-Rich. O: worthy of hype, this is glorious

L: dark dark brown with very slight mocha head, some lacing S: sweet, sweet sugary maple syrup smell with bourbon on the back T: maple syrup, bourbon M: heavy, syrupy O: very good beer, not quite up to expectations but enjoyable for sure and I am glad I got to try it

Founders take over at Beer Revolution Oakland Darth Vader black very limited head Maple and chocolate donut great maple taste that lingers, its like a liquid bourbon spiked brownie nice mouthfeel, no heat, couldnt put this down two could never be enough, it made my SF Beer week.

Founders tap takeover at Harry's Hofbrau in Redwood City, Ca. Pitch black goodness. Creamy bubbles and elegant lacing. Maple, bourbon, dark chocolate, vanilla, molasses, slight coffee. OH MY! Picking up everything in the nose in the taste! So sweet and rich! Rich mouthfeel....it coats the mouth and makes you come back for more. This brew deserves the hype. Founders killed it with this one!
Simply put, the best beer I have ever had.

2014 bottle shared. 'brewers only' release that was graciously shared by a guy that knows a guy. A: very dark brown, definitely not black. light brown frothy head. minimal lacing unfortunately. S: a lot of bourbon on the nose. not off putting, but very present. vanilla, chocolate, smoke, dark licorice, oak. T: chocolate, this is a very sweet brew. i assume that has something to do with the maple syrup which also has a presence. coffee notes in there as well. sweet brown sugar. alcohol is moderate and there is virtually no bitterness in this. M: body is full, but not throughout. manages to start very rich and tapers to a thinner than expected finish. D: really f'ing good. dangerously drinkable. makes complete sense to why it is regarded where it is.
The Willows - SF Beer Week - draft

Draft at Resolute Day, thick and delicious, smooth flavor with a touch of coffee, bourbon and coffee blends well together, booziness has faded over time and results in a much more mellow beer. Overall, delicious!

0% On draft at Novare Res (Portland, ME) for Stout Fest. Look: Black as night; no transparency at all. Light brown head that lingers a bit. Smell: So rich. Coffee. Bourbon. Chocolate. Taste: Maple and chocolate dominate. A little surprised but the subtly of the bourbon. Feel: Fairly thick and coating but fades quickly. Really nice for the type and high abv. Overall: This is an amazing stout but not sure it [personally] lived up to the hype. That said I'd never turn it down. A fantastic dark-chocolate-maple-bourbon stout.

This one lived up to the hype. A 9oz pour at Roots Pizza in Chicago. The maple was perfectly noticeable and added just the right amount of sweetness. The taste seemed to improve as the beer warmed. KBS is amazing, but this one blows it out of the water.

Look - Black with a moderate light tan head. Smell - Coffee, bourbon, surprisingly light on the maple taste, nice strong roasted cocoa taste. Taste - Maple up front, with some coffee and chocolate. Slight amount of bourbon, which blends with a little caramel to create a nice sweet overall taste that contrasts the cocoa and coffee. Feel - Medium body, hardly carbonated at all. Smooth and creamy. Overall - While it doesn't live up to the hype of a "perfect 5" this is still a damn good beer, and a creative one at that.
The lobster was basically non-existant.

Dark straw with a fading snowy head that leaves the odd trailer. Big juicy citrus nose with some MO doughiness underneath. Biscuit with bossy pink grapefruit, lychee, goosberry and light resin hops jumping right in. Lime curd ending and minty linger. Light, crisp, slight chew, no burn, a bit of oil. Nugget, Centennial, Cascade and Citra. BBD 25.Jul.2014, so coming up near the end of 3 months freshness. It's certainly got the hopping right - there are all sorts of angles to this combo, with Centennial and Citra representing the most - making it very refreshing, especially with no heat. But i's pale and thin for the strength (by Brit standards, anyway) and the bitterness is a bit powdery which is not quite a flaw, but not on point either. And it's in no way - IBUs, aroma, ABV - a DIPA. Solid, above average American IPA but given the brewery, I expected more somehow.

Pours clear golden-yellow with a finger of off-white cap that sets at medium pace. Nose is lychee, citrusy and spicy hops, banana esters reminiscent of Hefeweizen (a brief look at the back-label confirms the assumption that wheat-malt has been used in this one) and there's only subdued malt aroma. Flavor is lemony with very restrained pale malt character. There's a pleasant lasting retronasal oflaction provided by hops. No harshness nor oaky flavors as it should be and absolutely no signs of being 7%. Light with creamy texture (wheat) and substantial carbonation. Doesn't seem very much like an Imperial one but flawlessly crafted nonetheless. (A presumably fresh bottle without BB indication, into tulip.)

Deep mahogany pour with a small color of bubbles for a head. Aroma of dark fruits and bready yeast, boozy heat right from the get-go. Taste of caramel malts and dark fruits, grain alcohol, pumpernickel, and a pretty big oak quality. Not as smooth as I like my BB beers to be, but this is a style I don't often have in a barrel-aged form. Body was medium, smooth, hot, but not too hot, appropriate carbonation. Pretty good overall.

22 oz bottle. Thanks to Geist, Steve or Thorpe or someone. Pours a dark mahogany with a thin tan head. Pleasant aroma of vanilla, dark fruit, booze, oak and cherry. Barrel forward flavor, vanilla and caramel with light oak blends seamlessly with a robust malty quad. Medium thick with fine carbonation. Easy drinking for the style.

Thanks to oline73 for gifting me this bottle. Very gracious. Shared with Thorpe and Humbard. The beer is dark brown with a thin, wispy head that fades rapidly, leaving little lace. The aroma offers brown bread, Belgian yeast, oak, bourbon. Nice flavor. Well balanced. A bit of heat in the finish. Lingering caramel malt and brown bread with bourbon barrel character. Tasty beer.

I had this on-tap at the anniversary party. Served in a tasting glass. Appearance: The beer pours a mahogany color with some red at the edge when the light comes through. There is almost no head. Smell: Quite sweet with some raisins and caramel. There is also some heat from the bourbon that hits the nose. Taste: Super sweet with lots of dark fruit and some cherries. I'm getting caramel along with the bourbon. The finish is also quite sweet. Mouthfeel: The body is a bit on the syrupy side with foamy carbonation and a dry finish. Overall: This is a very sweet beer, but I enjoyed it. Fairly smooth. A nice beer to have for dessert. I'd have more.

I am sampling a cellar temp 16 oz can poured into a snifter. The beer pours a deep cola brown color with a short lived fizzy tan head of 1 cm foaming up. The foam is gone about 30 seconds after the can empties. The aroma is a nice mix of malts, some roasted malt, some milk chocolate, and a good dose of brown sugar. The first sip reveals a silky smooth textured beer with fine soft carbonation. I get a bit of sweet coating across my palate with each sip. The flavor is roasted malt, some sweet chocolate, and a bit of brown sugar again. The beer doesnt reveal any hops and the booze is incredibly well hidden throughout the finish of the beer. This is an easy drinking sweet and smooth stout with no hits of booze and no hops to note either. No flaws on a straightforward sweet stout.

L - Dark brown. Opaque. Thin off-white head. Not particularly persistent. S - Sweet dark malt. Chocolate and prune. Brown sugar. T - Not as rich as I expected. Quite sweet. Dark fruit and a little tart citrus. Chocolate is in the background.

Pours with weak head but nice dark reddish brown cola color. Smells like musty, rummy, and fruity, but was surprised by tartness. I was expecting something similar to Smutty's "Really Old Brown Dog". Love the sour! Reminds me of apples or sour cherries....? The rum takes a back seat to the sour after a while and I still enjoy it.

Got this one from dboon in a recent swap. Thanks for the FL brews man! From a bomber into a snifter Imperial porter aged in Bourbon barrels with coconut, coffee and natural flavors added Imperial version of Last Snow APPEARANCE: Pours thicker, opaque, dark brown/black and yields a cascading 2+ finger, medium looking, slightly creamy tan head with good retention. Black body with no carbonation evident. Head slowly fades to a thick, creamy cap. Slight wisp remains til the end leaving touches of lacing down the glass. SMELL: Big nose of bourbon barrel on the pour. Sweet vanilla cream, coconut, milk chocolate, oak notes and bourbon on the nose. A hint of sweet, creamy coffee in there under the barrel and vanilla aromas as well. Bold sweet vanilla, coconut and barrel. Smells great. TASTE: Sweet vanilla cream, milk chocolate, oak and bourbon up front. Flavorful for sure. A whiff of coconut at the swallow moving into a bold and persistent aftertaste of oak, bourbon, vanilla, coconut, milk chocolate and a hint of bitter coffee in there too. A touch of booze but not much. Lots of sweet flavor with a solid barrel character and a hint of coffee still. Well balanced and interesting. Really good. PALATE: Medium – full body and lower levels of carbonation. Creamy enough on the palate, enough weight for sure, goes down smooth with a bit of a scratch and finishes mouth-coating. A touch of heat lingers. OVERALL: This is great. A wonderful imperial porter and the barrel definitely compliments the coconut additions really nicely. The coffee could be a little stronger perhaps, but that might also be the result of age. Regardless, it’s decadent the way it is right now. Lots of wonderful aroma and flavor with a strong, full feel to support it all. As good as Last Snow is, in this case, bigger is better really does ring true. Definitely jump on this one if you get the chance. Thanks again for the beers dboon. Highly recommended.
Coconut magic.

Poured into a Dogfish traditional oversized snifter. Bottleneck says Bottled On 09/08/15. A- Pours a 99% opaque black color with a 1/4 inch light brown head that retains a bit before becoming a thick ring around the edge of the glass and a half sheet of sheer surface foam. Resilient lacing leaves a solid ring behind. S- An intense wave of coconut, bourbon and coffee washes through my nasal cavity sending signals of immense pleasure to my cerebral cortex. T- The sheer intensity of deliciousness that's brought on by this already magnificent beer treated with lovely bourbon complexity is near-crippling. Very sweet with the coconut blending with the vanilla notes from the barrel, then the coffee provides its balancing roast on the back end. Coconut is definitely the main player after multiple sips are taken and that's the main lingering flavor. There's also chocolate, caramel and cake batter coming along for the ride. M- Silky smooth, luscious, decadent. Also a bit syrupy. Medium-low carbonation and a full body. O- My first perfect 5. Nothing about this beer can be improved. If I could drink this every day for the rest of my life, I don't think I would ever get sick of it. Beautiful...just beautiful.

L- very dark brown, bordering as black. Nice brown head. S- subtle roast with a kick of brine. T- following along with smell. Plenty of cocoa up front that dominates the beginning. But as you swallow, lobster brine starts attacking. F- lobster (pleasantly) lingers. Did I just drink a beer or eat a po boy? Carb is quite pleasant as well O- glad I got to try what is a World of Beer exclusive. Definitely one of a kind. One wouldn't think lobster and chocolate would go well together, but Dogfish Head pulled it off wonderfully.

Drank from a 1 pint can purchased at Tree House Brewing Company, Monson, MA 01 27 16 Served in a snifter A finger tall, frothy white crown topped the opaque, orangey-amber liquid. Although the beer is called "Haze," the body on this could clearly be categorized as "cloudy." In fact, it looked very much like orange juice. The head quickly fell to a barely there film. Drippy streaks of lacing trickled down the glass. The aroma was really hoppy and bright. Tropical fruits came through strong right off the bat. Loads of passionfruit. Good amount of mango. Peach notes were apparent as well. Lots of zesty orange and orange peel. Juicy and fruity. As the beer sat, the orange notes took over. Later, the peach really came forth. The flavor profile was solid but more pithy and simple than the nose. Intense citrus notes. Orange peel dominated. Really juicy and fresh. Just a touch bitter. Peach notes also came through strong. Bit of mango. White grapefruit appeared in the finish. Fairly rind-like and moderately bitter. Some pithiness lingered after the swallow. On the palate, the beer was medium bodied. Perhaps a bit thinner than anticipated. The liquid contained a very fine, mellow effervesce that tuned the beer creamy and frothy on the palate. This almost felt a bit under carbonated. Haze is a really solid, citrus-forward double IPA, but it is far from Tree House's most impressive hoppy offering. By most accounts, this would be an amazing shelf beer, but by Tree House standards it was a bit disappointing.
Another fantastic IPA from Tree House. I would put this citrus juiciness above Alter Ego, but below Green and Julius. Still, it's just one more reason that Tree House is killing it right now.
Solid IPA and I like that it was put in pounders which is a good thing in my opinion. Clear golden color and nice hops kick.
Nice beer. Not great but certainly a beer I would buy again and serve to friends.

Sun King Lupulin Astronaut. 16 oz canned 12/18/16 6.5% ABV with mosaic, chinook & mandarina. Purchased 2/8/17 at the Fishers taproom. Poured into Sun King Rastal craftmaster one glass. Pours a golden color with shortlived white head. There are some floaties, but I would not call this beer hazy by any means. Smells like tropical fruit and citrus rind. Taste is more of the same with orange, and herbal dankness coming first then fading to bitterness at the end. Carbonation is high and feel is a bit thin to make this a world class contender. Overall, a good, drinkable APA that has just falls short of the standard bearing APAs available in the Midwest.

Had the IPA at a event I. Bargersville IN. 16oz. Can very strong hops presence. Would like to taste a bit more of a citrus balance such as grapefruit or blood orange. Other than that a fairly balanced IPA . Good new offering from Sun King.

A - Bright, clear yellow body with thin head and white lacing. S - Resin and pith, zest and a bit of wild hop notes. T - Strong hop notes of grapefruit and pine, mango, with powerful follow-through of pith. Malt counterpoints with a candied aspect. M - Crisp, with a clean finish that makes for a solid brew. The O - Sun King has often reached punishing when powerful would be better suited to the task. This one does not, avoiding aspirin or taxing bitterness and delivering a delicious, full IPA.

Labeled as The Hoppy Homunculus. Served in a tulip at the Scarborough brewpub. The color is hazy orange with a half-inch head. Lots of sticky lacing left behind. The aroma is full of citrus with just a hint of malt sweetness. The taste starts out with nice grainy sweetness followed by grapefruit rind. The finish is smooth and bitter The body is medium and the mouthfeel is smooth and creamy. Great stuff but the flavor procile doesn't seem radically different from Frye's Leap.

A: Pours a pitch black color with 2 fingers of head that slowly fades down to a decent cap S: Roasted malt, coffee, chocolate, bourbon, maple, oak, and vanilla all come rushing forward T: Follows the nose. Starts off with the roasted malt and coffee notes and then goes into the chocolate, maple, bourbon, and oak. Vanilla sweetness comes after. Finishes with lingering roasted malt, chocolate, bourbon and vanilla M: Full bodied with moderate carbonation O: An amazingly complex and balanced stout that brings forward the best of both the base and the barrel portions of the beer. Great to sip on in any occasion. Definitely a must-try brew

A- Black in the glass, one finger tan head that leaves nice lacing. S-Maple, oak, mild bourbon, some chocolate and light coffee. T-Great maple sweetness. It meshes amazingly with the oak and bourbon. Chocolate and nice coffee. Some roasted malt as well. M-Heavy and creamy. O-An amazing beer. Anything founders ages in maple bourbon barrels that aren't CBS is a waste.

Simply put, this was the best beer I have ever drank in my entire life. My best friend was kind enough to share half of his growler of this with me over this past Christmas. The beer.... which I may never even go into detail, is built of pure bliss. Black. Big. Malty. Rich. Sweet. Maple. Bourbon. Chocolate. Heavenly. Luscious. Vanilla. Just pure amazing. If you're lucky enough to have a chance to get your hands on this beer, even just once in your life, you had better do it.

Three pours on draft at Founders of CBS '17 and also from bottle on a separate occasion. Very similar to CBS when I had it 2 years ago. The word that continues to come to mind is 'balance'. Definitely picking up chocolate, maple, coffee and the bourbon, but none of the ingredients are overpowering the other. This beer definitely gets better if you let it warm closer to room temperature. If you're looking for a maple bomb, this isn't it. It's not a barrel aged stout with maple added. It's a stout aged in bourbon barrels that previously housed maple, so it is much more subtle. Thoroughly enjoy this beer. ------------------------- Four pours on draft at Founders Brewery on 12/29/2015. A perfect stout. If you ever get a chance to acquire it or have it on draft, do not pass on opportunity. Dark black color, with a light layer of foam head upon pour. The nose reminds of Breakfast Stout base but with more complexity with the maple coming through. Taste is delicious and pleasant on the palate with, again, Breakfast Stout base being obvious but the maple sweetness note unmistakably coming through as it warms. Shockingly smooth! There is zero hint of booziness. Just delicious with all the ingredients I look for in a stout, coffee, vanilla, chocolate, maple sweetness. Phenomenal.

Pours a black tar shadow. Tiny small bubble forms on the rim, no foamy head. The bubbles are a mocha brown and dissipate quickly. Aroma is intense maple/chocolate/coffee in that order. The maple smells so strong, makes for a sweet tooth boner. reminds me initially of Good Morning, but this smells richer and thicker. Plenty to love about this smell, I'm ready for a sugar bomb! Delicious, awesome bourbon vanilla balance. Now the coffee comes through and its beautiful.. Every flavor incorporated in the making of this beer is felt in even the smallest sip. There are no layers of different flavors here, everything is a pure mix and compliments itself. huge maple,coffee,rich chocolates, and bourbon sweetness to die for. Some will probably knock the (I'm not going to call it thin because it's not) mouthfeel, because we all probably crave the molasses/chewy BCBS style. But this beer is so damn easy to drink, make sure to take your time and let it warm up. Definitely an amazing beer, so awesomely crafted and balanced, very rich - just a pleasure to finally get my hands on a white whale like this. Was at first sad to trade away one of my favorite beers to obtain it, but in the end it was worth the price.
By far my favorite beer I'm a huge sucker for maple syrup stouts though. It surpassed the hype for me! Had it on tap btw

The darkest of brown, combined with black that makes a solid full 3/4" of tan head on it. Impressive as they come for barrel aged appearance. Aroma was decadent, coffee, maple, bourbon, chocolate, oak. The maple sweetness, heavy roasted malt, bitterness, chocolate, wood, and coffee in a lesser way, all really make for an insanely drinkable brew. Mild tobacco notes counter balance. An excellent breakfast beer.

While the first time I rated this was at a Founders event at The Brew Kettle, this full, updated review is based upon the December 2017 release, fresh and on draft. I'm actually struck by how smooth, rich, deep and velvetty thick this is, with a soft but faint carbonation that concludes semi-dry and sticky. On top of that much improved body over KBS, it's also a bit sweeter, and the maple is more pronounced than the previous version I had, but it's not outstanding. Whiskey is still present, with a Jack Daniels-like sting, and there's not a lot of roastiness, but more of that tangy cola and bourbon heat. Maybe there's some chocolate fighting through, but there's no coffee at all, which is sad. Smell is more whiskey forward than the palate, but is otherwise fairly identical. CBS actually gets hotter as it warms, which is a detracting attribute from my standpoint.
Heaven

Had it at dogfish head brew pub in rehoboth. Pours a black opaque color. I do not taste the lobster, however, I had it with a crab cake sandwich and it paired nicely. I did taste a lot of raw cocoa powder especially in the finish. An interesting brew. The low abv makes it rather light and drinkable.

* UPDATE: not really sure why Last Buffalo was combined with Snowed In. The ratings and review I have is for Snowed In. I didn't like Last Buffalo. Amazing nose, a huge coconut punch, but taste didn't follow. Flavors were artificial, very little barrel presence, light coffee in a medium porter body. * Possibly the best coconut nose I've ever sniffed from a bottle. Wow, straight up Almond Joy candy bar smell. Mouthfeel and flavors though were short of spectacular, the type I expected from Prop '13 given how much attention this beer has gotten. It's thin, almost no barrel to speak of in the flavor, coconut was very prominent, but felt flat, similar to Perrin No Rules.

On tap at 3/2/2013 release event. Notes from taplist: "Traditional saison exhibiting bright fruit notes with subtle spice." Light amber color. Smells spicy, some lavender type flowers, darker malt backbone though so it's not as bright as Le Git for example. Taste is malty with a rye like spicy malt backbone, mild flavors overall, slightly tangy. Decent body but could use a little more carbonation. Less good than the other new Jackie O's saisons but still pretty solid. 6.5/10

Appearance: THe cloudy goldstraw colored liquid builds as the bubble show recedes but the resultant head is well over two fingers thick; great retention and gobs of splashy lace Smell: Stone fruit (peach, nectarine and apricot) mirrored by orange and tangerine citrus tones Taste: Peach tones emerge first, on the taste buds, but the citrus shows more power, with orange creamsicle, tangy passion fruit and papaya flavors underneath; after the swallow, a dank bitterness builds but the malt stays in the background Mouthfeel: Medium to full body with moderate carbonation Overall: Another fine example of how to brew with hops from Tree House Thanks, EveningCordial, for the chance to revisit

650ml bottle, another one of those offerings that you only come across with you deign to visit the less discerning bottleshops around town, and have a heady sense of cognitive dissonance about the business practices of one Minhas Brewing, et al. This beer pours a rather solid black hole of colour, with very subtle basal cola edges, and three fingers of puffy, rocky, and foamy brown head, which leaves but a few instances of cannonball splash lace in places around the glass as things lazily and sloppily recede. It smells of more bitter than sweet cocoa powder, the sort that's been sitting on a discount store shelf for who the hell knows how long, gritty pale malt, a weak caramel sweetness, a bit of wan black licorice and earthy root-like character, and slightly sour cream. The taste is still quite chocolaty in that weak-ass dime-store manner - flaky and filmy, if ya get my poor student days drift - sour pale and still understated caramel malt, wayward sugary notes of the American military industrial complex ilk, a bland anise spiciness, increasingly off-seeming milky notes, and a twinge of unhinged booziness. The carbonation is quite light and ineffective at making me care about this usually frothy metric right now, the body a so-so middleweight, and plainly smooth, I suppose, with the cocoa at least providing a bit of further utility. It finishes just a tad off-dry, the same near-sickly chocolate taking us home in the same manner as it done brung us to this particular soiree. Sort of average all around, which for the brewery in question here, is way above their normal pedigree, I gotta say.
